Comment.create(id: '81', tool_id: '32', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong><em>List XML Elements (XML)</em></strong> is a free, web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It is easy to use, designed to <strong>search</strong> elements and attributes within an XML document, either hosted at a web address or uploaded from the user\'s files.</p> <p>Users may set <strong>list options</strong> via criteria such as unique element names, element tree structure, attributes or elements containing elements. The tool&rsquo;s processing is slowed somewhat as text size increases, but within acceptable limits and without impacting its utility. The output formats for this tool include <strong>XML Tree</strong> and<strong> tab delimited</strong>.</p> <p>This tool has only a few <strong>problems</strong>. When the tab delimited output is selected, the tool may not process some characters correctly; please see List Words (Plain Text) for examples. In addition, when the output is set to XML Tree, this tool frequently produces an XML parsing error.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these issue, List XML Elements (XML) is an effective way to see the elements, attributes or structure of an XML document.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:04:19', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:04:19', )
Comment.create(id: '82', tool_id: '66', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Aggregator (Other)</strong> is a free, simple to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It is designed to <strong>aggregate</strong> text from multiple web addresses, either manually copied into the tool, or from a list stored in a file on the user&rsquo;s local computer.</p> <p>The text from a given web address will appear in the same order as the list of sources. Users may also include a document from their local computer in the aggregate. The tool has two <strong>options for handling markup</strong>: strip any XML or HTML tags from the texts, or smart strip tags to form an XML corpus. The latter option transforms non-XML texts into comments. The output formats available for this tool are <strong>HTML</strong>, <strong>XML Text in HTML</strong>, <strong>XML Tree</strong> and<strong> Plain Text</strong>.</p> <p>This tool has only a few <strong>problems</strong>. When the plain text output is selected, the tool may not process some characters correctly; please see List Words (Plain Text) for examples. In addition, when the output is set to XML Tree, this tool frequently produces an XML parsing error.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these issue, Aggregator (Other) is an effective way to aggregate several web documents.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:21:05', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:21:05', )
Comment.create(id: '83', tool_id: '68', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Raining Words (Other)</strong> is a free, easy to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It generates a <strong>list of high-frequency words</strong> from an HTML document at a user-specified web address, and <strong>visualizes</strong> them in a <strong>Java applet</strong> that sizes and assigns a movement speed to words based on that frequency.</p> <p>To display the applet, users must have Java 1.4.2_8 or later installed for their browser. In order to have the applet display in a separate tab or browser window, users must also tell their browser&rsquo;s pop-up blocker to permit popups from the TAPoR website. The tool can handle novel-length texts, though the tool&rsquo;s processing will slow proportional to the size of the text.</p> <p>There are a few <strong>options</strong> available for this tool. Users may limit subtext to only that text appearing within specific HTML elements, and either include all words, or limit based on a user-specified list, Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong>, or a user-specified pattern. Searching a <strong>pattern</strong> rather than a word requires skill with <strong>regular expressions</strong> and is thus not accessible to all users. Once the applet has loaded, the user may manipulate the speed and direction of the text by gesturing with their mouse cursor.</p> <p>This tool has only a few minor <strong>problems</strong>. The Java applet is sensitive to the volume of other traffic on the user&rsquo;s network and its processing may be slowed or it may fail to load when traffic is heavy. If it fails to load, refreshing the page or resubmitting the tool will generally resolve the issue. In addition, this tool&rsquo;s input is limited to documents hosted at a web address, and it cannot process XML or plain text.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitations, Raining Words (Other) is an interesting, interactive alternative to a word cloud for visualizing high frequency words in an HTML document.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:22:02', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:22:02', )
Comment.create(id: '84', tool_id: '72', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Weighted Centroid (Other)</strong> is a free, easy to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It generates a circular <strong>visualization</strong> of <strong>high frequency words</strong> from an HTML, XML or plain text document at a user-specified web address or from a local file, and <strong>visualizes</strong> them in a <strong>Java applet</strong> that places them in a circle relative to their frequency and distribution within the source document.</p> <p>To display the applet, users must have Java 1.4.2_8 or later installed for their browser. In order to have the applet display in a separate tab or browser window, users must also tell their browser&rsquo;s pop-up blocker to permit popups from the TAPoR website. The tool can handle novel-length texts, though the tool&rsquo;s processing will slow proportional to the size of the text.</p> <p>There are a few <strong>options</strong> available for this tool. Users may break the text into <strong>paragraphs</strong>, according to its <strong>percentage</strong> of the larger text or into chunks of a specific number of words. They may also limit words to those not on the Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong>, choose how many of the top words to include in the visualization, and specify words in addition to those top words to include.</p> <p>Once the applet has loaded, users can click on or hover the mouse cursor over words to see their associations. HTML table and tab delimited text output is also available for users seeking an alternate means of representing the data.</p> <p>This tool has a few <strong>problems</strong>. The Java applet is sensitive to the volume of other traffic on the user&rsquo;s network and its processing may be slowed or it may fail to load when traffic is heavy. If it fails to load, refreshing the page or resubmitting the tool will generally resolve the issue. When the tool generates its list of top words, punctuation is often identified as a word and quotation marks appended to adjacent words. When the tab delimited output is selected, the tool may not process some characters correctly; please see List Words (Plain Text) for examples.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitations, Weighted Centroid (Other) is a rich, interactive means of visualizing word relationships and distributions.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:28:54', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:28:54', )
Comment.create(id: '85', tool_id: '73', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong><em>List Pairs (Beta)</em></strong> is a free, web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It is easy to use, designed <strong>generate lists</strong> of all <strong>words pairs</strong> in a user-specified document, either hosted at a web address or uploaded from the user\'s files.</p> <p>Users may specify a number of <strong>restrictions</strong> to limit the list. The options include ignoring all punctuation, treating sentences as a single text unit for the purposes of the search, specifying at least one word matching a user-provided pattern, including at least one word from a user-specified list, and exclude words according to either the Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong> or a user-specified list. Searching a <strong>pattern</strong> rather than a word requires skill with <strong>regular expressions</strong> and is thus not accessible to all users.</p> <p>The tool&rsquo;s <strong>results may be sorted</strong> according to frequency, order of appearance or in reverse alphabetical order. Display options currently include <strong>HTML</strong>, <strong>XML text in HTML</strong>, <strong>XML tree</strong> or <strong>tab delimited</strong>.</p> <p>This tool currently has some <strong>problems</strong>. Its processing is slowed significantly as text size approaches novel length. In addition, while it will accept HTML and XML documents, it strips all tagging and processes it as if it were plain text.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitations, List Pairs (Beta) is an effective way to view all pairs in a document.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-11-09 17:05:24', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:29:17', )
Comment.create(id: '86', tool_id: '74', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong><em>Principle Components Analysis (Beta)</em></strong> is a free, web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It is easy to use, designed <strong>generate relationships</strong> between words and text units in a user-specified plain text document, either hosted at a web address or uploaded from the user\'s files. The relationships are <strong>visualized</strong> in a <strong>Java applet</strong> that places words on an interactive <strong>scatter plot</strong>.</p> <p>To display the applet, users must have Java 1.4.2_8 or later installed for their browser. In order to have the applet display in a separate tab or browser window, users must also tell their browser&rsquo;s pop-up blocker to permit popups from the TAPoR website. The tool can handle novel-length texts, though the tool&rsquo;s processing will slow proportional to the size of the text. A number of <strong>options</strong> are available for interacting with the graph, including zoom, rotate, pan and changing the view axis.</p> <p>Users may specify a number of <strong>restrictions</strong> to limit the list. The subtext options allow one to break the text into paragraphs, by percentage or into chunks by number of words. The words themselves may be limited by the number of the highest frequency words to appear, and by whether or not to exclude words according to either the Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong> or a user-specified list.</p> <p>In addition to the Java applet, the tool&rsquo;s <strong>results</strong> can be displayed as an HTML table or as tab delimited text. The tool gives best results for documents over 500 words and a number of text units below 100.</p> <p>This tool currently has a few minor <strong>problems</strong>. When identifying words, it tends to include punctuation such as quotation marks, and opening quotes are appended to the word they appear adjacent to. The Java applet is sensitive to the volume of other traffic on the user&rsquo;s network and its processing may be slowed or it may fail to load when traffic is heavy. If it fails to load, refreshing the page or resubmitting the tool will generally resolve the issue. In addition, while it will accept HTML and XML documents, it strips all tagging and processes it as if it were plain text.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitations, Principal Components Analysis (Beta) is an interesting, interactive way to view the distribution of the top words in a document.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:30:33', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:30:33', )
Comment.create(id: '87', tool_id: '75', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Word Cloud (Beta)</strong> is a free, easy to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It generates a <strong>list of high-frequency words</strong> from plain text document at a user-specified web address or from the user\'s files, and <strong>visualizes</strong> them in a <strong>Java-enhanced web page </strong>that sizes words based on that frequency.</p> <p>There are a few <strong>options</strong> available for this tool. Users may limit the number of top words appearing in the cloud and choose whether or not to apply the Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong>. Once the page has loaded, the user can view the number of times a word appears in the text by hovering their cursor over that word, or click on the word to view a <strong>concordance</strong> for it.</p> <p>The <strong>results</strong> may be displayed by appearance, frequency or alphabetically, and users can enable or disable a fixed layout on the results page.</p> <p>This tool has only a few <strong>problems</strong>. When identifying words, it tends to include punctuation such as quotation marks. The size scaling of the least frequent to most frequent words in the cloud is not sufficiently diverse to allow for the clear distinction between words when the cloud is generated from 50 or less of the top words. In addition, while it will accept HTML and XML documents, it strips all tagging and processes it as if it were plain text.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitation, Word Cloud (Beta) is an effectively enriched variation on the standard a word cloud for visualizing high frequency words in a document.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:32:30', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:32:30', )
Comment.create(id: '88', tool_id: '82', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Keywords Finder (Beta)</strong> is a free, simple to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It generates a <strong>list of keywords</strong> from a plain text, HTML or XML document at a user-specified web address or from the user\'s files, and displays them in an HTML page.</p> <p>This tool is basic, with only one <strong>option</strong> to affect the <strong>results</strong>: an <strong>inflectional stemmer</strong>. The results page offers a list of key words and phrases, the 20 top frequency words, 10 top frequency word pairs and 10 top frequency word triplets. Users can click on the most frequent words, pairs or triplets to view a <strong>concordance</strong> for them.</p> <p>The tool has a few <strong>problems</strong>. While it will accept HTML and XML documents, it strips all tagging and processes it as if it were plain text. It is also slow to process, becoming more and more sluggish as text size increases and when the inflectional stemmer is applied. Though it can handle novel-length texts, the strain on the server often results in an error, requiring the user to resubmit the tool. In addition, the tool has no option to open the results in another window or tab, requiring the use of the back button to try another text or tool.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitation, Keywords Finder (Beta) is an effectively way to quickly identify key words or phrases within a text and generate a concordance from them.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:33:28', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:33:28', )
Comment.create(id: '89', tool_id: '83', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Compare with Control (Beta)</strong> is a free, easy to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It compares a text to a control text and generates a <strong>list of words by frequency </strong>with <strong>statistical information</strong> from a plain text document at a user-specified web address or from the user\'s files.</p> <p>This tool offers a few <strong>options</strong>. Users may compare their text with the provided <strong>Brown corpus</strong> or provide a corpus from their files, and choose to include all words or exclude those words on the Glasgow <strong>stop list</strong>.</p> <p>The <strong>results</strong> can be sorted either by frequency, or by ratio over the control corpus, and be displayed as HTML or a tab delimited list. The information provided in the results includes counts, relative frequencies and relative distributions. This tool can handle novel-length texts, though the tool\'s processing slows as the text size increases.</p> <p>The tool has a few <strong>problems</strong>. While it will accept HTML and XML documents, it strips all tagging and processes it as if it were plain text. The tab delimited list option has a poor alignment of headers to columns, impacting the clarity of the data. In addition, users are unable to provide their own stop word list.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitation, Compare with Control (Beta) is an effectively way to quickly generate statistics showing the difference between a given text and a control corpus.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:33:41', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:33:41', )
Comment.create(id: '90', tool_id: '84', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Web Page Cleaner (Beta)</strong> is a free, simple to use web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It processes an HTML document at a user-specified web address or from the user\'s files and removes all HTML tagging.</p> <p>This tool is basic, offering only two <strong>options</strong>: users may either <strong>strip tags</strong> from their document, or <strong>convert it to plain text</strong>.</p> <p>The tool has a few <strong>problems</strong>. It replaces some punctuation, other non-alphabetical and accented alphabetical characters with Unicode equivalents. When the strip tag option is selected, the tool also runs previously-tagged text together, which can result in issues if no space was included before or after a tagged chunk. &nbsp;</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these limitation, Web Page Cleaner (Beta) is an effectively way to quickly convert an HTML document to untagged text or plain text.</em></strong></p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 00:50:28', created_at: '2012-02-28 00:50:28', )
Comment.create(id: '91', tool_id: '61', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong><em>Comparator (Plain Text)</em></strong> is a free, web-based tool designed to run in a browser window. It is easy to use, designed to <strong>compare</strong> the text of two documents, either hosted at a web address or uploaded from the user\'s files.</p> <p>Users may set the comparison criteria. <strong>Options</strong> include all words, words matching a pattern, words in or excluded from a user-specified list, or excluded from the Glasgow <strong>stop word list</strong>. The second text can be plain text, HTML or XML; the tool will treat HTML and XML documents as plain text. Searching a <strong>pattern</strong> rather than a word requires skill with <strong>regular expressions</strong> and is thus not accessible to all users.</p> <p>Other features include <strong>options</strong> to sort by the first text&rsquo;s word count or ratio of relative word count, and to display as <strong>HTML </strong>or a <strong>tab delimited</strong> text. The HTML output gives several <strong>tables of information</strong> about the texts, including basic information about the texts, a word comparison, words in the first text, and words in the second. Any of the words in the word comparison table may be clicked to produce a <strong>concordance</strong> for that word.</p> <p>This tool has a few <strong>problems</strong>. When the tab delimited output is selected, the tool may not process some characters correctly; please see List Words (Plain Text) for examples. In addition, punctuation like open quotes and long dashes are often appended to the adjacent word, skewing the counts and comparison.</p> <p><strong><em>Despite these issues, Comparator (Plain Text) is an effective way to make a comparative analysis of two texts.</em></strong> Versions are also available for HTML and XML documents.</p>', updated_at: '2012-02-28 02:56:12', created_at: '2012-02-28 02:56:12', )
