Comment.create(id: '1214', tool_id: '199', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>TACT is generally recognized as a historically important text analysis tool within the Digital Humanities. Although no longer in wide use, it is known to have been used as a teaching tool in undergraduate literature courses into the mid-1990s. More information about the tool and its use can be found in the following articles:</p> <p>Armstrong, Gudya. \"Computer-Assisted Literary Analysis Using the TACT Text-Retrieval Program.\" <em>Computers &amp; Texts</em> 11.8 (1996). <a href=\"http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ctitext2/publish/comtxt/ct11/armstron.html\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Hawthorne, Mark. \"The Computer in Literary Analysis: Using <em>TACT</em> with Students.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 28.1 (1994): 19-27. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200307\">Web</a>.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>More information about TACT as a text analysis tool is available via the official guides. The former is maintained by the Modern Language Association as a free PDF:</p> <p>Lancashire, Ian, John Bradley, Willard McCarty, Michael Stairs and T. R. Wooldridge. <em>Using TACT With Electronic Texts: A Guide to Text-Analysis Computing Tools: Version 2.1 for MS-DOS and PC DOS</em>. New York: Modern Language Association of America, 1996. <a href=\"http://www.mla.org/store/CID7/PID236\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>McCarty, Willard. \"Text Analysis Computing Tools: a brief guide.\" <em>Centre for Computing in the Humanities</em>. 1993.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Information on ARRAS\' relationship to TACT is available in:</p> <p>Centre for Computing in the Humanities. <em>Tools for Humanists, 1989: Software &amp; Hardware: Fair Guide</em>. Toronto: Centre for Computing in the Humanities, University of Toronto (1989).</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:19:54', created_at: '2012-11-22 18:56:56', )
Comment.create(id: '1243', tool_id: '203', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information about GINGER II and its development and functionality may be found here:</p> <p>Dini, Luca, Vittorio di Tomaso and Frederique Segond. \"GINGER II: An Example-Driven Word Sense Disambiguator.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 34.1-2 (2000): 121-126. <a href=\"http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/16898915/ginger-ii-example-driven-word-sense-disambiguator\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:25:11', created_at: '2012-11-29 21:52:19', )
Comment.create(id: '1244', tool_id: '205', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>INTEX is a linguistic development environment promoted through workshops over the course of eight years and used by multiple projects and researchers. More information on its development and functionality may be found in the following articles:</p> <p>Silberztein, Max. \"INTEX: An Integrated FST Toolbox.\" <em>Automata Implementation: Lecture Notes in Computer Science</em> 1436 (1998): 185-197. <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3975(99)00015-8\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Silberztein, Max. \"INTEX 4.1 for Windows: A Walkthrough.\" <em>Automata Implementation: Lecture Notes in Computer Science</em> 1160 (1999): 230-243. <a href=\"http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=721539\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Silberztein, Max. \"Text Indexation with INTEX.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 33.3 (1999): 265-280. <a href=\"http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/2733448/text-indexation-intex\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:28:40', created_at: '2012-11-30 20:53:22', )
Comment.create(id: '1245', tool_id: '206', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>NETMET is a metaphor generator and interpreter designed for use in the humanities. More information on its development and functionality may be found in the following:</p> <p>Steinhart, Eric. \"NETMET: A Program for Generating and Interpreting Metaphors.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 28.6 (1995): 383-392. <a href=\"http://www.ericsteinhart.com/articles/netmetapa.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:30:25', created_at: '2012-11-30 21:23:18', )
Comment.create(id: '1246', tool_id: '207', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on Micro-EYEBALL, its applications and development is available here:</p> <p>Ross, Donald and David Hunter. \"Micro-EYEBALL: An Interactive System for Producing Stylistic Descriptions and Comparisons.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 28.1 (1994): 1-11. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200305\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>More information about the original version of EYEBALL is also available here:</p> <p>Ross Jr., Donald and Robert H. Rasche. \"EYEBALL: A Computer Program for Description of Style.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 6.4 (1972): 213-221. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204031\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:36:12', created_at: '2012-11-30 22:02:59', )
Comment.create(id: '1247', tool_id: '208', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Collate: Interactive Collation of Large Textual Traditions is a historically important tool. Additional information may be found in the following:</p> <p>Johnson, Eric. \"Technical Review: Collate: Interactive Collation of Large Textual Traditions.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 27.5-6 (1993): 401-420. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204565\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>\"Version 1.0 of Collate: A New Program for the Collation of Large Textual Traditions.\" Vicky A. Walsh, ed. <em>ACH Newsletter</em> 13.2 (1991): 6. Print.</p>', updated_at: '2014-07-21 17:52:40', created_at: '2012-11-30 23:03:55', )
Comment.create(id: '1248', tool_id: '209', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>XTRACT was a tool for lexical collocation developed in the 1980s and early 1990s. More information on its development and functionality may be found in the following:</p> <p>Smadja, Frank. \"Retrieving Collocations from Text: XTRACT.\" <em>Computational Linguistics</em> 19.1 (1993): 143-177. <a href=\"http://acl.ldc.upenn.edu/J/J93/J93-1007.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Smadja, Frank. \"XTRACT: An Overview.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.5-6 (1992): 399-413. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204633\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:54:50', created_at: '2012-11-30 23:39:44', )
Comment.create(id: '1249', tool_id: '210', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Concorder / Le Concordeur was available as early as 1992. More information is available on the Macintosh build in the following:</p> <p>Corre, Alan D. \"Technical Review: Concorder: Concordance Software for the Macintosh.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.5-6 (1992): 463-464. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204637\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Rand, David W. and Tatiana Patera. <em>Concorder: Concordance Software for the Macintosh, User\'s Manual: Version 1.1</em>. Montreal: Publications CRM, Universite de Montreal (1991). <a href=\"http://books.google.ca/books/about/Concorder_Concordance_Software_for_the_M.html?id=kpnNygAACAAJ&amp;redir_esc=y\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:52:44', created_at: '2012-12-06 20:07:20', )
Comment.create(id: '1250', tool_id: '211', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>PC-Kimmo is a microprocessor implementation of the original KIMMO morphological parser. More information on its development and functionality may be found in the following:</p> <p>Antworth, Evan L. \"Glossing Text with the PC-KIMMO Morphological Parser.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>&nbsp;26.5-6 (1992): 389-398. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204457\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Hinkelman, Elizabeth and Mark Olsen. \"Technical Reviews: PC-Kimmo: A Computational Linguistic Tool for Humanities Applications.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.2 (1992): 157-168. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204632\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-27 17:52:12', created_at: '2012-12-06 20:36:58', )
