Comment.create(id: '1259', tool_id: '212', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>URICA! II and its predecessor URICA! were historically important collation programs developed in the 1980s and early 1990s. More information on their development and functionality may be found in the following:</p> <p>Cannon, Robert L. and Oakman, Robert L. \"Interactive Collation on a Microcomputer: The URICA! Approach.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.6 (1989): 469-472. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200178\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Hilton, Michael L. \"The URICA! II Collation System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.2 (1992): 139-144. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204452\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:44:45', created_at: '2012-12-06 21:32:02', )
Comment.create(id: '1260', tool_id: '213', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>VINCI is an environment used to simulate language based on linguistic theory. More information on its development and functionality may be found here:</p> <p>Levison, Michael and Gregory Lessard. \"A System for Natural Language Sentence Generation.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.1 (1992): 43-58. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204437\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:43:42', created_at: '2012-12-06 22:30:16', )
Comment.create(id: '1261', tool_id: '214', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Micro-OCP was an implementation of the original Oxford Concordance Program, available since 1981. More information on its development and utility may be found here:</p> <p>Jones, Randall L. \"Software Review: Micro-OCP.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.2 (1989): 131-135. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200151\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>More information about the Oxford Concordance Program as originally released may be found here:</p> <p>O\'Brien, Frank. \"Software Reviews: Oxford Concordance Program.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 20.2 (1986): 138-141. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200056\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-03-13 17:45:50', created_at: '2012-12-06 23:20:33', )
