Comment.create(id: '1264', tool_id: '216', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the development and applications of WordCruncher may be found here:</p> <p>Olsen, Mark. \"Software Review: Textbase for Humanities Applications: WordCruncher.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 21.4 (1987): 255-260. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30207396\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:56:56', created_at: '2012-12-07 03:36:23', )
Comment.create(id: '1265', tool_id: '217', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the early development and applications of the Donne Variorum Textual Collation Program may be found here:</p> <p>Stringer, Gary A. and William R. Vilberg. \"The Donne Variorum Textual Collation Program.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 21.2 (1987): 83-89. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200075\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 20:57:39', created_at: '2012-12-07 16:59:44', )
Comment.create(id: '1266', tool_id: '218', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the applications of CLOC may be found here:</p> <p>Burnard, L.D. \"Software Review: CLOC.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 14.4 (1980): 259-260. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02404435\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:17:55', created_at: '2012-12-12 18:59:18', )
Comment.create(id: '1267', tool_id: '219', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the applications of WORDS may be found here:</p> <p>Cary, Charles D. \"Software Review: A User\'s View of WORDS.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 13.2 (1979): 129-30. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02404509\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Iker, Howard P. and Robert H. Klein. \"WORDS: A Computer System for the Analysis of Content.\" <em>Behavior Research Methods &amp; Instrumentation</em> 6.4 (1974): 430-438. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.3758%2FBF03200396\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:15:14', created_at: '2012-12-12 19:40:32', )
Comment.create(id: '1268', tool_id: '220', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the design and applications of KLIC may be found here:</p> <p>Logan, Harry M. \"KLIC: A Computer Aid to Graphological Analysis.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 12.1-2 (1978): 93-96. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199940\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:13:21', created_at: '2012-12-12 20:22:14', )
Comment.create(id: '1269', tool_id: '221', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information on the development and applications of LEXICO may be found here:</p> <p>Venezky, Richard L, Nathan Relles and Lynne Price. \"LEXICO: A System for Lexicographic Processing.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 11.3 (1977): 127-137. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199877\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:11:51', created_at: '2012-12-12 20:50:09', )
Comment.create(id: '1270', tool_id: '222', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information about the applications of COCOA is available here:</p> <p>Corcoran, Paul E. \"COCOA: A FORTRAN Program for Concordance and Word-count Processing of Natural Language Texts.\" <em>Behavior Research Methods &amp; Instrumentation</em> 6.6 (1974): 566. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.3758%2FBF03201351\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Day, Colin and Ian Marriott. \"Software Reviews: COCOA: A Word Count and Concordance Generator.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.1 (1976): 56. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02399143\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Russell, D. B. \"COCOA - A Word Count and Concordance Generator.\" <em>Associates Technology Literature Applications Society</em> (1965). <a href=\"http://www.chilton-computing.org.uk/acl/applications/cocoa/p001.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:10:07', created_at: '2012-12-12 21:43:45', )
Comment.create(id: '1271', tool_id: '223', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information about the development and application of SELECT, and its affiliation with WORDS, is available here:</p> <p>Iker, Howard P. \"SELECT: A Computer Program to Identify Associationally Rich Words for Content Analysis. I. Statistical Results.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. 8.5-6 (1974): 313-319. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199711\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Iker, Howard P. \"SELECT: A Computer Program to Identify Associationally Rich Words for Content Analysis. II. Substantive Results.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. 9.1 (1975): 3-12. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199732\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-06-18 21:03:40', created_at: '2012-12-13 21:25:28', )
Comment.create(id: '1272', tool_id: '224', user_id: '17', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overview and Setup</span></p> <p class=\"Standard\">Meandre is a <strong>graphical programing language</strong> built on top of the <strong>Seasr</strong> infrastructure designed to facilitate the creations of processes that the creators describe as flows. A flow is a<strong> pipeline</strong> of modules that accepts some kind of data as input, processes this data through a series of defined steps, and produces some form of output. Running Meandre requires a webserver but is otherwise easy to setup. Simply run the supplied sh scripts to activate both the Seasr infrastructure and the Meandre workbench. The Modules need to be added manually. Directions to do so are available on the Meandre website.</p> <p class=\"Standard\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Features</span></p> <p class=\"Standard\">Each step in the process comes in the form of a Meandre module. Each module represents some transformation of the original data. For example, one flow might as follows: input data, remove all capital letters, remove words in a stoplist, input into a word cloud, display word cloud. In this case, an arbitrary text is used as input and the output is a word cloud. Meandre is packaged with a default set of modules for several popular and powerful text analysis tools such as zotero and mallet, but also more primitive tools such as a date filter and a module that changes named locations into longitude and latitude pairs.</p> <p class=\"Standard\">Meandre works on top of the Seasr infrastructure. Each Meandre flow can be activated and is automatically uploaded to the Seasr server that it is running on. Once active, any user can access this flow by accessing the server it is running on allowing them to input their own data into the flow.</p> <p class=\"Standard\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Conclusion</span></p> <p class=\"Standard\">Meandre is best described as a <strong>platform for creating text analysis tools</strong>. Likewise, it is a visual programing language in the purest sense. Just like any other programing language there is a learning curve involved with using Meandre that some users might find challenging. However, Meandre offers its users the ability to create custom workflows and tie together other tools in a very systematic way.</p>', updated_at: '2012-12-18 02:26:07', created_at: '2012-12-18 02:18:04', )
Comment.create(id: '1273', tool_id: '90', user_id: '17', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overview and Setup</span></p> <p>Monk is an open source <strong>digital environment</strong> based around the Seasr analytics engine. Users can log into the Monk servers, access the Monk database, and pass select passages through a variety of Seasr flows. Monk is a web-based project and is accessible through any web browser via their website. Funding for the project ended in 2009 resulting in the programing behind sunset at the same time. No current work is being done on the project.</p> <p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Features</span></p> <p>The Monk project was primarily interested in<strong> creating a functional working environment</strong>. Likewise, Monk offers the user a streamlined process through which they can select text from the Monk corpus, select a tool or flow to operate on the chosen text, then save the results to their own personal profile for later viewing. Unfortunately, Monk does not give the user the option to upload their own text as the project experimented with <strong>building the texts into the platform itself</strong>. The user can choose between several different toolsets to apply to the chosen text as well as the ability to edit and save preferred toolsets. Unfortunately, many of these features are little more than a proof-of-concept and other more up to date tools easily outperform them. As well, many of the implemented features have not been updated to work with the latest versions of certain browsers, and the server no longer supports an important set of analysis tools.</p> <p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Conclusion</span></p> <p>For researchers interested in learning more about the development of tools themselves, Monk is a valuable asset as it represents and <strong>important experiment in interface and environment</strong>. Monk has inspired several other tools who have taken up and further explored the ideas that Monk created. Researchers interested in Monk should explore it as a working prototype, a living example of the thoughts and ideas that went into its creation. However, it probably won&rsquo;t find much use for the actual analysis of texts.</p>', updated_at: '2014-02-18 19:37:18', created_at: '2013-01-08 22:40:11', )
Comment.create(id: '1274', tool_id: '93', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>WordHoard</strong> is a <strong>free Java application</strong>, utilizing Northwestern University\'s Java Web Start plugin, for the <strong>study of large texts or transcribed speech</strong>. It enables the <strong>annotation</strong> or <strong>tagging</strong> of a text by applying morphological, lexical, prosodic and narrotological criteria, and can be applied either to the corpora built into the tool or to a user-provided text. Its functions also include concordance, word frequency, lemmatization and text comparison. It is designed to run on Windows, Mac OS X and Linux/UNIX systems alike, and includes an auto-update feature to ensure all users are running the most current version without the need for users to monitor for updates. Though it utilizes web content, the application runs from a cache stored on one\'s hard drive.</p> <p>On launch, WordHoard prompts users to choose from one of two WordHoard sites, each containing a different <strong>base corpus</strong>. The first, the Main Public Site, contains Early Greek Epics and the works of Shakespeare, Spenser and Chaucer and is open to all users. The second, the Early Modern English Drama Site, contains approximately 320 Early Modern English plays (including Shakespeare\'s plays), but is only available to institutions subscribing to the Text Creation Partnership (TCP). For users interested in these corpora, WordHoard offers rich <strong>metadata</strong> for each text in keeping with their canonical status, and this metadata can be leveraged in various ways by the tool to enhance users\' investigation of them. This metadata notably includes narratological and prosodic information, and metrical parsing of the Early Greek epics.</p> <p>WordHoard is <strong>easy to use</strong>, with well-labelled menus and options for investigating a text. This is well-supplemented by a clear, comprehensive <strong>user guide</strong>. The guide is indexed by topic and easily accessible from the main page, including install, troubleshooting and how to use each of its features. Of interest to advanced users, it also details such features as the application\'s built-in shortcuts and how to adjust WordHoard\'s look and feel to better suit UNIX users. <strong>Custom queries</strong> can also be saved for later use. New users can expect to begin meaningful analysis of a text within minutes of downloading the tool if they use the provided corpora.</p> <p>Using WordHoard with <strong>custom corpora</strong> may be <strong>challenging</strong> for some users. Users aiming to add their own texts will need to familiarize themselves with the application\'s directory structure and its raw data files before proceeding. Texts must be in <strong>XML format</strong> with UTF-8 encoding, and additions must be made to the application\'s raw data files in order for WordHoard to recognize and process the new corpora. <strong>Full instructions are included in the user guide.</strong></p> <p><strong>Linux/UNIX users</strong> will need to install a font suitable for displaying text in the Roman and Polytonic Greek alphabets to make the best use of the corpus provided (Windows and Mac OS X include suitable fonts already). The WordHoard development team recommends Gentium, and has provided a link for ease of access.</p> <p><strong>As a whole, WordHoard is a mature, well-designed text analysis tool, though users seeking to apply this tool to their own corpora may find it overly challenging</strong>. <strong>It is particularly recommended for users interested in Early Modern English and Greek texts.</strong> For users comfortable with the complex corpora addition process, it is also of high value to those seeking further insight into their own texts. However, users looking for a quick, easy way to delve into texts beyond the provided corpora should be advised that WordHoard may be inconveniently complex for their needs.</p>', updated_at: '2014-02-18 21:29:37', created_at: '2013-01-09 20:39:25', )
Comment.create(id: '1275', tool_id: '116', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>TextArc </strong>is a free Java applet combining <strong>visualization</strong> with elements of an <strong>index</strong>, <strong>concordance</strong> and <strong>summary</strong>. It is a <strong>simple and intuitive</strong> way to delve into a text, and <strong>includes a guide</strong> accompanied by screenshots. TextArc is unique amongst text analysis tools for the awards and recognition it has earned for the artistic merits of its text visualization.</p> <p>Though no longer under development, TextArc has been maintained online since 2002. It requires a 600 Mhz Pentium II or faster, running a minimum of Windows NT or Mac OS X, Java SE 6 or more recent, and a current web browser; as such, <strong>most modern computers will be able to run this tool with minimal difficulty though it can be slow and is processor-intensive</strong>.</p> <p><strong>TextArc offers a simple, clever way to examine a text.</strong> It takes a text, located by the user in the tool\'s provided Project Gutenberg search, and <strong>generates a circular representation in which the entirety of the text is arranged in sequence around the exterior</strong>. Each word in the text also appears in the centre of the visualization, its location determined by its frequency and at what points it shows up in the text. Other texts cannot be used with TextArc at this time.</p> <p>The most common words will appear in the centre and less common drawn toward the part of the edge it appears most frequently. Words are also brighter or darker accordingly. Hovering over a word reveals lines connecting that word to each place it appears along the arc or a looping line connecting words in the order they appear in the text. TextArc also includes concordance and association list functions. For a dynamic view of the text, users can run the Read function, which highlights each word in sequence to show where it appears in relation to other words and its distribution through the text all in one smooth animation.</p> <p>Though this tool stands up well even a decade later, <strong>texts larger than a short novel</strong>, such as the example texts <em>Alice in Wonderland</em> and <em>Hamlet</em>, will <strong>slow down the tool</strong> dramatically and can even <strong>cause it to crash</strong> on the Read function. When used on a laptop, the strain TextArc puts on the processor can cause the computer to rapidly overheat; reviewing its functions required several pauses to allow heat to dissipate. As such, <strong>TextArc is best run on a desktop computer</strong>.</p> <p><strong>TextArc is recommended as a way to gain simple insights into a text quickly and attractively without getting bogged down in statistical data from the start</strong>. It offers a means of intuitively delving into word choice and distribution particularly useful as a prelude to applying more complex or comprehensive tools to the text. It would be additionally useful as a didactic tool in the classroom, for example to show how characters and thematically loaded words come and go over the course of a work of fiction. <strong>Though minimalist in its functions, TextArc remains useful and attractive. It has earned a place as historically important tool for both its text analysis capabilities and its contributions to text visualization.</strong></p>', updated_at: '2013-01-09 23:02:03', created_at: '2013-01-09 23:01:25', )
Comment.create(id: '1276', tool_id: '102', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>SIMILE Widgets: Timeline is a free, open source tool for creating interactive timelines utilizing HTML, XML and JavaScript.</strong> SIMILE Widgets maintains a comprehensive Wiki-based <strong>user guide</strong> including numerous example timelines, and the full source code is available for download.</p> <p>Creating a timeline requires a <strong>basic knowledge of HTML and JavaScript</strong>. All timelines are <strong>created in a plain-text document</strong> rather than in an application. SIMILE Widgets recommends using a text editor suitable for coding, or an HTML editor. <strong>SIMILE Widgets provides code</strong> that can be copied and pasted to start a new timeline in the Getting Started section of their wiki, including a Document Type Definition and link to Timeline\'s JavaScript API code. The same section also provides all HTML elements and Java scripts required to populate the timeline. All tutorials for Timeline features, here and in other parts of the wiki, contain <strong>example code and detailed explanations</strong>.</p> <p>The timeline defaults to two horizontal bands, the top representing months and the bottom years, with events superimposed upon them. Users can add or remove bands as needed. <strong>Events are loaded into the timeline from a separate XML, JSON or SPARCL file.</strong> Individual events can take one of three forms, allowing users to distinguish between durations, instantaneous events with an imprecise start point, and instantaneous events with a precise start point. For timelines with many events on the same day, an hour-by-hour \'hot zone\' addition can be made, allowing finer granularity without sacrificing clarity. Users can <strong>customize</strong> most presentational details, such as the colours, icons, captions and overarching theme, including adjusting the timeline\'s CSS to add a background images, change the font characteristics and so on.</p> <p><strong>SIMILE Widgets: Timeline can easily accommodate timeline projects as large as several hundred events spanning thousands of years</strong>; the project has provided an <a href=\"http://www.simile-widgets.org/timeline/examples/religions/religions.html\">example timeline</a> of this size comparing Jewish and Christian religious history from 1AD to the present to show the tool\'s behavior and potential when handling such large datasets. Individual <strong>timelines must be embedded into a web page</strong> for viewing, with the source files hosted by the user. Control over the timeline\'s information and files remain with the user.</p> <p><strong>As a whole, SIMILE Widgets: Timeline is recommended as a versatile and scalable approach to timeline creation, though users unfamiliar with HTML, XML or JavaScript may find it challenging.</strong> However, those users willing to learn the coding required will find it well-documented and rewarding.</p>', updated_at: '2013-01-14 20:08:52', created_at: '2013-01-14 20:08:10', )
Comment.create(id: '1277', tool_id: '231', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>TACTweb 1.0 is a historically important web implementation of TACT, and some additional information about it is available on the web.</p> <p>Two implementations are available for exploration via the University of Toronto\'s CHASS TACTweb Server and may be accessed <a href=\"http://tactweb.chass.utoronto.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p> <p>Bradley, John and Geoffrey Rockwell. \"TACTweb: Argument and Evidence on the Internet.\" <em>Presented at the ACH/ALLC Conference 1995 (Santa Barbara)</em>. May 1996. <a href=\"http://staff.cch.kcl.ac.uk/~jbradley/docs/santaBarbara/tactweb.html\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Wooldridge, Russon. \"TACT et TACTweb.\" 2003. <a href=\"http://www.uottawa.ca/academic/arts/astrolabe/articles/art0039/Tact.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Wolldridge, Russon and &Eacute;milie Devriendt. \"TACT et TACTweb, logiciels de recherche de donn&eacute;es textuelles structur&eacute;es.\" <em>Maison des sciences de l&rsquo;homme et de la soci&eacute;t&eacute;, Poitiers, le 5 mai 2001</em>. <a href=\"http://homes.chass.utoronto.ca/~wulfric/articles2/poitiers2001/\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-03-07 00:26:26', created_at: '2013-01-29 18:32:33', )
Comment.create(id: '1278', tool_id: '230', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">For more information on FRANTEXT\'s powerful Stella search engine, please see the following publications.</p> <p style=\"line-height: 100%; text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Bernard, Pascale, Josette Lecomte, Jacques Dendien and Jean-Marie Pierrel. \"Computerized linguistic resources of the research laboratory ATILF for lexical and textual analysis: Frantext, TLFI, and the software Stella.\" <em>LREC 2002 Third International Conference on Language Resources and Evaluation, Las Palmas, Canary Islands, Spain</em> (29 - 31 May 2002). <a href=\"http://www.lrec-conf.org/proceedings/lrec2002/pdf/26.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p style=\"line-height: 100%; text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Brunet, &Eacute;. \"L\'Exploitation des Grands Corpus: Le Bestiare de la Litt&eacute;rature Fran&ccedil;aise.\" <em>Literary and Linguistic Computing</em> 4.2 (1989): 121-134. <a href=\"http://llc.oxfordjournals.org/content/4/2/121\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.<strong></strong></p>', updated_at: '2013-01-30 17:08:07', created_at: '2013-01-30 16:59:46', )
Comment.create(id: '1279', tool_id: '237', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>GRIPHOS was a foundational part of the Museum Computer Network, and is still discussed today. More information is available in the following resources:</p> <p>Heller, Jack, and Fullerton. Div. of Library Science. California State Univ. \"On Logical Data Organization, Card Catalogs, And The GRIPHOS Management Information System. Museum Data Bank Research Report No. 3.\" (1974): <em>ERIC</em>. Print.</p> <p>Johnston, Leslie. \"Before You Were Born...Museums had Networks.\" <em>The Signal: Digital Preservation</em>. 9 Nov. 2012. <a href=\"http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/11/before-you-were-born-museums-had-networks/\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Misunas, Marla and Richard Urban. \"A Brief History of the Museum Computer Network.\" <em>Museum Computer Network</em>. <a href=\"http://www.mcn.edu/brief-history\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Urban, Richard. \"Happy Birthday Museum Computer Network!\" <em>Musematic</em>. 9 Jul. 2007. <a href=\"http://musematic.net/2007/07/09/happy-birthday-museum-computer-network/\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Vance, David. <em>Manual for Museum Computer Network GRIPHOS Application</em>. Stony Brook, NY: Museum Computer Network, Inc., 1976. Print.</p> <p>Vance, David, and Stony Brook, NY. Museum Computer Network, Inc. \"Museum Computer Network, Inc.\" (1975): <em>ERIC</em>. Print.</p> <p>Williams, David. \"A Brief History of Museum Computerization.\" <em>Museums in a Digital Age</em>. Ed. Ross Parry. New York: Routledge, 2010. 15-21. Print.</p>', updated_at: '2014-05-29 15:52:21', created_at: '2013-02-04 18:01:38', )
Comment.create(id: '1280', tool_id: '238', user_id: '17', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overview and Setup</span></p> <p>R is a free open source programing language and statistical environment maintained by the GNU. R contains powerful libraries for parallel computing and is especially adept at computing on large data sets. The R website maintains and distributes the necessary files to install on all major operating systems. The R executable itself operates inside a command line environment; however, an optional and separate program Rstudio can provide a graphical development environment.</p> <p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Features</span></p> <p>R was not originally designed for textual analysis, and it abilities go beyond the direct needs of the average text analysis researcher. However, R&rsquo;s vector data type, its ability to work on several data sources simultaneously, and its built-in visualization tools make graphing data exceptionally easy. With some coaxing R provides an ideal environment for large-scale data processing and analysis. R provides all tools necessary for splitting and combining texts, yet prior knowledge of regular expressions is mandatory in order to get the most out of these options. The R language vector data structure scales easily between small and large data sets. R also includes one command graph generation for all common graph and data types.</p> <p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Conclusion</span></p> <p>R is a programing language, yet it does several things differently then most conventional scripting languages. R does not rely heavily on control structures, which makes it easier for someone not familiar with recursive programing to learn. Anyone with a solid understanding of flows and tokenization should be able to pick up the programing style easily. However, R is a tool far bigger then text analysis; its features may cause some confusion for the self-learning especially those not immediately familiar with statistical concepts. R is an excellent tool for large and long-term research projects as well as toying around with smaller data sets. An excellent introduction to R targeted at humanist scholars can be found in the book &lsquo;Quantitative Corpus Linguistics with R,&rsquo; by Stefan Th. Gries. (Link below) While more experience programmers might want to look at the official R tutorial on the R website.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.amazon.ca/Quantitative-Corpus-Linguistics-Practical-Introduction/dp/0415962706%20\">http://www.amazon.ca/Quantitative-Corpus-Linguistics-Practical-Introduction/dp/0415962706 </a></p> <p><a href=\"http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-intro.html\">http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-intro.html</a></p>', updated_at: '2013-06-07 20:30:33', created_at: '2013-02-22 01:31:03', )
