Comment.create(id: '1332', tool_id: '232', user_id: '45', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Flemm v3.1 provides inflected and POS tagged forms with their corresponding uninflected lemma, as well as the description of their inflectional features, within the Multext format.</p> <p>Fiammetta Namer : https://sites.google.com/site/fiammettanamer/</p>', updated_at: '2013-08-29 15:47:15', created_at: '2013-08-29 15:18:26', )
Comment.create(id: '1333', tool_id: '235', user_id: '45', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>D&eacute;riF is not a lemmatizer, but a rule-based morphosemantic analyser for French, i.e. it provides both derived and compounds words with their complete morphological analysis. D&eacute;riF\'s input must be a POS tagged lemma X. D&eacute;riF\'s output is a morphological description of X, including :</p> <ul> <li>its set of ancestors (= its \'direct\' morphological family)</li> </ul> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">ex:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\"><em>intoxication/N : (intoxication/N, intoxiquer/V, toxique/A)</em></p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[intoxication, intoxicate, toxic)</p> <ul> <li>its definition, according to the meaning of its base and the Word Formation rule relating X and this base:</li> </ul> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">ex:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\"><em>h&eacute;patique/A</em> =&gt; \"Related to the liver\"</p> <ul> <li>a set of morphology-predicted lexical semantic annotations</li> </ul> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">ex:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\"><em>laver/V</em> [wash] =&gt; [ aspect=dynamic, subcat = &lt; NPagent, NPpatient &gt; ]</p> <p>Further details about D&eacute;rif in :</p> <p>Namer, Fiammetta. 2009. Morphologie, Lexique et TAL : l\'analyseur D&eacute;riF: TIC et Sciences cognitives. London: Hermes Sciences Publishing.</p> <p>Namer, Fiammetta. 2013. A Rule-Based Morphosemantic Analyzer for French for a Fine-Grained Semantic Annotation of Texts. In SFCM 2013, eds. Cerstin Mahlow and M. Piotrowski, 93-115. Heidelberg: Springer.</p> <p>Fiammetta Namer : https://sites.google.com/site/fiammettanamer/</p>', updated_at: '2013-08-29 15:45:25', created_at: '2013-08-29 15:42:03', )
Comment.create(id: '1334', tool_id: '349', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>For more information about BookLamp, its origins and its goals, please see the <a href=\"http://bookgenome.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Book Genome Project\'s website</a> and the <a href=\"http://storytime.booklamp.org/booklamps-faq/\" target=\"_blank\">BookLamp FAQ document</a>.</p> <p>Individual books\' views show their most prominent StoryDNA elements and lists the most similar other books based on those elements. An option to search for similar books by adjusting the amount of particular StoryDNA elements is in the works. For a quick example, please see the entry for Octavia Butler\'s novel <a href=\"http://booklamp.org/book_suggestions.php?refbook=9780807083703\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Kindred</em></a>.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-11 17:47:07', created_at: '2013-09-10 20:50:56', )
Comment.create(id: '1335', tool_id: '214', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>Micro-OCP was a microprocessor implementation of the second version of the Oxford Concordance Program (Jones 131).</p> <p>Randall L. Jones regarded the OCP as an important and under-recognized contribution to the production of computer-assisted concordances (131). The original implementation of the OCP was designed and written by Ian Marriot and Susan Hockey over 1979 and 1980 (O\'Brien 138). It ran on mainframe computers, mostly Digital or IBM equipment though it was designed to be machine-independent (138). As of 1986, over 200 university computer departments had purchased copies, though one of the 40 respondents to Frank O\'Brien\'s 1984 survey of academic researchers reported that their institute could not accommodate the OCP\'s install requirements with the intended equipment (138).</p> <p>The most commonly reported drawback was its long processing times (138). Most users felt the program was reliable with intelligent defaults, though post-purchase technical support was \"poor to non-existent\" despite the excellent user\'s manual (138). Overall, O\'Brien judge the OCP to be a good investments for researchers who needed to do sophisticated analysis but for whom learning a programming language was prohibitive (O\'Brien 141). It was particularly notable for integrating many of the most useful features of CLOC and COCOA (O\'Brien 138).</p> <p>The Micro-OCP debuted in 1987 (Jones 131). Jones described the Micro-OCP as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a general purpose program which makes indexes, concordances, and words lists from texts in a variety of languages. It is not an interactive text retrieval program, but rather it processes the data in batch mode then produces formatted output. Micro-OCP allows for excellent flexibility in the definition of the input and output formats as well as the type of index or concordance to be made. The program is completely menu-driven and requires no programming experience or technical understanding of the computer. Micro-OCP is, however, so feature laden that for even simple applications a fairly detailed orientation is required. (131)</p> <p>Notably, the Micro-OCP allowed text to be formatted in fixed format, COCOA or starting string format (Jones 132). Its strength was its command language, which had commands in four categories (input, words, actions, format) that could be defined in a separate file via the provided commands construction kit and run on a text (132). Users could choose to extract only the dialogue spoken by a particular character, or extracts data from only one subset of the whole, or only process words of a particular length or starting with a particular character (Jones 133-134). The Micro-OCP was not suitable for lemmatized concordances or disambiguation -- though it was possible to use the commands to approximate it, the results suffered from accuracy problems (Jones 135).</p> <p>Jones tested the Micro-OCP\'s processing time and found that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The length of time needed to process a text is a function of the microprocessor speed and the complexity of the task to be performed. A basic word list of a simple text with most command options not chosen requires much less time than a complete concord- ance of a complex text in which several of the *WORDS and *ACTION options have been selected. To make an index of the 36KB sample Greek file (Book 1 of the Iliad) on a PS2/30 required 11.2 minutes, while a complete concord- ance required 25.5 minutes. The output for the index used 86KB of storage on the hard disk; the concordance took up 426.5KB. (Jones 135)</p> <p>He praised the manual as thorough with excellent tutorials, though he found the section on the command language to be cryptic in places (135). Despite a few drawbacks, Jones declared the Micro-OCP an excellent, high quality program (135).</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Jones, Randall L. \"Software Review: Micro-OCP.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.2 (1989): 131-167. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200151\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>O\'Brien, Frank. \"Software Reviews: Oxford Concordance Program.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 20.2 (1986): 131-167. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200056\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-19 21:06:28', created_at: '2013-09-19 20:10:17', )
Comment.create(id: '1336', tool_id: '218', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>L.D. Burnard described CLOC as \"a general purpose text analysis package in the tradition of COCOA, JEUDEMO or OCP\" (Burnard 259).</p> <p>CLOC was written in Algol 68-R, available only on ICL 1900 series mainframes, with its development future uncertain at the time of Burnard\'s review (Burnard 260). CLOC \"operated by first transforming the input text into what is essentially a large symbol table held on direct access backing store. This transformation is necessarily costly and highly machine specific\" (260). Burnard reported that it was faster than comparable programs like OCP at producing a concordance of the same short (500 word) text, remained faster for processing saved files, but was slower processing large texts (5000 words) from raw files (260).</p> <p>It was the first of its type to have a \"comparatively simple user interface\", which Burnard attributes to its intended audience of linguists rather than computer programmers (Burnard 259). It used a simple command language to generate concordances and indexes from text in any language, and required users to define individual characters as letters, padding, separators or to be ignored, with \'read as space\' defined as a special category of separators (259).</p> <p>Burnard found that there were significant limitations to how characters could be defined. For example, CLOC could not equate characters like \'a\' and \'A\' for sorting purposes, padding characters defaulted to non-sorting, and certain parts of a text could be selected for processing by means of delimiters or its position (259). Those limitations aside, CLOC was notable for permitting texts to be saved in its internal format for later, repeated processing - a feature many contemporary programs of its type lacked (259). Users could select words and phrases for analysis based on frequency or pattern, such as all five-letter words ending in T (259).</p> <p>Burnard was particularly pleased with CLOC\'s notably clear manual and simple command language (259). He noted that the command language had a few irritating idiosyncrasies, but judged these as minor quibbles given the program has been successfully used by humanities grad students with minimal trouble (Burnard 260).</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Burnard, L.D. \"Software Review: CLOC.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 14.4 (1980): 259-260. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02404435\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-19 21:06:05', created_at: '2013-09-19 20:59:56', )
Comment.create(id: '1337', tool_id: '222', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>COCOA was a program for creating KWIC concordances, word frequency reports and word counts on texts (Day and Marriott 56).</p> <p>COCOA was first available in the early to mid 1960s. D. B. Russell\'s 1965 review describes the earliest version as \"a system which allows users to generate word-counts and concordances from literary (or other) texts. It was written originally for Atlas after consultation with various British Universities, and is currently being implemented for System 4-75 at Edinburgh\" (Russell).</p> <p>It was still in use 10 years later. In 1974, Paul Corcoran described COCOA as</p> <p class=\"Body1\" style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a highly flexible device for processing natural language texts. The program can produce word and vocabulary counts, concordances with context formats and location references, and word-frequency profiles. Texts supplied by the user may be in any language, although non-Roman characters or alphabets must be transliterated by means of characters or character combinations available on input devices and acceptable to the computer system on which the program is to be run. (Corcoran 566)</p> <p class=\"Body1\">COCOA was written in FORTRAN and housed on approximately 4000 punched cards (Day and Mariott 56). Compared to other programs of its type, COCOA was powerful and flexible, capable of lemmatization, selecting words of specified length or suffix, or specifying only a given section of a text (56). COCOA required three interrelated parts to run, being the COCOA program itself, a 13-card \'control file\' and the text to be processed, though the version adapted to DECsystem-10 computers combined the control file with the text file and permitted users to combine them in a single deck of cards (Corcoran 566). Users could declare their own character set, punctuation, word separators and connectors, special characters and signs (to assist the program\'s processing), references to other parts of the text or text library, a reference format for concordances, inclusion or exclusion of particular words, and suffixes for special processing (566).</p> <p class=\"Body1\">Word counts output in tables, with the program automatically providing the counts sorted in frequency, alphabetic and rhyme (alphabetic on word endings) orders (Russell). Word frequencies were also arranged in a table (Russell). For concordances, COCOA produced a list of all lines a word appeared on, a limited amount of context, and a reference to the source of the text (Russell). The concorded word appeared in the center of the output line surrounded by its context (Russell). All output was suitable for printing without further processing (Corcoran 566). In its earliest version, COCOA required that texts in non-Roman alphabets be transliterated (Russell), but by 1974 it could handle texts of 256 individual characters, or 128 where the alphabet includes upper and lower case forms (Corcoran 566).</p> <p class=\"Body1\">COCOA was notable for permitting users to insert comments directly into the text by enclosing them in square brackets (Russell). Identification records, which assisted COCOA in processing the text, were enclosed in angle brackets (Russell). As both forms of bracket were treated as special characters by the program, they could not be included in the text body (Russell). Russell described the use and treatment of the identification records:</p> <p class=\"Body1\" style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The identification records will typically be copied from the headings of the original script, e.g.</p> <p class=\"Body1\" style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">&lt;W SHAKESPEARE&gt; &lt;T HAMLET&gt; &lt;A 1&gt; &lt;S 1&gt;</p> <p class=\"Body1\" style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">the W standing for Writer not William, T for Title, A for Act and S for Scene and so on. The choice of letters is arbitrary and is left to the individual user except that L always stands for Line Number, which is automatically initialized and incremented by the system. These identification records allow COCOA to identify the different sections of text. By reference to these records, users can program COCOA to select those sections of his archive which are appropriate for a particular study. He can also program COCOA to generate references for occurrences of words appearing in the output from a concordance. (Russell)</p> <p>The control cards provided with the program were used to specify functions, and had the drawback of both lacking clarity and being prone to human error (Day and Marriott 56). However, COCOA was otherwise well commented and had good technical support (56). While COCOA could process any size of text in theory, in practice it was restricted by the core space of the machine processing it and the user\'s available disk space (Corcoran 566). To work around those restrictions, COCOA provided controls for limiting the output of particularly large texts to manageable proportions (Russell). Users could reduce the scope of their text by providing a list of words of particular interest, providing a list of words to exclude, setting the program to only concord words appearing within a specified frequency range, or by breaking up concordance into blocks by alphabetic range (Russell).</p> <p>COCOA was a success with academic users from the start. Russell reports that by the time it had been out for six months, there were academic studies using it in over six languages (Russell). As of 1976, COCOA was still regarded as a valuable tool for literary research (Day and Marriott 56).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Corcoran, Paul E. \"COCOA: A FORTRAN Program for Concordance and Word-count Processing of Natural Language Texts.\" <em>Behavior Research Methods &amp; Instrumentation</em> 6.6 (1974): 566. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.3758%2FBF03201351\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Day, Colin and Ian Marriott. \"Software Reviews: COCOA: A Word Count and Concordance Generator.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.1 (1976): 56. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02399143\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Russell, D. B. \"COCOA - A Word Count and Concordance Generator.\" <em>Associates Technology Literature Applications Society</em> (1965). <a href=\"http://www.chilton-computing.org.uk/acl/applications/cocoa/p001.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-23 22:12:21', created_at: '2013-09-23 22:10:04', )
Comment.create(id: '1338', tool_id: '203', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>GINGER II was a word sense disambiguation tool for English language texts developed by Luca Dini, Vittorio di Tomaso and Fr&eacute;d&eacute;rique Segond, and released in 2000 as the successor to their GINGER I, released in 1998 (Dini, di Tomaso and Segond 121).</p> <p>GINGER II drew from machine-readable dictionaries to generate a semantically-tagged corpus (121). It used the HECTOR Oxford Dictionary of English, the Xerox Incremental Finite State Parser for English and WordNet 1.5 (English) to learn semantic disambiguation tools (Dini, di Tomaso and Segond 122). It used the syntactic relations between subject and verb, verb-object and modifier and subject-object, and associated each word of a functional pair with the appropriate semantic information (122). GINGER II then built a database of semantic disambiguation rules from the relations between words in the corpus\' sentences (Dini, di Tomaso and Segond 121).</p> <p>Unlike its predecessor GINGER I, GINGER II utilized a nonstatistical approach that \"directly extracts semantic disambiguation rules from dictionary example phreases using all funcitonal relations found there,\" which does not require statistical validation (121). It also improved on GINGER I:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">&minus; it relies on dictionary sense numbering to semantically tag dictionary examples</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">&minus; it uses syntactic parsing of dictionary examples to extract semantic disambiguation rules</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">&minus; it uses two sets of semantic information to produce semantic disambiguation rules: the dictionary numbering provided from HECTOR and the 45 top level categories of WordNet. (121)</p> <p>Though GINGER II was designed for English texts, its designers concluded that its methodology is applicable to any language where web-based dictionaries are extant but large pre-tagged corpora are not (Dini, di Tomaso and Segond 125).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Dini, Luca, Vittorio di Tomaso and Frederique Segond. \"GINGER II: An Example-Driven Word Sense Disambiguator.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 34.1-2 (2000): 121-126. <a href=\"http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/16898915/ginger-ii-example-driven-word-sense-disambiguator\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-24 16:52:33', created_at: '2013-09-24 16:49:57', )
Comment.create(id: '1339', tool_id: '206', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview </strong></p> <p>NETMET was a program for generating and interpreting metaphors developed by Eric Steinhart and first released in 1995 (Steinhart 383). It was intended primarily for humanities research, but was also applicable to other disciplines, such as the sciences or philosphy, where clear theories of metaphor are important (383).</p> <p>NETMET was a work of computational philosophy of language that translated philosophical theory from natural language text into a computer language program which could then test the theory (Steinhart 384). It treated producing and interpreting metaphors as rule-governed activities to provide at least a partial literal interpretation (Steinhart 383).</p> <p>Steinhart described it as \"a hybrid computational model, utilizing both the serial symbol processing techniques of classical artificial intelligence and more recent connectionist techniques\" (Steinhart 384). It used lexical semantics to parse input proposition (384). Propositions fell into seven basic kinds, being \"(1) sentential propositions; (2) attribute-value propositions; (3) features; (4) rules; (5) genitive propositions; (6) paradigmatic propositions [and] (7) mereological propositions\" (384).</p> <p>In Steinhart\'s view, NETMET was a successful model for generating and interpreting metaphors and confirmed that \"metaphors are at least as rule-governed as literal language\" (Steinhart 391).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Steinhart, Eric. \"<span class=\"search-match\">NETMET</span>: A Program for Generating and Interpreting Metaphors.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 28.6 (1995): 383-392. <a href=\"http://www.ericsteinhart.com/articles/netmetapa.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Note </strong></p> <p>Eric Steinhart offers NETMET for download on his personal website <a href=\"http://ericsteinhart.com/ANALOGY/lom-netmet.html\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-24 17:35:25', created_at: '2013-09-24 17:33:07', )
Comment.create(id: '1340', tool_id: '207', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview </strong></p> <p>Micro-EYEBALL was a revision of the mainframe program EYEBALL, which \"parses English language texts and provides a statistical description of many linguistic features which are of interest to those involved in stylistics\" (Ross and Hunter 1). It was a microcomputer implementation of the original, which dated to the 1970s, so the program could be of continuing use to humanities scholars who had not participated in mainframe computing (1).</p> <p>EYEBALL, developed by Donald Ross Jr. and Robert H. Rasche, was an information system for students of literature with particular applications for the study of literary style, literary criticism and the history of ideas (Ross and Rasche 213). They began development in the late 1960s:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The general design of the project was outlined in December 1969; by July 1970, the basic VLII programming for all stages had been completed. Current work is in two areas. First, the PL/I programs have been \"translated\" into the Fortran language, in versions for IBM 360 and CDC 6600 computers. This step has made EYEBALL more widely useful; we have found also that Fortran is markedly faster (and cheaper). Second, we have designed batch-processing algorithms of Phase 2 and Phase 4 for computing systems which do not support interactive processors. (Ross and Rasche 216)</p> <p>EYEBALL consisted of a series of computer programs that first surveyed natural language text and then marked wherever possible the text\'s syntax and vocabulary use properties (Ross and Rasche 213). The intermediate processing stage \"indicat[ed] the ends of phrases (prepositional, infinitive, and so on) and of clauses and locations of subjects, predicates, and objects within clauses\" (213). EYEBALL attempted to navigate the ambiguity of the English language while \"maximizing accuracy and minimizing the man-hours involved in the analysis\". Its error tolerance was in the range of 2%, which Ross and Rasche found to be \"quite acceptable\" to science and social science standards, particularly compared to the up to 10% error rate Ross calculated for his own hand counts (213). It did not require a large computer dictionary, nor did it require users to apply markup to their texts prior to processing (Ross and Rasche 214).</p> <p>The microprocessor edition, completed in 1994), was a major overhaul of EYEBALL (Ross and Hunter 1). Ross and Hunter wanted to ensure Micro-EYEBALL would run on widely-available computers to remove the cost and accessibility barrier for even poorly-funded researchers (Ross and Hunter 2). It ran on IBM/PC or compatible personal computers and required only 512K of memory and DOS 3.02 to run, and though a hard disk install was preferable, Ross and Hunter believed that it should also work from floppy disks (2). They kept Micro-EYEBALL\'s constituent programs in FORTRAN and designed the whole \"to be ported to other systems with little or no alteration of the source code\" (2).</p> <p>Micro-EYEBALL accepted ASCII text files and worked best with samples of 500-3000 words (2).</p> <p>Its programs could accomplish common tasks such as generating word lists and parsing (Ross and Hunter 4), and could also systematically characterize distributions of categories and functions (Ross and Hunter 4). Ross and Hunter aimed for Micro-EYEBALL to be straightforward and to accomplish necessary tasks without requiring a large investment of time or effort of its users:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The parser does not identify \"deep\" or \"remote\" structures, transformational histories, nor is it delicate enough to analyze nominal or verbal phrases beyond their main constituents. Unlike a parser which might emulate the psychology of the human reader, both versions of EYEBALL have worked within the technical limits of readily available, inexpensive hardware and software. The aim of the project is not to develop a computer program which teaches or learns English grammar. Our goal is to get to an accurately tagged text with the least time and effort on the researcher\'s part. We have decided upon straightforward syntactic and structural descriptions since a more elaborate system would produce descriptive classes too small for the sample size we recommend. (Ross and Hunter 3)</p> <p>In their view, EYEBALL enabled researchers to quickly and easy test hypotheses about relationships within texts (Ross and Hunter 10).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Ross, Donald and David Hunter. \"Micro-<span class=\"search-match\">EYEBALL</span>: An Interactive System for Producing Stylistic Descriptions and Comparisons.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 28.1 (1994): 1-11. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200305\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Ross Jr., Donald and Robert H. Rasche. \"<span class=\"search-match\">EYEBALL</span>: A Computer Program for Description of Style.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 6.4 (1972): 213-221. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204031\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-26 18:12:38', created_at: '2013-09-26 18:11:35', )
Comment.create(id: '1341', tool_id: '208', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview </strong></p> <p>Collate was a program released in the early 1990s for identifying similarities and differences between files on Macintosh computers (Johnson 401).</p> <p>Eric Johnson reviewed it for <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> in 1994, and tested it using variations of Shakespeare\'s eighteenth sonnet (401). Collate accepted and could process up to 100 text files, and each had to be edited to add the block markers, tags and codes needed to tell the program how to treat key parts of the file (401).</p> <p>Collate was originally developed for use on medieval texts, and consequently offered numerous tools for examining complex texts such as a regularizer for variant spellings (401). It also included fuzzy matching to assist researchers in determining what qualifies as a variant, could handle notation for marginal glosses and descriptions of ornamental capitals, and an output option for inserting formatting codes readable by TeX processors (Johnson 402).</p> <p>Johnson had a few criticisms of Collate. He found that the need to prepare text files with notations and tags increases the learning curve and margin for user errors (Johnson 402). In addition, Collate was not particularly fast at processing texts - Johnson estimated that it would take a full two days to collate the complete works of Shakespeare (Johnson 403).</p> <p>However, Johnson found Collate to overall be \"a robust and adaptable program for collating all kinds of texts...[i]ts output is exhaustive, and it can be formatted in sophisticate ways ready for publication\" (403).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Johnson, Eric. \"Technical Review: Collate: Interactive Collation of Large Textual Traditions.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 27.5-6 (1993): 401-420. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204565\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-26 19:07:17', created_at: '2013-09-26 19:06:16', )
Comment.create(id: '1342', tool_id: '209', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>XTRACT was a lexical collocation tool developed by Frank Smadja in the early 1990s that used statistical techniques for retrieving and identifying collocations in a large textual corpora (Smadja, \"XTRACT\" 399).</p> <p>Rather than a single tool, XTRACT was a set of tools for locating words in context and making statistical observations to identify collocations (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 150). Smadja aimed to promote XTRACT as useful for any text-based application, such as language generation, retrieving grammatical collocations (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 171), or generating a multilingual lexicography (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 174).</p> <p>In 1993, Smadja rolled out an expanded and refined version of XTRACT which computed more information and was optimized to improve how much fuctional information it could extract (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 150). According to Smadja, the 1993 version of XTRACT worked in three stages:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">In the first stage, pairwise lexical relations are retrieved using only statistical information....In the second stage, multiple-word combinations and complex expressions are identified....Finally, by combining parsing and statistical techniques the third stage labels and filters collocations retrieved at stage one. The third stage has been evaluated to raise the precision of Xtract from 40% to 80% with a recall of 94%. (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 145)</p> <p>Smadja also found that the third stage could \"be considered as a retrieval system that retrieves valid collocations from a set of candidates\" (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 166).</p> <p>It used statistics to retrieve pairwise lexical relations from a corpus where they are correlated within a sentence, and \"retain[ed] words (or parts of speech) occupying a position with probability greater than a given threshold\" (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 151). XTRACT could also apply its collocations to producing other lexicographic output, such as adding syntax (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 161), producing tagged concordances, parsing texts and labeling sentences (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 162).</p> <p>XTRACT\'s results varied based on the size of the corpus (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 168). Smadja found that the program was not effective low-frequency words, which negatively impacted smaller texts because they did not have a large enough distribution amongst their collocates (168). The results also varied based on the content of a corpus, evident with Smadja\'s example using Wall Street data:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Food is not eaten at Wall Street but rather traded, sold, offered, bought, etc. If the corpus only contains stories in a given domain, most of the collocations retrieved will also be dependent on this domain...in addition to jargonistic words, there are a number of more familiar terms that form collocations when used in different domains. A corpus containing stock market stories is obviously not a good choice for retrieving collocations related to weather reports or for retrieving domain independent collocations such as \"<em>make-decision</em>.\" (Smadja, \"Retrieving Collocations\" 169)</p> <p>In Smadja\'s view, XTRACT produced results with the highest quality and greatest range of collocations, which he credits to its filtering system and syntactic labeling (Smadja, \"XTRACT\" 411).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Smadja, Frank. \"Retrieving Collocations from Text: XTRACT.\" <em>Computational Linguistics</em> 19.1 (1993): 143-177. <a href=\"http://acl.ldc.upenn.edu/J/J93/J93-1007.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Smadja, Frank. \"XTRACT: An Overview.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.5-6 (1992): 399-413. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204633\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-09-27 17:48:25', created_at: '2013-09-27 17:47:32', )
Comment.create(id: '1343', tool_id: '211', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>PC-KIMMO is a morphological parser developed for microcomputers (Antworth 389). Its development began in 1985 at the Summer Institute for Linguistics in Texas (\"About PC-KIMMO\").</p> <p>PC-KIMMO was coded in Microsoft C by David Smith and Stephen McConnell, and was directed by Gary Simons (\"About PC-KIMMO\"). The program was developed for IBM/PC, Macintosh and UNIX (Hinkelman and Olsen 157), and also ran on PC-compatible computers with MS-DOS (Antworth 391). It could generate word forms from roots, reduce word forms to roots, and identify the tense, mood, gender and number of words (Hinkelman and Olsen 157). PC-KIMMO was language-independent and has been used for languages ranging from English to Finnish to Japanese (157).</p> <p>According to Evan L. Antworth, \"PC-KIMMO is based on [Kimmo] Koskenniemi\'s two-level model of morphology. In the two-level model, a word is represented as a direct, character-for-character correspondence between its underlying or lexical form (UF) and its surface form (SF) (Antworth 391).\" KIMMO was a parser where \"the morphological description is stated independently of the parser program code and comprises two components, a lexical (and morphotactic) component and a phonological component\" in Finnish computer scientist Kimmo Koskenniemi\'s morphological parsing system (Antworth 390). Koskenniemi developed his parser to be applicable across languages and the result \"[could] be used to build parsers for any natural language\" (390). Lauri Karttunen did so in 1983, and Karttunen\'s KIMMO became the best-known implementation (390).</p> <p>In addition to parsing texts, PC-KIMMO could produce interlinear text translations or annotations. It could also be used to build applications, such as the text processing program KTEXT (Antworth 393). The KTEXT application parsed text stored on a disk file then wrote the results to a new disk file, and had the advantage of accepting PC-KIMMO rules and lexicon files directly without requiring modification (393).</p> <p>PC-KIMMO was designed particularly for humanities computing tasks:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">In order to meet the demands of humanities computing, we need a general morphological parser that meets three criteria: (1) it must be consistent with generally accepted linguistic theory, (2) it can be used with any natural language, and (3) it can easily be used as part of a larger computational system. PC-KIMMO, though perhaps not the ultimate solution to our parsing needs, meets these criteria and has the advantage that it is readily available to scholars who use personal computers. (Antworth 397)</p> <p>It was well-received by the Humanities Computing academic community. Reviewers Elizabeth Hinkelman and Mark Olsen, writing for journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>, found that PC-KIMMO offered</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a very simple form of linguistic analysis that can be made very comprehensive with some effort. Like most CL efforts, it has a weak user interface and a data acquisition bottleneck. The code is competently executed and extensively documented. It shows great promise, and we consider it as one of the first solid indications that CL technology is ready for humanities applications. (Hinkelman and Olsen 162)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>NOTE: While development of PC-KIMMO ceased in the mid-1990s (\"About PC-KIMMO\"), SIL Computing Resources maintains it as a <a href=\"http://www.sil.org/pckimmo/\">free download</a>, including all applicable documentation.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>\"About PC-KIMMO: A Two-Level Processor for Morphological Analysis.\" <em>SIL International </em>(homepage). 27 Mar. 1996. <a href=\"http://www-01.sil.org/pckimmo/about_pc-kimmo.html\">Web</a>. 30 Sept. 2013.</p> <p>Antworth, Evan L. \"Glossing Text with the PC-<span class=\"search-match\">KIMMO</span> Morphological Parser.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>&nbsp;26.5-6 (1992): 389-398. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204457\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Hinkelman, Elizabeth and Mark Olsen. \"Technical Reviews: PC-<span class=\"search-match\">Kimmo</span>: A Computational Linguistic Tool for Humanities Applications.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.2 (1992): 157-168. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204632\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-01 18:50:13', created_at: '2013-10-01 18:47:20', )
Comment.create(id: '1344', tool_id: '212', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>URICA! II was collation tool for microcomputers, and an updated version of URICA! (User Response Interactive Collation Assistant) (Hilton 139.) This update was released in 1992 by Michael Hilton and his team (139).</p> <p>At the time of URICA! II\'s release, URICA! was installed at 35 registered sites (139). While URICA! ran on IBM and PC-compatible computers under DOS, URICA! II was developed for Macintosh to take advantage of the streamlined interface possible with its GUI and mouse (139). Rather than running in DOS, URICA! II was launched from its icon the Macintosh desktop (Hilton 140). Its interface integrated pull-down menus with options \"to begin a new collation, resume an old collation, define a variant category list, or conflate several variant files. Several other options, such as the viewing and printing of files...are included in the program\" (140). Hilton found that the mouse interface was more efficient at resolving variables than URICA!\'s reliance on the keyboard\'s function keys (Hilton 141).</p> <p>URICA! II built directly on URICA!, which sought to address the drawbacks of the computer collation systems available at the time:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">URICA!\'s primary goal is to give scholars an interactive system for text collation that is carried out as texts are being read into the computer. As a result, the system is more flexible than others that have been available previously. Run on large batch computer systems, previous approaches had to invoke the operating system, entering two file names, and wait for the collation results. In cases where two texts were greatly different, these computer programs often got lost trying to resolve complicated variants and were incapable of proceeding without human intervention. The scholar had to determine the point of resumption and start the system once more. (Cannon and Oakman 470)</p> <p>URICA! was developed by Robert Cannon and Robert Oakman to identify variants between two texts by comparing a text provided by the user to a machine-readable master text (Cannon and Oakman 469). The text for comparison could be loaded from a file or typed directly into URICA!\'s interface, and the tool output a third file detailing the variants, the classifications applied to each variant, and where they occurred in the text (469). According to Cannon and Oakman, URICA! was developed to assist Father Romauld Green of St. Bonaventure University in creating a scholarly edition of Duns Scotus:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Father Green had only one printed text of Duns Scotus, which had been optically scanned; the other ten significant texts were Latin manuscripts that had to be keyed into the machine manually. Green wanted a program to allow him to do his collations and store his variants interactively as he was preparing his texts at a keyboard of a micro- computer. As a result of his query, students and faculty in Computer Science at South Carolina set to work to produce a collation scheme to fit Green\'s problem: URICA! -- User Response Interactive Collation Assistant. (469)</p> <p>Cannon and Oakman found that interacting directly with the computer to resolve variants was faster and more convenient for scholars (Cannon and Oakman 470). URICA!\'s development began in 1984 using Turbo Pascal, then a popular choice for developing software for IBM and compatible personal computers (470). They chose Pascal and to target microcomputers in part because in 1984, microcomputers were the least expensive choice, and \"many academic departments and individuals in the humanities have already invested in such computers\" (470). In addition, Pascal supported their aim to present master and comparison texts in separate windows, so that users could see both at once as URICA! compared them (470). Microcomputers also permitted users to distribute files between disparate machines, including transferring machine-readable texts stored on tape to mainframes and then to a microcomputer with URICA! installed (470). The master text was stored on a diskette, and users could either enter the comparison text via keyboard or access it from a second diskette (470).</p> <p>URICA! II improved on its predecessor by semi-automating the process of collating texts (Hilton 139). It automatically resolved short variants up to approximately five words in length, and prompted users to resolve longer variants as the program found them (139). According to Hilton, \"[t]he computer provides fast and accurate manipulation of large quantities of text, and the human makes judgments regarding complex differences in the texts. The computer locates the start of a variant, and the human locates its end\" (Hilton 140). Unlike URICA!, which restricted users to three preset categories -- insertion, deletion and replacement&nbsp; (Cannon and Oakman 469) -- URICA! II enabled users to define their own categories and have the program tag variants as belonging to them automatically (Hilton 139).</p> <p>Unlike Collate, which was designed for use with medieval texts with a high degree of variability, \"URICA! II was designed primarily for use with modern literary texts where typographic and orthographic concerns are minimal. The result is a tool which is simple, easy to use, and sufficient for most collation tasks\" (Hilton 143). URICA! II did not contain direct features for handling alternate spellings or markup, as Collate did, but it could simulate them by creating categories for instances such as Middle English\'s variant word forms and using a filter to normalize variants marked as alternative spellings (143). URICA! II treated markup as text, and when a marked up text was compared to a version without markup, it could categorize markup as a variant (143).</p> <p>As a whole, URICA II improved on URICA! with an intuitive interface that made collation quick and efficient, enabling users to focus on analyzing the text rather than collecting variants (Hilton 144).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Cannon, Robert L. and Oakman, Robert L. \"Interactive Collation on a Microcomputer: The <span class=\"search-match\">URICA</span>! Approach.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.6 (1989): 469-472. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200178\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Hilton, Michael L. \"The <span class=\"search-match\">URICA</span>! II Collation System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.2 (1992): 139-144. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204452\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-03 19:45:30', created_at: '2013-10-03 19:44:10', )
Comment.create(id: '1345', tool_id: '91', user_id: '30', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: 'MorphAdorner v2.0 became available in September 2013.', updated_at: '2013-10-07 02:48:23', created_at: '2013-10-07 02:48:23', )
Comment.create(id: '1346', tool_id: '213', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>VINCI is a natural language generation system developed by Michael Levison and Gregory Lessard of Queen\'s University in Kingston, Ontario (Levison and Lessard 43). It was programmed in C, and the version released in 1992 could run in UNIX, MS-DOS and VM/CMS (43).</p> <p>Levison and Lessard describe VINCI as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a natural language generation system...which accepts as input a formal description of some subset of natural language, and generates strings in the language. With the help of an attribute grammar formalism, the system can be used to simulate on a computer components of several current linguistic theories. (43)</p> <p>Their goal was to create a system capable of embodying constructs from a variety of linguistic theories (Levison and Lessard 44). The resulting program is</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[o]n the one hand...an attempt to provide an environment for solving a particular range of problems, among them teaching basic concepts of linguistic theory, modelling performance errors and providing a generative computer-aided language learning environment. On the other hand, it attempts to provide the most common devices found in mainstream generative grammar. (44)</p> <p>Levison and Lessard wanted a system with rules that were as familiar as possible to researchers, that did not require them to learn to program, and that provided a morphology and lexicon rather than require users to construct their own (44). As such, \"VINCI provides the linguist with metalanguages as similar as possible to those used in current linguistic research\" (44).</p> <p>As of 1992, they were working toward expanding VINCI to include second-language learning, via exercises composed of question and expected answer pairs (Levison and Lessard 55). The prototype looked for common typing errors such as transposition and omitted letters or words, with the intent of identifying errors by type and providing appropriate advice (Levison and Lessard 57). They were also applying VINCI to modelling language errors, or \"malrules\" (Levison and Lessard 57).</p> <p>The 1992 release of VINCI allowed users to modify the data, including morphology and lexicon, as needed (Levison and Lessard 45). The system could load a language description in under a minute on a SUN network or an IBM 3081G, but was \"considerably slower\" on an IBM PC (286) (45). It was designed to handle a wide range of languages -- though Levison and Lessard mostly used VINCI with French, it was also successfully applied to English, Russian, Italian and basic French phonetics (45).</p> <p>Even in its earliest version, VINCI was successful as a tool for facilitating linguistic research, and for linguistic students exploring language generation concepts (Levison and Lessard 55).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><em>Note: Vinci continued development into the 2000s and has been maintained online by the developers with comprehensive documentation. It can be found <a href=\"http://research.cs.queensu.ca/CompLing/\">here</a>.</em></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Levison, Michael and Gregory Lessard. \"A System for Natural Language Sentence Generation.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.1 (1992): 43-58. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204437\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-08 17:49:36', created_at: '2013-10-08 17:46:57', )
Comment.create(id: '1347', tool_id: '217', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>DV-COLL is a data entry and textual collation program originally developed in the 1980s by the Donne Variorum to facilitate digitizing and updating The Variorum Edition of the Poetry of John Donne (Stringer and Vilberg 83).</p> <p>The Donne Variorum\'s Advisory Board began investigating their options for digitization in 1981, and identified microcomputers as relatively inexpensive and the most convenient computer system available (83). They first tried two preexisting collation programs developed for the Apple II + (Stringer and Vilberg 85). The first was a PASCAL program called Imitatio Christi, which could manage up to six variations at a time but relied on the user to locate variations by sight and resolve them manually (Stringer and Vilberg 86). The second was an unnamed program, described as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Dearing\'s adaptation for the microcomputer of the COBOL code that the editors of the California Dryden project have run for years on the UCLA mainframe. This program...performs word-by-word comparison of variants, but like the other, is specifically written for the Apple II + with language card. (86)</p> <p>However, the project had already transcribed and numbered each of Donne\'s poems, and assigned an 11-character identification code to each record (Stringer and Vilberg 84). They also encoded metadata indicating the source, page numbers, format of source, date of transcription, transcriber, title, line of the poem, any applicable subscriptions, and distinctive features of the original text (ex: scribal flourishes or orthographic peculiarities) alongside the poems (84). They required a program that could not only handle this metadata, but assist in reconciling variant versions of Donne\'s poems.</p> <p>Neither Imitatio Christi nor the Dearing program fully met the Donne Variorum\'s needs, so Bill Vilberg and Bruce Dinoff wrote a BASIC program in two major phases to meet the project\'s requirements (Stringer and Vilberg 86). This program ran on microcomputers, with versions for CP/M machines, including the Apple II +, for the IBM-PC and the TRS-80 (86). This program, which was soon called DV-COLL, was</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[q]uite flexible and powerful in its present form, the program can collate up to fourteen versions of a poem simultaneously. Individual lines may extend to 256 characters each, far more than enough capacity to handle even the longest lines in Whitman and roughly twice the compressed-print line-length of the eighty-column printer. (86)</p> <p>The program handled data in small quantities and 48k of memory was sufficient to run it (86). It was restricted by the length of the text, the disk capacity available for the variants users wished to collate, and whether the user wanted to store the output on disk for later access or manipulation with a word processor (86). The output could be displayed onscreen or printed instead (86).</p> <p>Users could choose from three options for output. Firstly, DV-COLL could show each line of the text next to the corresponding line from each variant (86). It could also flag each distinct version of a line (Stringer and Vilberg 87). Thirdly, it could compare individual words of each alternate version of a line to the master text, and flag words according to whether they\'re variants, deleted or additional (87). In the line and word comparison instances, DV-COLL displayed exact matches to the master version as a blank line or space, showing only the variations in full (87).</p> <p>Stringer and Vilburg also described key features of DV-COLL\'s interface:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">A number of built-in internal features make the program versatile and easy to use. Once a collation run is completed, the program returns to its opening menu, which shows a numbered list of the files currently entered for processing, and allows the editor either to break out of BASIC and turn to other tasks or to proceed with additional collation. At this point the operator can exercise any of the several options that are available at initial boot up: to clear the list and enter new files for collation, to re-collate the currently entered batch at a different level, to insert or delete files from the list, to re-order the files in any way desired, to call up a disk directory of files available for collation, or to look at a help screen. (Stringer and Vilburg 88-89)</p> <p>The Donne Variorum released DV-COLL to the wider academic community as \"a contribution to the field of textual editing,\" and Stringer and Vilburg judged that the project \"made every effort to ensure that the program will be friendly to the scholars who need to use it\" (89). Interested users could purchase both the program and its documentation directly from The Donne Variorum for $10 (89).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><em>Note</em>: The Donne Variorum has continued development on DV-COLL and now offers it for free download through their website.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Stringer, Gary A. and William R. Vilberg. \"The Donne Variorum Textual Collation Program.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 21.2 (1987): 83-89. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200075\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-10 17:45:42', created_at: '2013-10-10 17:41:42', )
Comment.create(id: '1348', tool_id: '220', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>KLIC was a program for text analysis developed in the 1970s by Grace B. Logan of the University of Waterloo Arts Computing Office (Logan 94).</p> <p>Much like Key Word in Context (KWIC) programs produced word concordances, KLIC produced \"an alphabetized list of key letters printed under each other in a \"gutter\" with the graphological context of the word it occurs in printed on either side of it\" with individual words \"tagged to indicate its frequency of occurrence in each text and manuscript\" (94).</p> <p>KLIC was developed to address the problem of analyzing medieval texts, particularly the relationship between pronunciation and spelling found in such texts (Logan 93). For example, \"in the Modem English the sons raise meat and the sun\'s rays meet, the two sentences have exactly the same pronunciation but are differentiated in writing\" (italics in original) because</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">in medieval texts writing was more strongly motivated to represent speech than to represent grammatical forms. In a medieval text the two sentences cited above might be spelled the same since they are pronounced the same. Nevertheless, no text represents a phonological transcription, and there are further inconsistencies in that the same word may be represented by different spellings. The problem, then, is to determine when these different spellings represent different pronunciations and when they represent different words with the same pronunciation. (93)</p> <p>Grace B. Logan developed KLIC to analyze lists of headwords or unique words generated by Philip H. Smith\'s concordance package (Logan 94). Harry M. Logan found that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The headword includes a \"translated\" form for proper collation and alphabetizing, the text form and its frequency of occurrence, to which KLIC adds a tag identifying manuscript and text. The \"translated\" form is necessary to indicate equivalences of letters and positioning in the alphabet, especially when non-alphabetic characters and diacritics are used. Thus, not only can capital letters be equated with their small letter equivalents, but such letters as &thorn; and &eth; can be listed after t in the alphabet and either treated separately or together, depending on the choice of the concordancer. (94)</p> <p>KLIC sorted all words containing the desired letter by the letters appearing to the right of that letter, which made it possible to determine which letters or combinations of letters tend to follow the key letter within the source text (94). The list of sorted words were arranged in the leftmost column of a table, with the frequency of each word provided in the columns to the right (Logan 96). Each text in the corpus analyzed was assigned its own column, enabling direct comparison of word frequencies between texts (96).</p> <p>The KLIC results required cross-referencing with a concordance for word context information, but Harry M. Logan found that even the KLIC results alone were useful for identifying dialect characteristics and differences across texts when applied to Middle English texts (96).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Logan, Harry M. \"<span class=\"search-match\">KLIC</span>: A Computer Aid to Graphological Analysis.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 12.1-2 (1978): 93-96. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199940\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-16 18:45:05', created_at: '2013-10-16 18:43:34', )
Comment.create(id: '1349', tool_id: '215', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>FINNMORF was a computational linguistics reference tool developed in the 1980s by Eugene Holman (Holman 165).</p> <p>Holman wrote FINNMORF in BASIC to generate full paradigms for \"virtually any Finnish lexical item which can be declined or conjugated\" (165). It ran directly from the operating system on an IBM PC or compatible under MS-DOS (Holman 166).</p> <p>Holman designed FINNMORF to take advantage of the capacity for personal computers to \"become a source of specific information about the language being studied\" (Holman 165). Holman chose BASIC, which was not commonly used in computational linguistics at the time, to complement this aim (Holman 171). BASIC\'s appeal lay in its string handling capabilities and the fact it permitted developers to create ad hoc variables as needed (171). Most importantly, Holman found that BASIC was so common and easy to learn compared to languages like LISP or SNOBOL4 that, \"insofar as a future language teacher or student is going to have any programming experience at all, it is most likely to be with some dialect of BASIC\" (171) -- an important consideration for a language modeling tool.</p> <p>It was designed to assist language learning and instruction, and for that reason, \"[a]ppropriately programmed, it can provide a powerful alternative to dictionaries, thesauruses, morphological hand-books, and many other traditional ancillaries to foreign-language instruction in CALL\" (165) It modeled Finnish morphological forms, taking into account factors unique to the Finnish language:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Three considerations require a reference tool of this type: (1) the paradigm of a Finnish nominal or verb can have several hundred different forms, (2) the Finnish lexicographical tradition is oriented towards Finns learning foreign languages rather than towards foreigners learning Finnish (for this reason neither bilingual nor monolingual Finnish dictionaries normally list principal parts or provide information concerning the morphological behavior of specific entries), and (3) Finnish morphology is characterized by several morphophonemic alternations such as grade alternation, vowel harmony, and assibilation, which can cause the surface forms of a specific lexical stem to diverge from one another sharply. Consequently, students of Finnish as a foreign language acutely need a convenient and quick means of viewing the paradigms of an unfamiliar lexical item and determining its inflectional characteristics. (Holman 165-166)</p> <p>FINNMORPH contained two modules for handling data, FINNVERB, which conjugated verbs, and FINNSUB, which declined nominals, plus a third for returning the user to the operating system (Holman 166). FINNVERB was self-contained, while FINNSUB required eleven separate data files to run (166). Its modules could be run separately or together, and its output could be printed or saved to disk (166). The interface consisted of a menu of options tied to numerical keys (166).</p> <p>Wherever the text contained compound words, FINNMORF required users to insert a slash (/) between the component words as without it, the program could not locate the morpheme boundary (Holman 167). FINNMORF broke down words for processing via string-handling processes, and then generated stems and paradigms for the item:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">After a lexical item is input, the program module in question matches it as a whole against various lists of ambiguous or anomalous lexical items to determine whether more information is needed before the paradigms can be constructed, and then breaks it down into substrings of various sizes to determine whether it is synchronically foreign, and how it behaves with respect to such morpho-phonemic processes as vowel harmony, consonant gradation, and vowel mutations. When these basic characteristics have been determined the program subjects the string to a battery of tests to determine which morphological alternations and which declensional patterns apply to it; strings corresponding to the appropriate stem allomorphs are produced when appropriate. When the entire battery of tests is complete, strings corresponding to the major and minor stems will have been produced, and from these the paradigms are formed by simply adding the endings to the appropriate stem. (167)</p> <p>In Holman\'s estimation, FINNMORF \"exemplifies the potential of [the BASIC] programming language for computational linguistics\" (Holman 165).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Holman, Eugene. \"<span class=\"search-match\">FINNMORF</span>: A Computerized Reference Tool for Students of Finnish Morphology.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 22.3 (1988):165-172. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200118\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-16 19:51:40', created_at: '2013-10-16 19:50:23', )
Comment.create(id: '1350', tool_id: '356', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: 'Welkin serves as a \"telescope\" for the RDF data, a tool that lets you understand global shape and cluster characteristics of the data rather than the individual item. Its functions allow not only graphical representation of subject, object and predicate, but also more interactive exploration of the graph. End users are not the audience whose needs Welkin is ready to address. The program caters more for the data and metadata analysts who need to see connectivity of a particular dataset within the whole.  Generally speaking Welkin helps analysts to get the mental model of a dataset. In addition to different graph manipulation Welkin offers different functions for the work with predicates, resources and charts.   ', updated_at: '2013-10-30 22:41:23', created_at: '2013-10-18 17:28:12', )
Comment.create(id: '1351', tool_id: '219', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>WORDS was a system of content analysis programs developed by Howard P. Iker and associates at the University of Rochester (Cary 129). It was designed to identify major themes within a text without relying on preexisting categorization systems (Iker and Klein 430).</p> <p>The WORDS system was first described in the mid-1960s and was in continuous development over the 1960s and 1970s (Iker and Klein 430). The name WORDS is a mnemonic referring to the collection of programs within the system and \"is based upon the pivotal logic of the method itself, viz, that sufficient information exists within the word and within the temporal associations among and between words to allow data-generated elicitation of major content themes and materials\" (430). As of 1979, WORDS had been installed in over a dozen facilities across North America and continental Europe, in addition to South America (Cary 130).</p> <p>As a system, WORDS was composed of a collection of compatible and interrelated but otherwise independent programs designed to help users to manage the data flow of their analysis by both passing and receiving data as needed (Iker and Klein 430). It contained a suite of 38 sub-programs, 32 which were available to be called by users, with the remaining 8 designed to be called only by other programs or act as service programs (Cary 129). </p> <p>Each program within WORDS intended for human access was assigned a mnemonic used to call it, such as CLOSE to output data and retrieve any messages generated, or JOIN to concatenate data sets (Iker and Klein 432). Users could set a run of programs and call them in any order (432). WORDS included an associated program, JOBS, which produced diagnostic error messages and assisted users in communicating with the computer\'s operating system, which removed the need for users to learn how to do so themselves (432). JOBS also included five fixed configurations of WORDS programs, to save time for users when calling programs that were usually preceded or followed by particular other programs (432). Iker and Klein described JOBS as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">our best current attempt to make the use of WORDS a relatively straightforward task requiring a minimum of computer sophistication. It is further developed to minimize the problems of implementing WORDS at installations other than that at which the system was developed. Our experience has been that JOBS can substantially reduce the effect of installation differences through use of its many options and parameters. (432)</p> <p>WORDS used individual words as units of information and divided the text according to units of time, segments of a specified length, paragraphs or other similar divisions (Iker and Klein 430). Within a text\'s divisions, WORDS determined word frequencies and frequencies of word correlations to develop an intercorrelation matrix and systematically locate common word groups (430). It was designed specifically to avoid dependency on predetermined categories or dictionaries, and instead to generate its own thematic \"centroids\" (430). According to Iker and his colleague Robert H. Klein, this design approach was a deliberate response to research findings:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Our research has demonstrated that these word groups both represent and indentify the major content themes in the raw data. Elaboration and analysis of these thematic data can then be conducted by using such methods as cluster of factor scoring to locate and inspect highly saturated sections of the raw data, by configurational analyses to examine changes in content profile patternings in different portions of the data, and so on. (430)</p> <p>WORDS worked by manipulating words statistically and handled words individually while also associating metadata about that word such its location, the part of speech it represents, or the speaker (Iker and Klein 431). It separated words and punctuation marks into an independent standardized record with 10 pieces of associated metadata (431).</p> <p>Users were required to prepare the text before processing (431). Preparation entailed selecting an observational unit, such as paragraphs, or segments split by time such as one minute\'s worth data (431). Iker and Klein found units of one minute particularly useful for psychotherapy data (431), though their 1974 paper does not indicate whether units of time refer to how much the computer can process in that span, or an equivalent quantity of spoken language, or a specific number of sentences or words. Users then needed to assign a unique number to each unit and transfer the data onto punched cards (431). For each card, contractions needed to be expanded into separate words, proper nouns flagged by preceding them with \'$\', and quotation marks either removed or replaced with double apostrophes (431). All text on a given card had to belong to the same segment, though the segment could span as many cards as needed (431).</p> <p>Iker and his colleagues developed WORDS in PL/I, and as of the 1974 edition it would run on</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">an IBM S/360 Model 50 (or higher) computer with at least 256K bytes of available core, which operates under full OS, has a PLII compiler of LevelS or greater, and has available a 2314 disk device or interchangeable counterpart. If these requirements can be satisfied, WORDS can be implemented at the target installation. The project has several memoranda which detail specific requirements; they are available on request. (Iker and Klein 437).</p> <p>Charles D. Cary, who reviewed WORDS for <em>Computers in the Humanities</em> in 1979, found that WORDS required a specialist to install it and assist with any problems encountered in its use (Cary 130). Cary recommended that users of the WORDS system be familiar with operating packaged programs, and have a basic understanding of statistics, as this experience would \"help to make sense out of what is happening during the content analysis and to interpret the results\" (130).</p> <p>Indeed, WORDS required a large investment of time despite efforts to make it as simple as possible (Iker and Klein 437). While not \"intolerably difficult\", Iker and Klein</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">wish[ed] to stress that one should not expect to make use of the system as though it could be acquired in one day, run up on the target computer on the next, and put into operation on the third. Understanding the interrelationship among and between programs, learning to use the JOBS program, making changes to satisfy installation differences by appropriate option and parameter changes, all require substantial amounts of time. While the project itself sets no constraints on potential users, we have always advised interested researchers to consider carefully whether they wish to invest the time to learn to use WORDS effectively. (437)</p> <p>Iker and Klein emphasized the value of WORDS as a research tool despite the challenges of using it. In their view,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[t]he asset of WORDS is that the themes and content areas it produces are much richer, more detailed, and, by definition, more in tune with the original data than those which would be produced by the sole use of a priori category systems. At the same time, one of the liabilities of WORDS is that these results are inevitably defined in the words of the speaker. This is a reasonable characteristic so long as WORDS is used to describe solely the data base under analysis. When, however, one tries to generalize from one set of data to another, to compare one data base with another, even to compare two separate analyses on different parts of the same data, substantial problems can arise, because the results are difficult to put onto a common measuring dimension or set of dimensions. (Iker and Klein 436)</p> <p>From the user\'s perspective, Cary found the manual detailed, with over 200 pages of material. He noted its seven-point write-up for each user-called program, the full listing of the diagnostic messages produced in response to system errors, a glossary of data processing terms as used in the manual, and example configurations of the user-called programs for content analysis (Cary 130). The manual also included installation memoranda and listed a variety of texts describing the system and research applying it (Cary 129). Though WORDS was designed for use with English text, Cary found that researchers had applied it to Russian, French and a South African dialect, Chichewa and that it could be applied to additional languages as long as the text used the Latin alphabet and Arabic numerals (Cary 130).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Cary, Charles D. \"Software Review: A User\'s View of WORDS.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 13.2 (1979): 129-30. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02404509\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Iker, Howard P. and Robert H. Klein. \"WORDS: A Computer System for the Analysis of Content.\" <em>Behavior Research Methods &amp; Instrumentation</em> 6.4 (1974): 430-438. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.3758%2FBF03200396\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-22 18:42:24', created_at: '2013-10-22 18:39:26', )
Comment.create(id: '1352', tool_id: '216', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>WordCruncher was a microcomputer concordance program for manipulating large text corpora developed by the Electronic Text Corporation in the late 1980s (Olsen 255).</p> <p>According to Mark Olsen, who reviewed the program for <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>, \"WordCruncher is a renamed and slightly updated version of the successful Brigham Young University Concordance Program (4.0)\" that included rewritten documentation and improvements on the original (255).</p> <p>The 1987 version of WordCruncher consisted of two sub-programs, INDEXETC and VIEWETC (Olsen 256). From a plain text input file, INDEXETC created files with cross references, a word list and word frequencies, while VIEWETC used INDEXETC output to concord the specified words, generate word frequency and distribution reports, and index both key word in context (KWIC) and key word out-of-context data for the text (256). Users were required to specify which control codes WordCruncher should use to partition the text into sections for identification before processing, or WordCruncher would default to book, chapter and paragraph partitioning (256). Alternate divisions included page and line (Olsen 256).</p> <p>INDEXETC also included translation tables, which specified word sort orders, character attributes and character translations for use users\' texts, and stopword files (256). WordCruncher defaulted to English for these, but alternate languages such as French and German were also included with the program (256). The translation tables enabled users to specify which characters to treat as separators, to automate character substitutions where required, and define the desired sort order for the tool\'s output (256). While INDEXETC could embed code into ASCII texts automatically, its capabilities were sufficiently limited that Olsen expected most users would resort to insert coding manually or through their own customized coding program to ensure the program handled all aspects of the text as required (256).</p> <p>VIEWETC permitted users to query output, such as looking up words, parts of words or phrases (Olsen 257). It also included features for underlining or highlighting parts of the text (257). This part of WordCruncher utilized a windows-based interface, enabling users to not only have multiple windows open but to customize the display for each one as needed (257). Lookup could be accomplished either by typing directly or by selecting a word from the provided list, which also showed the number of occurrences for each searchable item (257).</p> <p>VIEWETC\'s collocation program was particularly powerful as it generated a table with the total occurrences of a word, its co-occurrences within a specified range and also listed valid cases (257). For word occurrences, users could specify ranges of texts to include, so that users could compare results between sections of their corpus (Olsen 258). Users could create reference lists of multiple words to include in a concordance report (Olsen 257). The lists feature enabled users to concord inflections of a single word (257), or related words, such as legal terms or pronouns, all in the same report (Olsen 258).</p> <p>The interface was a major part of WordCruncher\'s appeal. Olsen found that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[t]he user interface is sensible and remains consistent between the two programs. Display screens are usually well laid out, are easy to read and can be tailored to individual tastes. This aspect is important since both programs deliver a lot of information, even during long processing periods, and are completely menu-driven. Once the command structure is mastered, the programs are manipulated quickly and efficiently. (Olsen 255)</p> <p>WordCruncher was capable of manipulating large text corpora exceeding 250 megabytes, though it required a computer with a CD-ROM drive to handle such texts (Olsen 255).</p> <p>Olsen identified several problems with WordCruncher, all of which he judged minor (Olsen 260). He found its reference section confusing, as the VIEWETC section was arranged by command name in defiance of its menu-driven interface, and INDEXETC was arranged by file name, which Olsen found \"opaque\" (260). He also noted a few bugs, one of which caused menus to display briefly even when not in use, and another that monopolized the computer\'s printer port, preventing other programs from sending jobs to the printer correctly unless the user reset the machine (260). The INDEXETC subprogram was furthermore incompatible with some memory-resident utilities to the point that INDEXETC \"will fail on start\" (260). Lastly, Olsen found WordCruncher\'s output less readable than its previous version, the BYU Concordance, as highlighted target words could now appear anywhere in the line rather than the program automatically centering them in the display (260).</p> <p>Despite his concerns with the presentation order, Olsen found the documentation thorough, including a list of error messages, explanations of error codes with troubleshooting recommendations, textbase design help and a frequently asked questions section (260). The commands and procedures were clearly explained and accompanied with examples and illustrations (260).</p> <p>Olsen \"enthusiastically recommended [WordCruncher] to scholars requiring a concordance system as well as a more general text retrieval system\" (Olsen 255). As a whole, he judged that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[WordCruncher] is, with very minor exceptions, well finished. It incorporates a powerful concording system with more general search and retrieval capabilities. Married to mass storage technologies now reaching the microcomputer market, it offers an intriguing method of organizing and analyzing text on a large scale. The promise of large bodies of text for scholarly use on WordCruncher only adds potential to this impressive product. (Olsen 260)</p> <p><em>NOTE:</em> WordCruncher has been in active development since the 1980s. The current version is maintained by Brigham Young University and now includes four separate tools. It is freely available for download from <a href=\"http://www.wordcruncher.com\">http://www.wordcruncher.com</a></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Olsen, Mark. \"Software Review: Textbase for Humanities Applications: WordCruncher.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 21.4 (1987): 255-260. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30207396\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-18 21:30:41', created_at: '2013-10-22 18:59:42', )
Comment.create(id: '1353', tool_id: '223', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>SELECT was a tool for multivariate reduction (MVR), a method of factor or cluster analysis of text, developed by Howard P. Iker in the 1970s (Iker, \"Statistical Results\" 131). </p> <p>SELECT emerged from the development of Iker\'s WORDS system, which could not include an effective MVR function due to its intensive computational demands (313). WORD also didn\'t include synonymization as it was too difficult to implement, required too much processing time, and imposed a need for the very a priori categorization systems WORDS was intended to avoid (Iker, \"Statistical Results\" 313).</p> <p>The multivariate reduction technique that became SELECT was originally intended for WORDS, but Iker and his colleagues found that \"the technique has implications for any attempt to determine word groupings that uses word contiguities for primary data\" (Iker, \"Substantive Results\" 3). It addressed a gap in WORDS\' processing by selecting the words within a text with the highest correlation sums for inclusion in an Inter-Correlational Matrix (ICM) and MVR analysis (Iker, \"Statistical Results\" 315). The name SELECT derived from its method, which \"is to <em>S</em>um and <em>E</em>valuate the <em>L</em>argest <em>E</em>xponentiated <em>C</em>orrelation <em>T</em>erms from the ICM\" (315). </p> <p>SELECT used statistics to determine word correlations within a text, relying on linguistic redundancy to accomplish its MVR analysis (3):</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">In brief, a computer program, SELECT, is applied to all word types remaining after removal of function words and lemmatization. SELECT works (1) by computing the absolute correlation between a pair of words, (2) setting the correlation to zero if it is statistically nonsignificant, (3) exponentiating the correlation in order to emphasize high coefficients, (4) adding this value to sum cells corresponding to the two words correlated, and (5) continuing this procedure until all possible pairwise word combinations have been examined. On completion, the 215 highest \"correlating\" words (the largest number of variables currently used in the WORDS System) are selected for MVR analysis. This method is under study as an alternative to choosing for analysis the 215 highest frequency words - regardless of their associational structure. (Iker, \"Substantive Results\" 3)</p> <p>The design of SELECT was intended to improve the results possible with the MVR techniques used in WORDS, particularly its value to extracting themes from a text (3). With respect to linguistic redundancy, Iker judged that \"[i]f the same basic content materials can be identified by different words, then a procedure can be devised to maximize the identification, discrimination, richness, etc., of these themes by choosing \"better\" words without having to worry about losing those themes which would have been identified were the words different\" (3).</p> <p>In Iker\'s opinion, SELECT was successful within the context of WORDS for two reasons:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">(1) it allows a totally objective, associationally sensible, and reasonably efficient method for selecting the best word subset for analysis; (2) the words it does select afford a much better set of content themes for description of the data base under analysis. These themes are \"better\" because they are richer, more interpretable, and more easily discriminated from each other, and they constitute better descriptions of the data. (Iker, \"Substantive Results\" 319)</p> <p>When he overviewed SELECT\'s results, Iker found that they \"parallel those produced by frequency-based word selection,\" but were easier to interpret and distinguish than thematic results generated from frequency data (Iker, \"Statistical Results\" 12).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Iker, Howard P. \"SELECT: A Computer Program to Identify Associationally Rich Words for Content Analysis. I. Statistical Results.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. 8.5-6 (1974): 313-319. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199711\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Iker, Howard P. \"SELECT: A Computer Program to Identify Associationally Rich Words for Content Analysis. II. Substantive Results.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. 9.1 (1975): 3-12. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199732\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-30 20:49:25', created_at: '2013-10-30 20:47:54', )
Comment.create(id: '1354', tool_id: '356', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Welkin is a free open source graph &ndash; based RDF visualizer created by the SIMILE project and originally written by Stefano Mazzocchi&nbsp;and Paolo Ciccarese. Welkin serves as a \"telescope\" for the RDF data. It lets you understand global shape and cluster characteristics of the data rather than just a single RDF statement. It allows not only graphical representation of subject, object and predicate, but also more interactive exploration of the graph.</p> <p>The program caters to data and metadata analysts who need to see connectivity within a particular dataset within the whole. Generally speaking Welkin helps analysts to get the mental model of a dataset. The options for manipulation with RDF data visualization are available. Welkin offers different functions for the work with predicates, resources and charts. To be more specific the program shows each predicate contained in the loaded RDF model and grouped by their URI common prefixes and tokens as well as two widgets associated with each of them. &nbsp;</p> <p>Welkin is fast with immediate interactivity. Welkin&rsquo;s developers position interactivity as a crucial component for understanding complex data models. In its developers&rsquo; view it&rsquo;s much harder to do panning and zooming on statistically drawn graphs and that&rsquo;s why Welkin&rsquo;s interactivity is a definite advantage for analysts.</p> <p>Welkin&rsquo;s visualization represents RDF statements as dots and lines. With the effort to reduce clutter developers built visualization in a way that smaller dots represent objects while larger dots stand for those resources that were used at least once as a subject.&nbsp; Developers explain such visualization choice by the fact that &ldquo;object nodes are normally more numerous and, in the sense, that they are just referenced by the loaded model, as only&nbsp;<em>subject</em>&nbsp;nodes are actually described in the mode.&rdquo;</p> <p>Developers strive to achieve efficiency both in performance and visualization. Despite the fact that there can be two different predicates between the same resources Welkin displays only one of them in one line. As it mentions the website Welkin&rsquo;s team is currently designing the options to be able to display multiple predicates on the graph as well as allow mouseover &ndash; like effects to visualize the predicate values in the future. Although RDF models can be directed Welkin works with direction arrows of the predicates turned off to increase operational efficiency.</p> <p>Welkin\'s developers recommend running Welkin through Java WebStart (to install Java WebStart you&rsquo;ll need first to get the latest version of the Java Runtime Environment from the official website of Java). Omitting slightly complicated process of downloading and running the program in general Welkin has a good set of functions for metadata analysts working with complex data models. The possibility of working with multiple predicates makes this tool especially good.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-31 20:14:33', created_at: '2013-10-30 22:41:08', )
Comment.create(id: '1355', tool_id: '357', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>LodLive is an experimental project whose goal is to create a tool that could offer RDF browser connection capabilities with data graph representation. Working as an open source program under MIT license LodLive is available for use under the conditions of Creative Commons. Designed by a team of independent developers from Italy - Diego Valerio Camarda,&nbsp;Silvia Mazzini&nbsp;and&nbsp;Alessandro Antonuccio -&nbsp;the program is still in its developmental stage.</p> <p>LodLive is written mostly in JavaScript. The program\'s purpose is to advance the linked-open-data philosophy into the DH community. The program especially calls for data administrators and large data owners to add their resources to LodLive and share them. There are no specific strict technology requirements to run the program, all you need is internet connection and latest up-dated browsers.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>LodLive is the first navigator that uses RDF resources based solely on SPARQL endpoints. As a very user-friendly tool LodLive advocates for the linked-open-data philosophy and the effectiveness of data graph representation. LodLive consists of a jQuery plug-in (lodlive-core.js), a JSON configuration map (lodlive-profile.js), an HTML page, a few images (sprites), and some other jQuery public plug-ins. The program invites Public Administrations and large&ndash;scale data owners to share their resources on LOD. Although LodLive is still in its developmental stage the project already runs 2 big datasets which are dbpedia.org and freebase.com.</p> <p>After choosing the dataset and selecting the keyword, shows &nbsp;big circles surrounded by some smaller circles. You can browse the data by clicking any of the circles and can see the links to the page associated with the word of search. Trying to find something about Canada I came across this visualization:</p> <p>The big blue circle is the main endpoint offering links to other endpoints. By clicking one of the smaller blue circles this way, I moved myself to another end point &ndash; the big yellow circle again with smaller circles. You can see the elements of semantic web that help user to navigate through the associations and meanings in the search. From the term Canada I managed to come to Parliament of Canada and the program helped me to understand the meaning of it &ndash; location and meeting place. The next step was to know the associations LodLive built with Parliament of Canada. These connects were numerous and important point is that all those links and web page search results were in different languages. If you look at Canada bubble it&rsquo;s in English, Chinese, French, Russian, Italian etc.: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>In a very simple way users can find interesting data just searching by any particular key word. The funny thing is the search can work just the opposite way - starting from URI input and going deeper into keywords on the webpage of database.&nbsp; Despite the seeming ease of use LodLive is not that simple and superficial. It&rsquo;s not just about browsing the resources. You can see a bubble of Settings in each of the circles. This bubble open pane with features for user to work with the resources. Those features are Information on the resource; Focus on the resource; Access the online resource; Expand related resources and Remove this box. After playing with LodLive I can completely agree with the idea program creators advance for DH community &ndash; &ldquo;resources published by W3C standards for the semantic web can be made easily accessible and legible with a few viable tools.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s really easy to browse the web of data with LodLive.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-31 20:17:18', created_at: '2013-10-30 23:09:14', )
Comment.create(id: '1356', tool_id: '221', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>LEXICO was \"an interactive system which assists lexicographers in storing, editing, and concording texts; lemmatizing word lists; and generating slips\" developed in the 1970s by Richard L. Venezky of the University of Delaware and Nathan Relles and Lynne Price of the University of Wisconsin-Madison (Venezky, Relles and Price 127).</p> <p>The LEXICO system began development in the early 1970s (Venezky, Relles and Price 137). It was originally designed as research tool for exploring different computerized approaches for lexical processing, but as of 1977 had become a user system (Venezky, Relles and Price 127). It was installed at the Madison Academic Computing Center at the University of Wisconsin, and had been applied to projects such as a stylistic analysis of Modern French literature and text processing for the Dictionary of Old English (127). Its slips, analogous to file cards, were particularly useful for compiling dictionary entries as they encoded words with their lemma, context and information about their source (127). As a user-oriented system, LEXICO was intended to be accessible to users regardless of skill level, and to provide the appropriate level of assistance as needed (127).</p> <p>LEXICO was developed to run on mainframe and networked computers (Venezky, Relles and Price 136). Venezky, Relles and Price indicated, however, that if they were to start the project over again, they would include microcomputers for certain tasks (Venezky, Relles and Price 137). At the time of initial development, they found FORTRAN to be the only high-level programming language suitable for implementing it (Venezky, Relles and Price 136). As of 1977, LEXICO</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">requires a minimum of 100k of core storage, a remote terminal, and minimal random access, secondary storage...[t]he system consists of 20 separately executable subsystems (programs), composed of 285 distinct functional modules (subroutines). The entire system contains about 28,000 lines of code, 95% of which are FORTRAN, the remainder assembly language; this is equivalent to about 100,000 machine instructions. (136)</p> <p>The system was developed to meet six goals: A) The system should be unified with consistent methods of accomplishing tasks and responses to user requests; B) Users should not need to understand the computer\'s operating system, file formats and so forth to successfully complete their tasks; C) Users should be able to flexibly and easily to specify tasks in a manner that minimizes the potential for user error; D) The system should have default values that reduce the need for user declarations; E) The system should be easy to maintain with minimal additional programming; F) Design decision should take into account user cost and minimize its expense (Venezky, Relles and Price 127-128).</p> <p>As a system, LEXICO enabled users to process a text or collections of texts (Venezky, Relles and Price 128). A collection included a directory identifying and describing the text, some elements of which could be defined as defaults applying to all texts in the user\'s collection (128). Users specified tasks with LEXICO\'s command language, with keywords corresponding to the type of task and method of execution, in addition to a declared endpoint (128). They could also enter commands corresponding to user aids, such as explaining an error or question, viewing an example or viewing the system menu, which showed all commands permissible for the given task (Venezky, Relles and Price 128-129).</p> <p>To process a given collection, LEXICO required users to define a sequence of processes, which may include</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">1. creation of a collection and, optionally, definition of collection default values; 2. entry of one or more texts into the collection, optionally producing a listing of each text; 3. correction of errors in texts (editing); 4. concording texts; 5. formation of a headword classification (lemmatization) process for the collection by definition of spelling conversions and base form -- text form associations; 6. headword classification of the words that occur in texts, producing, for each text, a listing of the headword (base form) associated with each text form; 7. deletion of texts from the collection; and 8. deletion of the collection from the system (after all processing is complete). (Venezky, Relles and Price 128)</p> <p>Users interacted with the system from a remote terminal, from which some tasks could be completed on demand, while others were so processing intensive that they were performed externally at a computing center, requiring the user to add their job to a queue and retrieve printouts some time later (128).</p> <p>Venezky, Relles and Price compared LEXICO to its contemporaries. They noted that, while LEXICO shares concordance generation functionality with JEUDEMO, it could not match JEUDEMO\'s stylistic analysis capabilities, such as word-pattern searching (Venezky, Relles and Price 137). At the same time, JEUDEMO could not match LEXICO\'s collection management, spelling conversion or lemmatization (137). They also note that LEXICO had specialized lexicographic functions missing in EYEBALL, SCAN and RATS, but that they were better suited for phrase handling and grammatical parsing due to their origins in literary computing (137).</p> <p>Venezky\'s team was still gathering data on how well their design criteria had been met at the time of writing, though they had logged several hundred hours of user interactions (137). That said, they found that \"[t]he system permits a unique symbiosis of user and computer. Lemmatization...is too time-consuming to be achieved by human effort alone and too ill-defined to allow complete algorithmic specification\" (137).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Venezky, Richard L, Nathan Relles and Lynne Price. \"LEXICO: A System for Lexicographic Processing.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 11.3 (1977): 127-137. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199877\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-10-31 20:07:01', created_at: '2013-10-31 20:04:56', )
