Comment.create(id: '1358', tool_id: '122', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Cytoscape is a platform for network visualization and analysis. The latest version, Cytoscape 3.0.1, is the result of a long-running collaborative project involving numerous developers and funding agencies across the globe. The team of core developers resides mainly at the University of California and is funded by the US National Institute of General Medical Sciences and the National Resource for Network Biology.</p> <p>The program was first designed for bioinformatic systems, and many of the people involved in the project have background in biology. The key goals of the program are visualization of molecular interaction networks and biological pathways as well as integration of these networks with annotations, gene expression profiles and other state data. Cytoscape has been used to analyze data from a variety of fields beyond biomedical research, such as network analysis, the semantic web or the social sciences.Cytoscape is a Java application and runs on the Linux, Windows, and Mac OS X platforms. UNIX platforms such as Solaris and FreeBSD can run Cytoscape with Java version 5 or later. The program is available under the GNU Lesser General Public License.</p> <p>Cytoscape has numerous features, distributed for free through the Cytoscape App Store. Its latest version includes a flexible toolbar for quick access to common actions, new Data Table controls to interface with the data, integrated support for graphical annotations in networks, support for independent sets of networks within a single session, advanced network and table import controls, improved architecture and an API for a more stable experience. Cytoscape can be downloaded as an automatic installation package for Windows, Mac OS X, and Linux, or as a compressed archive. The source code is also available for download. It&rsquo;s important to notice that Cytoscape requires registration to download the program or the code.</p> <p>Cytoscape\'s strengths include its ability to support several languages for the data files including Eastern Asian languages using two-byte characters, English and many others. It also has a function that allows users to encode any attribute of their data (such as name, type, degree, weight or expression data) as a visual property (such as color, size, transparency, or font type). These encoded attributes together form a&nbsp;<strong>Visual Style</strong>&nbsp;that can be used to customize the visual appearance of the network. As a program with many rich functions it looks challenging, but thanks to a very clear and detailed online manual it ran quite smoothly afterwards. The manual on Cytoscape&rsquo;s website is really helpful in case you are either a newbie or guru in the network visualization. The manual gives detailed description of all the functions and capabilities of the program. It answered almost all the questions I had in the process of installation and running the program. &nbsp;</p> <p>To summarize the review of Cytoscape I&rsquo;d like to mention some more features that make the program really valuable for in depth visualization analysis. First of all it&rsquo;s flexibility of working with visualization. Visualizations are dynamic allowing users to interact with them. Additionally it&rsquo;s the ability to support import/export standard file formats. Also you can export networks as publishiable-quality images in PDF, PS, SVG, PNG, JPEG, and BMP files. &nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2014-02-18 18:47:44', created_at: '2013-11-08 18:04:38', )
Comment.create(id: '1359', tool_id: '374', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>For more information about the CMU-Cambridge Statistical Language Modelling Toolkit, please see the following paper by its creators:</p> <p>Clarkson, P. R. and R. Rosenfeld. \"Statistical Language Modeling Using the CMU-Cambridge Toolkit<em>.\"</em> <em>Proceedings of the ESCA Eurospeech</em>, 1997. <a href=\"http://svr-www.eng.cam.ac.uk/~prc14/eurospeech97.ps\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-05 20:28:32', created_at: '2013-12-05 20:26:20', )
Comment.create(id: '1360', tool_id: '317', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>PRORA was an early set of interconnected programs developed by Robert J. Glickman and Gerrit J. Staalman of the University of Toronto for creating concordances and word indexes with the assistance of a computer (Burton 139).</p> <p>It was written in FORTRAN IV, SPS and MAP (Burton 146) and required an IBM 026 Keypunch with a FORTRAN keyboard, chosen as the devices most commonly available in North American universities (Glickman 5). Its name derived from an abbreviation of Programs for Research on Romance Authors, but despite its original focus on texts in Romance languages, Glickman and Staalman stressed that PRORA was also applicable to texts in any language written in the Latin alphabet, such as Dutch, Czech or Finnish (1). For texts with characters not available on the FORTRAN keyboard, PRORA implemented special codes to accommodate them (Glickman 5). This included characters with diacritic marks, such as in Spanish and Italian texts (Glickman 7).</p> <p>PRORA emerged from the tension between the benefits and drawbacks of concording texts by computer (Glickman 1). Despite the clear speed advantages of computer versus manual concordance, the need for users to have special training in computer programming and techniques was a deterrent to humanities scholars, while the need to pre-edit their data for best results meant less time available for analyzing the output (1). Furthermore, the characters available on computers were limited, as computers of the time were designed with scientific rather than literary applications in mind (Glickman 2). Glickman and Staalman believed that \"intervention by the scholar should be limited to decision-making in the scholar\'s own field of competency\" (Glickman and Staalman 1), and as such, PRORA was designed to meet eight aims:</p> <ol> <li style=\"list-style-type: none;\"><ol> <li>To provide a complete set of computer programs that can be executed by a part-time production assistant without the scholar\'s intervention.</li> <li>To simplify encoding techniques so that it will be as easy to prepare literary texts for machine processing as it is to copy those texts on a typewriter.</li> <li>To print literary texts in such a way that they will contain all necessary upper- and lower-case characters, diacritics, punctuation marks, and special signs; and to produce those texts in formats that will meet the particular needs of their users.</li> <li>To reduce the overall size of concordances, while substantially increasing the amount of context around each concorded word.</li> <li>To enable concordence-users physically to change the order of contexts as often as they wish.</li> <li>To establish a set of post-editing routines that will eliminate the need for complex pre-editing of the corpus.</li> <li>To facilitate the creation, modification, and augmentation of a master reference file containing all words of research interest.</li> <li>To make it possible to compile various types of word-index and to print each index in upper- and lower-case form. (Glickman 4)</li> </ol></li> </ol> <p>Glickman and Staalman released their \"Manual for the Printing of Literary Texts and Concordances by Computer\" in 1966, describing PRORA\'s functions and use (Glickman and Staalman 1). At this time, PRORA consisted of three programs (Glickman and Staalman 2). PRORA I converted a tape stored on IBM punch cards to a record on tape, PRORA II used that tape record to print out the text in a \'standard\' format, and PRORA III printed the record in a \'special\' format optimized for concordance (2).</p> <p>PRORA III\'s special format included page numbers and coding information, namely index number, book, part and line number (Glickman and Staalman 9). It printed on cards that had to be placed in a specialized binder for browsing (Glickman and Staalman 13). To examine instances of a particular word, users had to consult the word index for the text, which required PRORA V to print, and manually pull out all the cards where the word appeared (Glickman and Staalman 15). </p> <p>PRORA IV-VI were projected, not available, at the time of the manual\'s publication (Lieberman 12). PRORA VI would \"to construct and update a master tape-file of all words appearing in a given text or group of texts\" (Glickman and Staalman 15). It would also include functions for adding lemma to each word, translations of a word in context, variants from other editions of the text, and for directly inserting analytical data (Glickman and Staalman 15-16). PRORA VI would also generate a Vertical List, compare words from the PRORA I tape to the Master Reference File, and print words according to the order of their appearance alongside their lemma and function (Glickman 17). PRORA V would be a means of retrieving and arranging information from PRORA IV\'s master tape, extending beyond generating word indexes into dictionaries and frequency lists (Glickman and Staalman 16). The index function used a version of PRORA\'s Vertical List that had been edited to include only those words of interest (Glickman 18). Finally, PRORA VI would generate a complete or partial concordance from the master tape (Glickman and Staalman 16). </p> <p>PRORA was favourably received by its audience. In 1966, David Lieberman reviewed the manual for Computers in the Humanities, with the final assessment that \"[t]his manual should be of great interest not only to a literary scholar interested in using the program described therein, but to anyone actively working with computer aids to literary text analysis\" (Lieberman 12). He particularly drew attention to the care with which Glickman and Staalman described the limitations of the system in relation to the available hardware, and why they implemented the solutions they did (12). The only drawback Lieberman noted was the lack of information on program runtimes (12).</p> <p>It was also still in discussion fifteen years later, appearing in Dolores M. Burton\'s 1981 article \"Automated Concordances and Word Indexes: The Process, The Programs, and the Products.\" Burton found PRORA notable for \"its clarity and its humanistic orientation\" (Burton 146). </p> <p>In light of Lieberman and Burton\'s assessments, PRORA was successful at smoothing the path of scholars wishing to create computer-assisted concordances, and as a fulfilment of Glickman and Staalman\'s aim of providing</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a series of computer programs designed primarily for scholars who work in the fields of literature and linguistics; who have little or no knowledge of how computers operate, but who would utilize computer technology if it were possible to do so without sacrificing their own research time in order to learn the details of computer science. (Glickman and Staalman 1).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Burton, Dolores M. \"Automated Concordances and Word Indexes: The Process, The Programs, and the Products.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 15.3 (1981): 139-154. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007%2FBF02404180.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <div class=\"comment-desc\"> <p>Glickman, Robert Jay. \"An Integrated Series of Computer Programs for Literary Research.<em>\" MLA, Conference 16</em>, 27 Dec. 1965.</p> <p>Glickman, Robert Jay and Gerrit Joseph Staalman. <em>Manual for the Printing of Literary Texts and Concordances by Computer: Preliminary Edition</em>. Toronto: University of Toronto Press (1966).</p> <p>Lieberman, David. \"Reviews.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 1.1 (1966): 12. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00188014\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> </div>', updated_at: '2013-12-19 23:44:55', created_at: '2013-12-19 23:42:48', )
Comment.create(id: '1361', tool_id: '364', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Visual Browser is a free tool developed by Masaryk University Natural Language Processing Centre with the goal to visualize the data in RDF scheme. The software is provided under NLP Centre Web Services Licence and GNU GPL Licence version 2. One can download the source codes after requesting the password from Masaryk University representative.</p> <p>Visual Browser can be operated very easily in Java command line. Important note to keep in mind is that it requires Jena framework to obtain the data. Developers explain that this integration gives possibility for saving RDF in various formats, for instance XML file or relational database. Besides packaged version there is Visual Browser Mini that works as a Java Applet directly from the web browser. A very useful feature of the tool is an option to load own data from file, a database (MySQL and Postgre SQL) or an URL. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> <p>The tool&rsquo;s visualization uses the methods of animated expansions. Users can expand and hide nodes, switch the view of edges. Visual Browser&rsquo;s visualization engine is powered by TouchGraph LLC and supports navigation approach of WebOFDAV. The user interface is pretty simple which makes it very easy to work with visualization. Such functions available within the user interface as View the labels, history and clue make Visual Browser a good tool for getting statistics about the data, for example by clicking Display clue one can see many important characteristics of the data &ndash; the form of the word, its functions, the literal, involved agent etc.&nbsp; The graphs provided by Visual Browser are animated containing the fixed points (nodes) and elastic connections (edges). This feature is good in case a user wants to focus on a specific part of the network or research a particular issue in the context of the whole data.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-20 19:29:35', created_at: '2013-12-20 19:29:35', )
Comment.create(id: '1362', tool_id: '360', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Prefuse was developed by University of California Berkeley\'s Visualization Lab to facilitate the visual representation of data through spatial position, size, shape, color and other visual features. The software package is available for free and works under the terms of a BSD (Berkeley Standard Distribution) license. So far Prefuse got a wide use in the academic and industrial research, software development as well as school projects.&nbsp;</p> <p>Prefuse is operated in an integrated development environment Eclipse using Java programming language with some features of 2D computer graphics. The set of functions for interaction with data is quite rich. The data structures that Prefuse supports are tables, graphs and trees. The visualization nature of Prefuse is very dynamic and includes numerous possible operations with data including support for queries to SQL databases. But the zest of Prefuse is in its interactive filtering of data, view transformation and animation. In the user interface of final visualization one can choose the proper view of its data based on such parameters as connectivity filter with a possibility to set distance among nodes and edges, a degree of force simulation for dynamic layout and animation of the data. Prefuse seems to be a very convenient tool in case one wants to play with different visual forms of the data, for instance the tree structure of the data can be divided into balanced tree or diamond tree.</p> <p>Although Prefuse user interface seems to be pretty easy the successful work with the program requires substantial knowledge of Eclipse, otherwise it can be hard to get the best performance results out of the program. The software seems to be a really good one in terms of visual abstraction. But as the program does the biggest part of your work it doesn&rsquo;t seem to provide a big room for the visual fantasy of the user. The animation is really strong, sometimes to the point of annoyance when you need to struggle with non stop moving spots on the screen of your visualization. Such visual components as layout parameters, color, size, distortion and animation add value to Prefuse as a good program for data visualization. Another feature such as text search support for prefix, keyword, and regular expression helps for better orientation within the text. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-20 19:32:05', created_at: '2013-12-20 19:32:05', )
Comment.create(id: '1363', tool_id: '363', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>RDF Gravity was developed by Salzburg Research, Knowledge Information Systems Group, Austria. The main purpose of the tool is to provide visualization of RDF/OWL graphs and ontologies. The software is available free of charge under the license of Salzburg Research Forschungsgesellschaft mbH.<br /> <br /> RDF Gravity was developed by using the JUNG Graph API and Jena semantic web toolkit. In addition to the resilient graph user interface there is a big variety of functions for customizable graph views. Graph filtering seemed to me one of the most notable features as it allows a lot of flexibility in working with data visualization. Local and Global filter panels make visualization easily manageable. For instance Global Filters can give more generic view of the data. By selecting &ldquo;subClassOf&rdquo; one can see that the detailed edge relations visible before were automatically hidden. It&rsquo;s possible to manipulate the graph in a reverse manner to focus on more specific description of edges and concepts. The availability of such filters makes data visualization very flexible to work with. In addition to applying different filters there is another helpful feature &ndash; a good selection of nodes to be displayed.&nbsp;</p> <p>Despite user&ndash;friendliness of RDF Gravity there are some pitfalls in running the program. The program can be opened with \'Java Web Start\' and seems to load everything but then won\'t launch the app due to some unsigned entry issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-20 19:34:30', created_at: '2013-12-20 19:34:30', )
Comment.create(id: '1364', tool_id: '366', user_id: '72', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>RelFinder is part of the Visual DataWeb family. The tool enables users to track relationships between given objects in the interactive visualization. RelFinder supports any RDF datasets, provides SPARQL access and operates within open source framework Adobe Flex. The user audience of the tool is quite variable starting from data analysts in such humanities spheres like history, language studies as well as non-humanities areas like biomedical research and others. The tool is web &ndash; based, hosted on Google Code and available under GNU General Public License.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>Like any other tool of Visual DataWeb set RelFinder works with minimal technical requirements and offers intuitive user interface. The integrated datasets of the tool include DBpedia, LinkedMDB, Linked Movie database, Linking Open Data (LOD) and Semantic Web Dog Food. All of them can be easily found and linked to through the user interface in the Settings. It&rsquo;s good to note that successful running of RelFinder, especially if you want to extract data from DBpedia requires Flash Player to be installed in your browser. The tool can be really helpful for those working with knowledge bases and willing to understand the relationships between any objects of interest. A good point in favor of RelFinder that you can make input of any kind of object you are interested in. For example I made a query of Alberta and British Columbia. Visualization of the relationships between objects works pretty smoothly and quickly. A very useful feature of the user interface is its presentation area. The biggest part of the interface is devoted to the visualization representation for the purpose of better readability. According to the developers there are certain principles put into visualization mechanisms to make it specially user &ndash; friendly. The subject &ndash; predicate &ndash; object schema allows user to see the relationships of the objects on the micro and macro levels simultaneously. User &ndash; given objects serve as starting nodes in the graph, the links between the objects further turn into labeled and directed edges. Pointing at any particular word on the graph lets user analyze details of any single object while the sidebar lets user work with more generic picture of the connection. In my visualization of Alberta/British Columbia one can see the connectivity level 2 in the sidebar. Other information provided is the link and class categories of the relationships. For example many people in Alberta and BC are connected by their places of birth or involvement in any particular organization, e.g. OfficeHolder or IceHockeyPlayer.</p> <p>Despite user &ndash; friendliness of the tool there can be some errors in the work of the program as RelFinder is still a research prototype - the developers warn. In my view the absence of an option to save the visualization as a file is a light drawback of the tool. Although the possibility to save the link is present and seriously saves time in case you want to get back to your visualization in the future. Visualization features are very strong. One more good feature of RelFinder is its rich selection of languages in its user interface. You can choose the language for the objects and its description in the sidebar, then the dataset will turn on the description or an object in your desired language. &nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-20 22:20:09', created_at: '2013-12-20 22:20:09', )
Comment.create(id: '1365', tool_id: '250', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>The General Inquirer was a program for processing natural language text with a focus on content analysis from Philip Stone and his colleagues at Harvard University (Rice 332). It was developed in the 1960s at the Harvard Laboratory of Social Relations, and as late as 1984, Robert Oakman described it as a \"pioneering computer application\" for its capacity to automate the process of applying preset categories to the words of a text from a dictionary such as the Harvard Psychosocial Dictionary (Oakman 150). </p> <p>The General Inquirer lemmatized each word, assigned content tags, performed graphical and statistical analysis, and produced a report containing sentences with significant content words (Oakman 151). Oakman, reflecting back, noted that it was most useful to the social sciences as \"with literary texts, its usage has been minimal and the results often disappointing\" (151).</p> <p>In the manual released in 1966, <em>The General Inquirer: A Computer Approach to Content Analysis</em>, the developers described the system as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a set of computer programs to (a) identify systematically, within text, instances of words and phrases that belong to categories specified by the investigator; (b) count occurrences and specified co-occurrences of these categories; (c) print and graph tabulations; (d) perform statistical tests; (e) sort and regroup sentences according to whether they contain instances of a particular category of combination of categories. (Stone et al 68).</p> <p>The General Inquirer\'s applications and value was a subject of debate amongst researchers seeking computer automation within the Humanities. The journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> published a review symposium focused on the General Inquirer as an aid to literary analysis in 1968 (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 177). All three reviewers criticized the system for its reliance on dictionaries for categorizing words. Charles Kadushin found that, due to the dictionaries, \"[t]he Inquirer is indeed limited to small-unit coding, in either broad or narrow contexts. That it does its coding by means of single words, even in contexts, is its major drawback as well as its chief virtue\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 180). He concluded that, with respect to categorizing words, &nbsp;\"making do with general dictionaries or a slight modification of them leads, in many cases, to almost unbearable intellectual costs\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 182).</p> <p>Joseph Lovett criticized the General Inquirer, and its manual, sharply. In his view, \"[t]he pitfall of these chapters [on content analysis] lies in the biases of the authors, for these biases of the General Inquirer approach influence its implementation in any specific research problem\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 184). He disliked the emphasis on procedural, rules-based content analysis, and the system\'s inability to handle homographs (184). With respect to homographs, he regarded the challenges with them as a shortfall of the developers as much as the program itself:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">That homographs would be confused more by the computer than by a human coder is admitted by the authors. They view the problem as one of category consistency, however, not of coder reliability. It seems unclear, if \'river bank\' and \'savings bank\' are assigned by the computer to the same category, why the researcher is to blame. (184)</p> <p>Like Kadushin, Lovett identified the dictionary as the root of the General Inquirer\'s shortfalls, finding that \"[t]he burden of proof of the General Inquirer...is on the method and logic by which the descriptors are conceived to bring about the many-to-few mapping, i.e., the dictionary of the program\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 185).</p> <p>James Merriman provided the final assessment of the roundtable. In his view, computers had proved their value with automatic data processing, and that the General Inquirer was a welcome attempt to extend the usefulness of computers by leveraging them to tease meaning from literature (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 187). For him, the General Inquirer\'s use of dictionaries for categorizations was the \"real novelty of the approach, and it is precisely the difficulties of \'dictionary\' construction that raise major doubts about the present and perhaps even future utility of the General Inquirer to literary studies\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 189). He criticized the challenges of selecting and constructing categories through dictionaries (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 191) and the Harvard Third Psychosocial Dictionary in particular as problematic when used for Humanities applications (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 192). However, Merriman judged the suggestion that users construct dictionaries tailored to texts unrealistic and representative of \"abandoning the General Inquirer\" (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 200). Rather, he suggested that \"[t]he hope for fully automatic preparation of texts...will almost certainly have to be abandoned in favor of extensive manual pre-editing\" (200). Whether a universal dictionary was a realistic outcome, Merriman called for researchers to work on creating better dictionaries, and a better solution for creating categories and category systems (Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman 201).</p> <p>George Psanthas disagreed with Kadushin, Lovett and Merriman\'s criticisms, and contributed a rebuttal to <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> in 1969 for the purpose of dispelling misconceptions about the General Inquirer (GI) and its value to Humanities research applications. In his view,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Many criticisms of the GI, based on the description of the system and its uses by Stone <em>et al</em>., can be shown to be inappropriate, since they are based on a misunderstanding of the system and the failure to make certain basic distinctions among hardware, software, dictionary construction, data preparation and input, data analysis, and inferences from data analysis...[m]uch work needs to be done to improve the GI but it does offer possibilities for use in literary and content analysis, as well as other application. (Psanthas 163)</p> <p>He stressed that the dictionaries were distinct from the General Inquirer as a system, and that any dictionary may be used, not just the Harvard Third Psychosocial Dictionary (Psanthas 164). Psanthas described the General Inquirer as \"a system that can be used for making classifications of words (idioms), or sentences and need not be used for content analysis in the traditional sense of the word\" (164). He noted that it offered a classification/tagging system for words and sentences, with \'word\' being better defined as \'string\', and \'sentence\' as \"any string of words marked by a beginning and end marker\" such as a space or punctuation mark (164).</p> <p>With respect to criticism of the General Inquirer\'s capacity to classify words, Psanthas found that if a scholar\'s classifications were not programmable into the General Inquirer, they were butting up against the limitations of the software and/or hardware, and their own understanding of what computers can\'t do yet (Psanthas 168). It was his view that, \"in all honesty, it must be stated that all of our desires for a completely automated system of classification still remain dreams\" (168). Like Merriman, Psanthas called for scholars to focus on creating better dictionaries as the solution to categorization problems (Psanthas 169), but added that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[i]f there is an inherent set of limitations built into the dictionary approach to the classification of natural language, it is simply that at this time we do not have enough knowledge to enable us to use the computer to automatically and correctly classify words, idioms, or even whole sentences into a clearly defined category...[t]he search for better methods for analyzing language is of more proper concern. (169)</p> <p>Psanthas criticized the General Inquirer for its reliance on statistics, and suggested that new models of peering into a text were required (Psanthas 172). He also cited the labour of keypunching a text, and the limited symbols available, as a drawback (172), in addition to the challenges of pre-editing texts by hand (Psanthas 173).</p> <p>Despite its shortcomings, the General Inquirer remained in use into the 1980s, though even in 1984 Robert Oakman noted that the system was only as good as the content categories of the dictionary it drew from (Oakman 151). It saw continued development, including adaptation, as with the INQUIRER III (Edinburgh Version) reviewed by Sandra Rice in 1976 (Rice 332). The Edinburgh Version retained a reliance on punched card input and a preset dictionary (332). Rice found the supplementary job control cards \"difficult to prepare and comprehend for the user not conversant with IBM OS system [sic],\" while the program itself was poorly commented and required precise input to receive comprehensible results (332).</p> <p>Rice and Oakman\'s interest in the General Inquirer well after its initial release demonstrates the long term impact of its approach to automating the analysis of natural language text. Notably, its shortcomings prompted other researchers to develop their own programs to accomplish similar tasks, as Howard P. Iker cited the General Inquirer\'s reliance on dictionaries as the spur for the WORDS system, which used the text at hand to isolate words instead (Oakman 152).</p> <p>Amongst Humanities researchers interested in applying computers within their scholarly practices, conversations surrounding the General Inquirer were characterized by ambivalence due to the tension between its potential and individual scholars\' experiences of its shortcomings. Psanthas, though an advocate for the system and its manual, nevertheless concluded that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">the book was unduly optimistic in proposing that the system could be applied fairly easily and quickly to a variety of problems....Unless the investigator is willing to make a long-term commitment to research with computers, the use of the General Inquirer system is not to be recommended at this time....For those who wish to focus their research on computer program development for natural language processing, the General Inquirer already provides a reality; for those who wish substantive results by applying a \"ready-made\" system, <em>caveat emptor</em>. (Psanthas 174)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Kadushin, Charles, Joseph Lovett and James D. Merriman. \"Literary Analysis with the Aid of the Computer.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 2.4 (1968): 177-202. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02402487\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p> <p>Psathas, George. \"The General Inquirer: Useful or Not?\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 3.3 (1969): 163-174. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02401609\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Rice, Sandra. \"Software Review: INQUIRER III (Edinburgh Edition) A Computer Based System for Content Analysis.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.6 (1976): 332. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007%2FBF02402556.pdf\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Stone, Philip J., Dexter C. Dunphy, Marshall S. Smith and Daniel M. Ogilvie. <em>The General Inquirer: A Computer Approach to Content Analysis</em>. Cambridge: MIT Press, 1966.</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-30 20:53:33', created_at: '2013-12-30 20:50:04', )
Comment.create(id: '1366', tool_id: '275', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>PL/I (Programming Language/One) is an early programming language developed by IBM for their 360/370 machines (Oakman 155). It was a multipurpose language adaptable for business analysis, scientific data processing and character handling (155), and could handle data stored on magnetic tape or on disks (Heller and Logemann 24). It was commonly available due to both wide adoption of IBM\'s equipment, and other companies like Honeywell and General Electric followed IBM\'s lead in making the language available on their machines (Oakman 155).</p> <p>PL/I was commonly used for natural language processing within the Humanities, second only to FORTRAN for language processing applications due to its wide availability (Joyce 271). By 1972, PL/I was used on 40% of such projects, with FORTRAN coming in at 50% (271), and scholar James Joyce considered PL/I the better suited of the two languages as it accommodated business data in its design, rather than the strictly formula-oriented scientific bent of FORTRAN (271).</p> <p>In their 1966 article \"PL/I: A Programming Language for Humanities Research,\" Jack Heller and George Logemann described PL/I as \"ideally suited for writing interpreters for problem-oriented language\" (Heller and Logemann 20). They also found PL/I appealing as it was versatile and compact, making it possible to focus on reducing the labour cost of writing programs and the potential for human error (20). The language combined arithmetic and data manipulative facilities, which enabled researchers to use it for both numeric and string data (20). In addition, its control language was compact, and \"permit[ted] both free-form as well as rigid, fixed field format\" for passing results to and from the computer (20). In Heller and Logemann\'s view, PL/I was particularly important to the Humanities because</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Humanities programmers are concerned primarily with symbolic data as opposed to numbers. They wish to manipulate sentences and texts, or strings of their own notations...We observe that PL/I allows data to take the form of strings of symbols. Thus in a PL/I program one can generate any desired text or coding schemes, and move and save strings for accumulating dictionaries and preparing output text. Moreover, PL/I provides the essential minimum of operations on strings of symbols. (Heller and Logemann 21)</p> <p>This includes functions like concatenation, specifying a substring, finding a string\'s length, or searching a string for a substring (21). PL/I also included the ability to run loops, a capacity useful for iterating through texts or specifying conditions under which a program will execute particular operations and end them (Heller and Logemann 24). Its functions enabled users to build programs for complex text manipulation and retrieval (Heller and Logemann 23). In Heller and Logemann\'s view, this made PL/I particularly important to Humanities programmers who</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">need the ability to split, scan, measure, compare, and join strings in practically all of their computer efforts: the simple problem of right-justifying a line, filling in blanks between words so that the total line length fills the width of the column, takes all four manipulative operations. Editing a text requires many search and split operations; alphabetization is essential in making an index or concordance. Finally, complex pattern-matching problems that arise in musical or graphic art analysis definitely require the facility to recognize substrings and to move elements of data. (Heller and Logemann 22)</p> <p>Where string data was concerned, PL/I used a combination of two functions, INDEX and SUBSTR (\'substring\'), for pattern matching (Oakman 56). It assigned a numerical position to particular characters, and, to search a string, \"the function INDEX moves through LINE, counting the positions until it gets to the first space\" (56). &nbsp;However, it required additional code to examine text at the word level, such as custom extensions (Joyce 271). These extensions enabled important text handling functions such as recognizing apostrophes as letters so contractions can be identified as words, defining hyphens as punctuation so hyphenated words can be recognized separately, converting strings to upper or lower case, finding words within a string, or reversing character order in a string (Joyce 272). Joyce wrote a number of extensions to \"produce fast code with a minimal strain on the user,\" though he took care to state that his extensions \"do not pretend to represent an optimal set of extensions...[r]ather, they are to me some obviously needed extensions that make PL/I more docile for those wishing to do natural-language processing\" (Joyce 271).</p> <p>Thanks to its wide availability and text handling capabilities, Heller and Logemann advocated for Humanities scholars to adopt PL/I as \"a powerful, versatile programming language designed to handle contemporary problems on contemporary machines. PL/I is not guaranteed to solve all problems, but it certainly will facilitate the scholars\' search\" (Heller and Logemann 27). Indeed, PL/I was discussed as late as 1984 as a significant multipurpose language for text handling (Oakman 50).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Heller, Jack and George W. Logemann. \"PL/I: A Programming Language for Humanities Research.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 1.2 (1966): 19-27. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199201\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Joyce, James. \"Extension to PL/I For Natural-Language Processing.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 6.5 (1972): 271-276. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199499\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p>', updated_at: '2013-12-31 20:15:08', created_at: '2013-12-31 20:13:41', )
Comment.create(id: '1367', tool_id: '319', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>CLAS (Computerized Language Analysis System) was a software package for text analysis that combined standard statistical tests with concordance functions (Oakman 179). It was developed by George Borden and James Watts of Pennsylvania State University (Borden and Watts 129) and ran in PL/I on IBM 360/370 machines (Borden and Watts 136).</p> <p>In their 1971 paper \"A Computerized Language System,\" Borden and Watts described CLAS as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a general-purpose computer system that can perform standard statistical tests on natural language texts as well as print a concordance or index of all the words of that text or a specified subset of those words. It was developed from a simple concordance generating program on the belief that since the computer had already separated the text into its constituent words, it might as well do some statistical and semantic operation on this text to aid the scholar in his research. (Borden and Watts 129)</p> <p>CLAS required the text to be keypunched on punch cards, which it used to generate an index and generate statistical data such as word counts, or numbers of lines, sentences and punctuation marks (Oakman 179). It could also generate mean word and sentence lengths with standard deviations (179). Borden and Watts found the statistical output particularly useful, as \"[t]his allows one to accumulate a bank of statistical data for natural language analysis\" (Borden and Watts 132).</p> <p>The system was designed to work with natural language text with standard spacing and punctuation, though it required users to manually keypunch a variable length identifier at the beginning of each line (Borden and Watts 129). This identifier was used to locate words out of context (Borden and Watts 130). Users could generate concordances and indexes for either the full text or a specified subset (Borden and Watts 130-131). The subsets were specified via word lists for exclusion or inclusion (Borden and Watts 131), or via a word frequency cap that caused the system to only index or concord those words falling below that frequency (Borden and Watts 132).</p> <p>Particularly notably, CLAS could recognize statements ending in a period as sentences, and colons and semi-colons as in-sentence delimiters for determining \'verbal segments\' (132). Colons and semi-colons were not the only markers of verbal segments. Rather, \"[a] verbal segment is considered to be that linguistic string falling between any two segment delimiters, i.e., (;) (:) (,) (--) (...) (?) (.) (!)\" (132). CLAS generated counts for each of these markers and included them in its statistics (132).</p> <p>Various statistics could be output in bar graph form, showing information such as frequency distributions, type/token ratios, or the number of word types in relation to the total counts for the text (Oakman 179-180). Beyond graphs, the system could generate a</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">detailed statistical analysis of vocabulary types and tokens. This option causes the system to divide the text into a number of equal length linguistic strings (the length of the string is specified by the user: defaults to 100 words). This series of linguistic strings then becomes the basis for a series of type/token analyses. (Borden and Watts 134)</p> <p>For thematic analysis, the system could also generate printouts of particular words based on a selected text division (Borden and Watts 135).</p> <p>To run, CLAS required 240 bytes of external storage per word in the text to be processed, and the developers recommended that external storage be sequential in disk, drum or magnetic tape form (Borden and Watts 136). Punch cards and paper tape was also supported, but not recommended (136). The system\'s input was governed by a parameter card that specified the text to be processed, the name of the job and what program options to use (Borden and Watts 137). As a whole, CLAS consisted of six programs, being a main monitor program governing order of execution, and five subprograms performing specific functions on the user\'s text (Borden and Watts 136-137). The subprograms, named according to their purpose, were Initialization, Word-Break-Up, Concordance/Index, Decreasing Word Frequency, and Increasing Word Length (Borden and Watts 137).</p> <p>CLAS was designed to allow users to run large batch jobs and provide feedback if the process stopped prematurely (Borden and Watts 138). In the case of an error, jobs could be restarted from the middle (Borden and Watts 139). Borden and Watts considered this restart function its most powerful feature:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">When execution must be terminated due to a recoverable error or from a lack of time or records, the monitor will halt execution and note where it stopped so that the system can be restarted. The restart capability is especially useful under a system which limits the amount of time and records a user can run at any one time. The restart capability allows the maximum amount of data to be run. (Borden and Watts 140)</p> <p>In terms of speed, Borden and Watts found CLAS took approximately 100 seconds when tested with a 1000-word text using all phases of the program on an IBM 360/67, and found that the larger the text, as with a batch job, the less time per word the system required (Borden and Watts 141).</p> <p>In addition to the benefits of CLAS\' speed and batch processing capacity, Borden and Watts provided a means for users to modify the system\'s built-in collating sequence, which opened up CLAS to languages beyond English (141). This facility with other languages proved valuable to its audience, enabling text analysis studies such as Franklin Waltman\'s 1976 authorship study of the medieval Spanish epic poem <em>Cantar de Mio Cid</em>, described in his paper \"C.L.A.S. and the Cantar de Mio Cid\" (Waltman 145). He focused on CLAS\' concordance function to examine the text for formulas and formulaic expressions (145). In particular, he made use of a new feature, \"[a] theme segment analysis [which] has recently been added to C.L.A.S. This provides a concordance, statistical data, and theme density maps for analysis of particular themes\" (Waltman 146).</p> <p>Waltman\'s final assessment of CLAS was favourable:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The use of the C.L.A.S. has permitted an analysis which indicates that there are no great differences among the three <em>cantares</em> of the poem, nor any statistical evidence which can be considered conclusive proof that two poets had a hand in composing the poem as it exists today. C.L.A.S. has been an extremely valuable tool in this research. (Waltman 146)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Borden, George A. and James J. Watts. \"A Computerized Language Analysis System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 5.3 (1971): 129-141. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199396\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p> <p>Waltman, Franklin M. \"C.L.A.S. and the Cantar de Mio Cid.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.3 (1976): 145-152. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/i30204250\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-03 20:17:11', created_at: '2014-01-03 20:14:08', )
Comment.create(id: '1368', tool_id: '51', user_id: '166', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: 'Deepika Padukone (born 1986) is an Indian film actress and model. She has established a successful career in Hindi (Bollywood) films, and is cited in the media as one of the most popular and attractive Indian celebrities. She made her acting debut in 2006 as the titular character of the Kannada film Aishwarya. She then played dual roles in her first Bollywood release—the 2007 blockbuster Om Shanti Om—and won a Filmfare Award for Best Female Debut. Padukone received praise for portraying the lead female role in the 2009 romance Love Aaj Kal, but her performances in the 2008 romantic comedy Bachna Ae Haseeno and the 2010 comedy Housefull met with negative reviews. The 2012 box office hit Cocktail marked a significant turning point in her career, earning her critical acclaim and Best Actress nominations at several award ceremonies. In 2013, Padukone established herself as a leading actress of Hindi cinema by playing primary roles in the comedies Yeh Jawaani Hai Deewani and Chennai Express (both of which rank among the highest-grossing Bollywood films of all time), and garnered critical acclaim for her role in the tragic romance Goliyon Ki Raasleela Ram-Leela. (Full article...) Recently featured: \"Weight Gain 4000\" – False potto – Gagak Item', updated_at: '2014-01-07 19:15:42', created_at: '2014-01-05 19:05:40', )
