Comment.create(id: '1370', tool_id: '388', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>More information about JEUDEMO is available via two articlesf from its creators:</p> <p>Bratley, Paul, Serge Lusignan and Francine Ouellette. \"JEUDEMO: A Text-Handling System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. Ed. J. L. Mitchell. Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1974. 234-239.</p> <p>Bratley, Paul, Serge Lusignan and Francine Ouellette. \"JEUDEMO, A Package for Scholars in the Humanities.\" <em>SIGLASH Newsletter</em> 7.3 (1974): 15-19.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-06 17:59:04', created_at: '2014-01-06 17:46:15', )
Comment.create(id: '1371', tool_id: '388', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong> </p> <p>JEUDEMO was an information retrieval program for text building on COCOA developed at the University of Montreal by Paul Bratley, Serge Lusignan and Francine Ouellette in the 1970s (Oakman 178).</p> <p>It combined the functions of COCOA with Boolean search capabilities to locate co-occurrences and other patterns:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The user first defines his on hierarchies of text--word, sentence, paragraph, chapter, etc. Then, using its pattern-searching features, JEUDEMO can look for two words, like \"boy\" and \"dog,\" occurring in the same sentence, in the same paragraph, or within ten words from each other in the whole text. (Oakman 179)</p> <p>JEUDEMO required text to be in punched card or Flexowriter paper tape format (Oakman 178). Its commands were developed with inexperienced programmers, with the aim of making the program accessible to Humanists without computer backgrounds, and an interactive version was planned (178).</p> <p>However, JEUDEMO had a prohibitive drawback, as the developers chose to program it in a system-exclusive language that limited its audience to only those scholars with access to a CDC Cyber 74 system (Oakman 179). Robert Oakman found this requirement to be a major barrier to the program\'s wide adoption (179).</p> <p>JEUDEMO was nevertheless a notable contribution to text analysis, as Oakman found that \"[c]ompared to COCOA, its forerunner, JEUDEMO offers attractive additional features and a few easy commands that humanists can learn to use quickly\" (179).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-06 18:00:16', created_at: '2014-01-06 17:59:25', )
Comment.create(id: '1372', tool_id: '389', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>For more information about RATS, see John B. Smith\'s paper:</p> <p>Smith, John B. \"RATS: A Mid-Level Text Utility System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 6.5 (1972): 277-283. <a href=\"http://download.springer.com/static/pdf/538/art%253A10.1007%252FBF02404244.pdf?auth66=1389205134_9c45fcce7c893dc1254bf53245b58f45&amp;ext=.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>. </p>', updated_at: '2014-01-10 16:19:54', created_at: '2014-01-07 19:09:43', )
Comment.create(id: '1373', tool_id: '389', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>RATS (Random-Accessible Text Systems) was a PL/I utility \"for the researcher with some knowledge of programming\" developed by John B. Smith of Pennsylvania State University in the early 1970s (Smith 277).</p> <p>Smith designed RATS to allow researchers to skip over file creation and proceed directly to text analysis (277). As an analysis tool, it aimed to provide \"a highly flexible representation of a text, allowing the researcher to write specific programs to perform the exact analysis he desires\" (277).</p> <p>It integrated the INDEX program from VIA-II, developed by S. Y. Sedelow, as its initial text scanner (277). RATS accepted text punched in columns and used spaces as delimiters between words and punctuation (277). It tokenized the text for its output, assigning each token to a record with a numeric index plus markers for volume, chapter, paragraph, sentence and word (277).</p> <p>These tokens were stored on tape, disk or other available storage, and used to generate three sets: Dictionary, which contained each word and punctuation mark with its frequency, cross-referenced to the index; AB which indexed each occurrence of a word, arranged alphabetically; and LIN which indexed each occurrence of a word, arranged in order of appearance in the text, cross-referenced to the Dictionary (Smith 278).</p> <p>RATS used its BUILD program to generate the Dictionary, AB and LIN sets, while two additional programs, COMPRESS and EXPAND, provided its text analysis functions (Smith 279). COMPRESS permitted users to specify which words from the Dictionary to work with, as it \"takes the file structure created by BUILD and compresses it to either a linear subset of the text or a subset represented by a partitioning of the dictionary\" (279). EXPAND, not available at the time of Smith\'s publication, \"takes the file structures created by BUILD for several texts or subsets of a text and combines them into a single RATS file structure\" (Smith 279-280). Smith projected a summer 1972 release for the BUILD program (Smith 280), with additional functions and programs to follow by fall of the same year (Smith 283).</p> <p>As a text analysis tool, Smith promoted RATS for concordance generation (Smith 280), for creating thematic distribution line graphs (Smith 281), and for creating transitional matrixes (Smith 282). To extend the system\'s functionality, he was developing a RANDOM program for writing RATS datasets to random-access files, and a RETURN/SEARCH program that would allow users to specify a set of information to examine and a word or group of words to search for (Smith 283).</p> <p>Smith found that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">While this system does not supply all of the features we might wish, it does facilities greatly many of the tasks that humanists and language analysts often perform. Its general flexibility should enable the user to design and implement procedures that fit his analytic model more precisely and sensitively than is generally possible. (283)</p> <p>A decade later, Robert Oakman reflected on Smith\'s work and RATS and judged that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">[a]lthough Smith has shown admirable concern for achieving efficiency in computer storage, his programs seem, by and large, too complex for most inexperienced literary scholars to use with ease. Practically one of the other PL/I program packages may be more convenient for the novice. (Oakman 180n)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p> <p>Smith, John B. \"RATS: A Mid-Level Text Utility System.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 6.5 (1972): 277-283. <a href=\"http://download.springer.com/static/pdf/538/art%253A10.1007%252FBF02404244.pdf?auth66=1389205134_9c45fcce7c893dc1254bf53245b58f45&amp;ext=.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-10 16:19:54', created_at: '2014-01-07 19:13:59', )
Comment.create(id: '1374', tool_id: '277', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>SOLAR (<em>S</em>emantically <em>O</em>riented <em>L</em>exical <em>AR</em>chive) was a lexical resource developed by the System Development Corporation (SCR) in Santa Monica, California in the 1970s (Diller and Olney 301). It was primarily distributed via the ARPA Network, with copies available by request for those without access to the network (Diller and Olney 310).</p> <p>According to Timothy Diller and John Olney of SCR, SOLAR \"is designed to permit a researcher to access a broad range of semantic data, all keyed to individual English words\" (Diller and Olney 301). SCR built in that breadth with the aim of making SOLAR relevant across fields, such as theoretical linguistics, philosophy of language, second language instruction and automated language processing (301). According to Diller and Olney in their article \"SOLAR (A <em>S</em>emantically <em>O</em>riented <em>L</em>exical <em>AR</em>chive): Current Status and Plans,\" published in 1974 prior to SOLAR\'s release,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The SOLAR project is beginning to function both as a lexical information center and as a source of new lexical data. As an information center, it provides insightful descriptions of selected English words extracted from the technical literature of several fields and formatted for machine processing. As a source of new lexical data, it offers collocational features, semantic fields, definitional expansions within a designated set of words, and keyword-in-context materials derived by processing machine-readable transcripts <em>of Webster\'s Seventh New Collegiate Dictionary (W7)</em>, <em>Roget\'s International Thesaurus</em> and other text corpora. (Diller and Olney 301-302).</p> <p>Rather than being a lexicon itself, it offered a series of information-rich source files for constructing a lexicon (Diller and Olney 302). It was made up of seven files:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 1: Semantic Analysis</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 2: Explanatory Notes for the Descriptive Constants Used in the Semantic Analyses</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 3: Conceptual Analysis of Notions Involved by the Descriptive Constants</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 4: Collocational Features Correlated with Particular Word Senses</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 5: Semantic Fields</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 6: Definitional Expansions</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">File 7: Contexts of Occurrence (Diller and Olney 302-303)</p> <p>It also included two supplementary files, a Word Index and a Bibliography (Diller and Olney 309). Within this collection of files, SOLAR integrated data derived from relevant papers, presented in according to the wishes of the authors wherever possible (309).</p> <p>Diller and Olney summarized SOLAR as a resource</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">designed to provide convenient access to semantic and conceptual analyses proposed by linguists, anthropologists, psychologists, philosophers and computer scientists, as well as to semi-processed, formatted data extracted from dictionaries, thesauri, and textual corpora. (Diller and Olney 310).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Diller, Timothy and John Olney. \"SOLAR (A Semantically-Oriented Lexical Archive): Current Status and Plans.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 8.4-5 (1974): 301-311. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30199709\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-08 21:49:19', created_at: '2014-01-08 21:46:33', )
Comment.create(id: '1375', tool_id: '278', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>OPCOL was an experimental algorithm \"which optimizes efficiency with respect to the number of word comparisons\" during an automated text collation developed by Robert L. Cannon, Jr. of the University of South Carolina (Cannon 33).</p> <p>OPCOL\'s optimization applied recent research into the \'longest common subsequence\' (<em>lcs</em>) problem (Oakman 130). The <em>lcs </em>problem refers to \"finding the longest common sequence between two texts of length M and N [which] has shown that both the maximum and minimum number of comparisons is M times N\" (130).</p> <p>The OPCOL algorithm conducted \"pairwise matching between two texts until a point is reached at which the texts do not match\" and built a table of distances between words from the master and comparison texts as it searched for the next match (Cannon 37). Then, once the algorithm found a new match, \"an additional word from the master (comparison) text will next be added. The algorithm will continue to add words from the master (comparison) text as long as their addition continues to reduce the distance between the two texts\" (Cannon 38).</p> <p>Robert Oakman, whom Cannon thanked for \"many helpful discussions and for a critical reading of a draft of this paper\" in his article \"OPCOL: An Optimal Text Collation Algorithm\" (Cannon 33), discussed OPCOL in his book <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Oakman, describing Cannon\'s findings and their implementation in OPCOL, clarified that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">the \"distance\" increases between texts increases as long as they lack identity and begins to decrease when a word in common is finally encountered. The computer continues to check distances every time it adds and looks at another word in either text. When the distance stops decreasing again, the maximum common distance has been found, the variants can be printed, and normal checking resumes. (Oakman 130-131)</p> <p>Reflecting on Cannon and his work on OPCOL, Oakman praised his contribution to literary research:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Cannon\'s approach is intended to minimize comparisons and the amount of compute storage required for large collations; the mathematical elegance of his approach argues for the further application of theoretical results in computer science complicated, real problems like literary collation. Rarely to theoretical breakthroughs in computer research ever reach the needs of literary scholars; Cannon deserves commendation for his commitment to concrete applications of theoretical principals. His algorithm, only tested experimentally, also deserves test with a significant literary textual problem and modification to present the variants in a form easily analyzable by the scholar. (Oakman 131)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Cannon Jr., Robert L. \"OPCOL: an Optimal Text Collation Algorithm.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.1 (1976): 33-40. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204218\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-09 19:17:24', created_at: '2014-01-09 19:16:30', )
Comment.create(id: '1376', tool_id: '26', user_id: '175', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><span style=\"font-family: georgia, palatino; font-size: large;\">Po trati deklica hodila, tako je deklica tožila: Cvetice lani brala sem, kar jih najlep&scaron;ih znala sem, za god jih manki podarila. Cvetice letos brala bom, kar jih najlep&scaron;ih znala bom, na grob ji bom jih podarila. </span></p>', updated_at: '2014-01-17 19:54:18', created_at: '2014-01-11 12:55:30', )
Comment.create(id: '1377', tool_id: '279', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>FISHER (FORTRAN Implemented String Handling and Editing Routine) was a package of routines for text handling in FORTRAN developed in the 1970s by A. Colin Day (Oakman 181). It was distributed on 1500 punch cards and available by contacting Day at the University College London\'s Computing Centre (Allwright 297).</p> <p>Robert Oakman, commenting on FISHER in his book <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>, noted that \"using FISHER\'s commands resembles programming in PL/I; the process of putting them together in order to carry out a major job like a word index of a text is similar to programming in a more textually compatible language\" (Oakman 181).</p> <p>FISHER was also reviewed by Christine Allwright in the journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em>. In her examination of the package, she found that</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">FISHER consists of a set of Fortran subroutines and functions which, it is claimed, in effect add several new data types to Fortran....The three new data types of greatest interest to the user are: the character held as a small integer, the string of characters represented by an integer value and the marker pointing to a particular position within a character string, also represented by an integer value. Besides being able to create items of the new data types, FISHER provides facilities for their efficient use in many text handling situations, for example, comparing strings, searching for particular characters in strings, removing sections, joining two strings together, inserting substrings, etc. (Allwright 297)</p> <p>The FISHER package was written on an IBM 360, a mark of cross-system compatibility (297). Allwright was able to run it successfully on a CDC 6600 using two other FORTRAN compilers (297). The package included documentation comprised of three sections, a User\'s Manual, a Technical Description, and an Implementation Guide (297). The User\'s Manual included descriptions of FISHER\'s text-handling, error-handling facilities and explanations of error messages, plus \"a comprehensive index and glossary\" (297). The Technical Description expanded on FISHER\'s various aspects (297), such as its routines and data structures (Allwright 298).</p> <p>Allwright favourably compared FISHER\'s capabilities to SNOBOL, a contemporary language designed for string handling (297). In her review trials, it proved time-efficient when running small and medium programs (Allwright 298). However, she assessed it to be of most value not to beginners, but rather \"to assist the experienced Fortran programmer...given that, it is relatively straightforward to use\" (Allwright 297). Oakman also cautioned potential users that \"[e]ven with the helpful user\'s manual, the inexperienced scholar will find the going rough at first\" (Oakman 182).</p> <p>Allwright\'s final assessment of FISHER was positive:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">As an apparently useful set of routines for anyone wishing to handle characters and character strings, FISHER provides the programmer with facilities which otherwise he must expend time and energy creating fro himself each time he sets out to write a text-handling program. It would be a useful addition to a program library wherever character-handling computer users may be found. (Allwright 298)</p> <p>Oakman agreed on FISHER\'s value to FORTRAN users, though he retained reservations with regard to using FORTRAN for text processing:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Compared to a program package like JEUDEMO or CLAS, in which the computer can be instructed in a few commands to do a complex index, in terms of convenience FISHER comes out in second place, although it is probably more machine efficient. On the other hand, for people whose only option is FORTRAN, Day has already done much of the hard work of modifying the language for text processing. For those scholars, FISHER could make the difference in being able or not being able to carry out any analysis on the computer. (Oakman 182)</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>Allwright, Christine. \"Software Review: FISHER: A String-Handling Package.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 10.5 (1976): 297-298. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007%2FBF02420064.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p> <p>Oakman, Robert L. <em>Computer Methods for Literary Research</em>. Athens: University of Georgia Press, 1984.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-13 18:37:03', created_at: '2014-01-13 18:34:28', )
Comment.create(id: '1378', tool_id: '269', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>FANGORN was a language written particularly for literary and linguistic analysis developed by Peter B&oslash;gh Andersen of the Nordic Institute of the University of Aarhus in the 1970s (Andersen 227).</p> <p>In Andersen\'s words, \"FANGORN, a special-purpose language for linguistic and literary analysis, was designed because I encountered certain descriptive problems that were not due to the linguistic research I did, but to the languages I used\" (227). Andersen had encountered difficulties particularly with most languages\' inability to recognize linguistic constructs as being simultaneously subject and object (227), and so, \"FANGORN was designed in order to avoid the descriptive problems generated by the subject/object dichotomy\" (Andersen 228).</p> <p>FANGORN programs consisted of networks of nodes with a known location, name, and a process related to other nodes in the network (228). Each node and node relationship corresponded to a value in the source text (Andersen 229). According to Andersen, \"[t]he interpreter is programmed in modules, each node roughly corresponding to a SIMULA class declaration. Because of the modular structure, it is easy to remove or add new nodes\" (Andersen 241). It was applied to a variety of text analysis functions:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The language has been used for minor, rather different purposes: morphological analysis and synthesis, testing sentence grammars and narrative grammars by synthesizing sentences and stories, semantic analysis, plan construction, question answering, and parsing.\" (241)</p> <p>At the time of Andersen\'s 1981 article \"FANGORN: A Special-Purpose Language for the Humanities,\" FANGORN was in its third version (241). Andersen implemented the language via \"an interpreter written in the SIMULA 67...running under the NOS operating system on the CDC Cyber 173,\" which was available at University of Aarhus\' Regional EDP-Center (RECAU) (241). In terms of performance, Andersen noted that the interpreter \"is reasonably fast, but it consumes far too much space\" (241). He offered a user manual, available by contacting him directly at the University of Aarhus (241).</p> <p>Andersen evaluated FANGORN, though prefaced with the disclaimer that \"[e]very father loves his children, and that goes for programming languages too. Objective evaluation is difficult\" (Andersen 242). From the perspective of its developer, Andersen found that \"[w]hat I like most in FANGORN is the \'bodily\' character of the algorithms: it is possible to have the program build and modify algorithms in rather sophisticate ways. This is extremely useful in programs dealing with historical and developmental issues\" (242).</p> <p>He also acknowledged its weaknesses:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The main drawback in the language is the syntax. FANGORN programs are as unreadable as LISP programs, and I always use a graphical notation when I write them. One solution, and possibly the best one, is to provide FANGORN with graphical input facilities. Another solution is to design a linguistic front end that is easier to read and write for humans. The problem is that the bodily nature of the algorithm, i.e., the network that implements it, must be completely transparent from the program text; else the user could not change it...the syntactical problem is not merely a technical problem. It arose because we have no suitable framework or categories in which to describe self-modifying processes; at least, I have no such framework. (242)</p> <p>However, in Andersen\'s view, \"FANGORN was built as a tool for experimenting with exactly those processes\" (242).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p>Anderson, Peter B&oslash;gh. \"FANGORN: A Special-Purpose Language for the Humanities.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 15.4 (1981): 227-242. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204310\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-14 19:08:20', created_at: '2014-01-14 19:02:22', )
Comment.create(id: '1379', tool_id: '266', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>TEXTPACK V was a text analysis package for PCs released in the 1980s by Peter Mohler and Cornelia Zuell of ZUMA (Zentrum fuer Umfragen, Methoden un Analysen (Olsen 155). This version was a port with improvements of the original FORTRAN program, which was released for mainframe computers in the 1970s and developed by Jurgen Hoehe, Hans-Dieter Klingemann and Klaus Radermacher (155).</p> <p>Mark Olsen, who reviewed TEXTPACK V for the journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> in 1989, described it as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">a collection of interdependent utilities designed to perform simple elements of text analysis, such as concordances, word frequency counts, word tagging, and text reformatting. The utilities are batch-oriented, reflecting the early development of TEXTPACK on mainframe computers. (155)</p> <p>As a package, its programs were useful&nbsp; \"for the qualitative description of literary texts, analysis of content, and data management. The majority of the program assists users in exploring and editing textual source material\" (McCarty et al. 114).</p> <p>It was included in the <em>Tools for Humanists, 1989</em> guide to available software and hardware for humanistic research. At the time of its publication, that guide found that \"TextPack is it [sic] the only package reliably distributed for mainframes and personal computers that automatically codes a text\" (McCarty et al. 115).</p> <p>TEXTPACK V required users to pre-process texts by applying two hierarchical levels of descriptive tags, with a third level supplied by the system (115). This tagging supplied identifiers that labeled information such as paragraphs and sentences, conforming to one of three prescribed formats (Olsen 155). The SENTENCE program used the pre-processed text to convert it into a form compatible with the rest of TEXTPACK (155).</p> <p>There were ten additional programs in TEXTPACK V, supplying functions such as correcting and editing system files (SENMERGE), tokenization (LISTSPLT), frequency counts (FREQ), keyword-in-context listings (KWIC), and generating a content analysis dictionary (TAGCODER) (McCarty et al 115-116). It also included a function for converting output to ASCII for use by analytical systems (REFORM).</p> <p>The TEXTPACK V programs were distributed on four diskettes, requiring 1.3MB storage, and were easily installed without compatibility problems (Olsen 155). It ran on PCs and compatibles in an MS-DOS environment (Olsen 160).</p> <p>Mark Olsen was highly critical of TEXTPACK V. Some of his issues with it stemmed from its origins as a mainframe package, as to his eye, the ported version \"ha[s] not...lost the flavor of a much earlier and more primitive era of humanities computing\" (Olsen 155). The programs retained markers of mainframe computing, for example that \"[a]ll the programs are controlled with options set using \'Program Control Cards,\' and include such quaint parameters as specifying whether the INPUT is from DISK or CARD\" (155). These characteristics negatively impacted Olsen\'s user experience, as in his view,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">simply compiling mainframe programs to run in a PC environment is counter-productive, since the main advantage of the PC is its interactive immediacy. Batch-oriented programs may be better left on mainframes with their superior processing speed and expensive high-speed peripheral devices, such as line-printers. (155)</p> <p>He found a number of TEXTPACK V\'s programs frustrating, particularly SENTENCE:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">SENTENCE does very little in addition to what the user is required to provide in pre-processing. While the program can separate punctuation marks from words and transform numeric strings to words (i.e. \"50\" becomes \"fifty\"), SENTENCE hardly seems worth the effort, particularly in a microcomputer environment, as the user is required to perform a large number of pre-processing steps to prepare the data for SENTENCE. (Olsen 156)</p> <p>Olsen also found the KWIC program \"difficult to use, requires several preliminary steps, and fails to work properly,\" based on a test using a sample from a French text (156). From the original text of 707 words, comprising 5,016 bytes, the KWIC took \"seven minutes to generate a full concordance, not including the pre-processing time required by SENTENCE and LISTSPLT\" (156).</p> <p>Olsen\'s final assessment was damning:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">There is little to recommend TEXTPACK V to the researcher in the humanities. It is difficult to use and not particularly effective. Its individual modules, such as the KWIC program, are not comparable to many other packages and public domain programs. Given the structural limitations of the system, it is hard to see any advantage that can be gained from learning how to use it. This is only compounded when the weak documentation and obscure program operation are taken into account. (Olsen 159-160)</p> <p>In light of its numerous problems, Olsen concluded \"TEXTPACK V needs to be redesigned from the ground up, a process which should attempt to incorporate elements of full text retrieval and more sophisticated text processing than is supported by the current implementation\" (Olsen 160).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Sources</strong></p> <p>McCarty, Willard et al. <em>Tools for Humanists, 1989</em>. Toronto: Centre for Computing in the Humanities at the University of Toronto, Jun. 6-9, 1989.</p> <p>Olsen, Mark. \"Software Review: TEXTPACK V: Text Analysis Utilities for the Personal Computer.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.2 (1989):155-160. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200155\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</p>', updated_at: '2014-01-16 19:47:35', created_at: '2014-01-16 19:45:34', )
