Comment.create(id: '1383', tool_id: '27', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Hello PWT T.,</p> <p>Thank you for your feedback. We link to the tool\'s homepage and documentation wherever possible, but for tools like Voyant\'s FeatureClusters, we only have limited information.</p> <p>I did some checking, and it appears that this tool is not currently available, likely owing to its experimental status. As such, we know a bit about it, but there is no tool homepage or documentation to link to yet.</p> <p>That said, Voyant is a large family of tools and there may be another one that you would find similarly interesting, such as their Links, RezoViz or Mandala. You can browse all the Voyant tools in TAPoR on its family page:</p> <p><a href=\"../filterbyattribute?att_val_id=36\">http://www.tapor.ca/tools/filterbyattribute?att_val_id=36</a></p> <p>If you\'d like more information on how to use individual tools, click on the link provided under Documentation on its entry page. This will take you to Voyant\'s own documentation for that tool. You can also see all the documentation available at Voyant\'s own Tool Index page:</p> <p><a href=\"http://docs.voyant-tools.org/tools/\">http://docs.voyant-tools.org/tools/ </a></p> <p>In addition, Voyant has a Getting Started tutorial for new users:</p> <p><a href=\"http://docs.voyant-tools.org/start/\">http://docs.voyant-tools.org/start/</a></p> <p>I hope this helps. TAPoR 2.5 is an ongoing project, and we appreciate your feedback. If you have any other questions for us, I am monitoring the site\'s comments, or you can contact us directly at <a href=\"mailto:tapor@ualberta.ca\">tapor@ualberta.ca</a></p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><em>Updated February 12 to correct a broken link.</em></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-12 23:36:07', created_at: '2014-01-28 20:31:42', )
Comment.create(id: '1384', tool_id: '1', user_id: '246', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: 'My fellow citizens:  I stand here today humbled by the task before us, grateful for the trust you have bestowed, mindful of the sacrifices borne by our ancestors. I thank President Bush for his service to our nation, as well as the generosity and cooperation he has shown throughout this transition.  Forty-four Americans have now taken the presidential oath. The words have been spoken during rising tides of prosperity and the still waters of peace. Yet, every so often the oath is taken amidst gathering clouds and raging storms. At these moments, America has carried on not simply because of the skill or vision of those in high office, but because We the People have remained faithful to the ideals of our forbearers, and true to our founding documents.  So it has been. So it must be with this generation of Americans.  That we are in the midst of crisis is now well understood. Our nation is at war, against a far-reaching network of violence and hatred. Our economy is badly weakened, a consequence of greed and irresponsibility on the part of some, but also our collective failure to make hard choices and prepare the nation for a new age. Homes have been lost; jobs shed; businesses shuttered. Our health care is too costly; our schools fail too many; and each day brings further evidence that the ways we use energy strengthen our adversaries and threaten our planet.  These are the indicators of crisis, subject to data and statistics. Less measurable but no less profound is a sapping of confidence across our land - a nagging fear that America\'s decline is inevitable, and that the next generation must lower its sights.  Today I say to you that the challenges we face are real. They are serious and they are many.  They will not be met easily or in a short span of time. But know this, America - they will be met. On this day, we gather because we have chosen hope over fear, unity of purpose over conflict and discord.  On this day, we come to proclaim an end to the petty grievances and false promises, the recriminations and worn out dogmas, that for far too long have strangled our politics.  We remain a young nation, but in the words of Scripture, the time has come to set aside childish things. The time has come to reaffirm our enduring spirit; to choose our better history; to carry forward that precious gift, that noble idea, passed on from generation to generation: the God-given promise that all are equal, all are free, and all deserve a chance to pursue their full measure of happiness.  In reaffirming the greatness of our nation, we understand that greatness is never a given. It must be earned. Our journey has never been one of short-cuts or settling for less. It has not been the path for the faint-hearted - for those who prefer leisure over work, or seek only the pleasures of riches and fame. Rather, it has been the risk-takers, the doers, the makers of things - some celebrated but more often men and women obscure in their labor, who have carried us up the long, rugged path towards prosperity and freedom.  For us, they packed up their few worldly possessions and traveled across oceans in search of a new life.  For us, they toiled in sweatshops and settled the West; endured the lash of the whip and plowed the hard earth.  For us, they fought and died, in places like Concord and Gettysburg; Normandy and Khe Sahn. Time and again these men and women struggled and sacrificed and worked till their hands were raw so that we might live a better life. They saw America as bigger than the sum of our individual ambitions; greater than all the differences of birth or wealth or faction.  This is the journey we continue today. We remain the most prosperous, powerful nation on Earth. Our workers are no less productive than when this crisis began. Our minds are no less inventive, our goods and services no less needed than they were last week or last month or last year. Our capacity remains undiminished. But our time of standing pat, of protecting narrow interests and putting off unpleasant decisions - that time has surely passed. Starting today, we must pick ourselves up, dust ourselves off, and begin again the work of remaking America.  For everywhere we look, there is work to be done. The state of the economy calls for action, bold and swift, and we will act - not only to create new jobs, but to lay a new foundation for growth. We will build the roads and bridges, the electric grids and digital lines that feed our commerce and bind us together. We will restore science to its rightful place, and wield technology\'s wonders to raise health care\'s quality and lower its cost. We will harness the sun and the winds and the soil to fuel our cars and run our factories. And we will transform our schools and colleges and universities to meet the demands of a new age. All this we can do. And all this we will do.  Now, there are some who question the scale of our ambitions - who suggest that our system cannot tolerate too many big plans. Their memories are short. For they have forgotten what this country has already done; what free men and women can achieve when imagination is joined to common purpose, and necessity to courage.  What the cynics fail to understand is that the ground has shifted beneath them - that the stale political arguments that have consumed us for so long no longer apply. The question we ask today is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works - whether it helps families find jobs at a decent wage, care they can afford, a retirement that is dignified. Where the answer is yes, we intend to move forward. Where the answer is no, programs will end. And those of us who manage the public\'s dollars will be held to account - to spend wisely, reform bad habits, and do our business in the light of day - because only then can we restore the vital trust between a people and their government.  Nor is the question before us whether the market is a force for good or ill. Its power to generate wealth and expand freedom is unmatched, but this crisis has reminded us that without a watchful eye, the market can spin out of control - and that a nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous. The success of our economy has always depended not just on the size of our Gross Domestic Product, but on the reach of our prosperity; on our ability to extend opportunity to every willing heart - not out of charity, but because it is the surest route to our common good.  As for our common defense, we reject as false the choice between our safety and our ideals. Our Founding Fathers, faced with perils we can scarcely imagine, drafted a charter to assure the rule of law and the rights of man, a charter expanded by the blood of generations. Those ideals still light the world, and we will not give them up for expedience\'s sake. And so to all other peoples and governments who are watching today, from the grandest capitals to the small village where my father was born: know that America is a friend of each nation and every man, woman, and child who seeks a future of peace and dignity, and that we are ready to lead once more.  Recall that earlier generations faced down fascism and communism not just with missiles and tanks, but with sturdy alliances and enduring convictions. They understood that our power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please. Instead, they knew that our power grows through its prudent use; our security emanates from the justness of our cause, the force of our example, the tempering qualities of humility and restraint.  We are the keepers of this legacy. Guided by these principles once more, we can meet those new threats that demand even greater effort - even greater cooperation and understanding between nations. We will begin to responsibly leave Iraq to its people, and forge a hard-earned peace in Afghanistan. With old friends and former foes, we will work tirelessly to lessen the nuclear threat, and roll back the specter of a warming planet. We will not apologize for our way of life, nor will we waver in its defense, and for those who seek to advance their aims by inducing terror and slaughtering innocents, we say to you now that our spirit is stronger and cannot be broken; you cannot outlast us, and we will defeat you.  For we know that our patchwork heritage is a strength, not a weakness. We are a nation of Christians and Muslims, Jews and Hindus - and non-believers. We are shaped by every language and culture, drawn from every end of this Earth; and because we have tasted the bitter swill of civil war and segregation, and emerged from that dark chapter stronger and more united, we cannot help but believe that the old hatreds shall someday pass; that the lines of tribe shall soon dissolve; that as the world grows smaller, our common humanity shall reveal itself; and that America must play its role in ushering in a new era of peace.  To the Muslim world, we seek a new way forward, based on mutual interest and mutual respect.  To those leaders around the globe who seek to sow conflict, or blame their society\'s ills on the West - know that your people will judge you on what you can build, not what you destroy. To those who cling to power through corruption and deceit and the silencing of dissent, know that you are on the wrong side of history; but that we will extend a hand if you are willing to unclench your fist.  To the people of poor nations, we pledge to work alongside you to make your farms flourish and let clean waters flow; to nourish starved bodies and feed hungry minds. And to those nations like ours that enjoy relative plenty, we say we can no longer afford indifference to suffering outside our borders; nor can we consume the world\'s resources without regard to effect. For the world has changed, and we must change with it.  As we consider the road that unfolds before us, we remember with humble gratitude those brave Americans who, at this very hour, patrol far-off deserts and distant mountains. They have something to tell us today, just as the fallen heroes who lie in Arlington whisper through the ages.  We honor them not only because they are guardians of our liberty, but because they embody the spirit of service; a willingness to find meaning in something greater than themselves. And yet, at this moment - a moment that will define a generation - it is precisely this spirit that must inhabit us all.  For as much as government can do and must do, it is ultimately the faith and determination of the American people upon which this nation relies. It is the kindness to take in a stranger when the levees break, the selflessness of workers who would rather cut their hours than see a friend lose their job which sees us through our darkest hours. It is the firefighter\'s courage to storm a stairway filled with smoke, but also a parent\'s willingness to nurture a child, that finally decides our fate.  Our challenges may be new. The instruments with which we meet them may be new. But those values upon which our success depends - hard work and honesty, courage and fair play, tolerance and curiosity, loyalty and patriotism - these things are old. These things are true. They have been the quiet force of progress throughout our history. What is demanded then is a return to these truths. What is required of us now is a new era of responsibility - a recognition, on the part of every American, that we have duties to ourselves, our nation, and the world, duties that we do not grudgingly accept but rather seize gladly, firm in the knowledge that there is nothing so satisfying to the spirit, so defining of our character, than giving our all to a difficult task.  This is the price and the promise of citizenship.  This is the source of our confidence - the knowledge that God calls on us to shape an uncertain destiny.  This is the meaning of our liberty and our creed - why men and women and children of every race and every faith can join in celebration across this magnificent mall, and why a man whose father less than sixty years ago might not have been served at a local restaurant can now stand before you to take a most sacred oath.  So let us mark this day with remembrance, of who we are and how far we have traveled. In the year of America\'s birth, in the coldest of months, a small band of patriots huddled by dying campfires on the shores of an icy river. The capital was abandoned. The enemy was advancing. The snow was stained with blood. At a moment when the outcome of our revolution was most in doubt, the father of our nation ordered these words be read to the people:  \"Let it be told to the future world...that in the depth of winter, when nothing but hope and virtue could survive...that the city and the country, alarmed at one common danger, came forth to meet [it].\"  America. In the face of our common dangers, in this winter of our hardship, let us remember these timeless words. With hope and virtue, let us brave once more the icy currents, and endure what storms may come. Let it be said by our children\'s children that when we were tested we refused to let this journey end, that we did not turn back nor did we falter; and with eyes fixed on the horizon and God\'s grace upon us, we carried forth that great gift of freedom and delivered it safely to future generations.', updated_at: '2014-02-18 17:46:19', created_at: '2014-02-12 17:50:20', )
Comment.create(id: '1385', tool_id: '4', user_id: '256', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: 'TI  Heat treatment technology for  rapid  annealing of  steel T91 Ultra- rapid  annealing of nonoriented electrical  steel. Process for the  transformation  annealing of  steels PRODUCTION OF SURFACE TREATED  STEEL SHEET HAVING 3 TO 4 TEMPERING DEGREE BY  RAPID HEATING  ANNEALING  RAPID CONTINUOUS SPHEROIDIZING  ANNEALING TREATMENT FOR  STEEL MATERIAL CONTINUOUS  ANNEALING METHOD OF REDUCING PICK-UPS FOR  HIGH  STRENGTH  STEEL MANUFACTURING METHOD OF PRECIPITATION HARDNESS  HIGH  STRENGTH  STEEL PLATE BY CONTINUOUS  ANNEALING SHORT-TIME  ANNEALING  STEEL HAVING FERRITE FORMED BY STRAIN INDUCED DYNAMIC  TRANSFORMATION CAPABLE OF GREATLY SHORTENING SOFTENING TIME BY FORMING FINE FERRITE AND METHOD FOR MANUFACTURING THE  STEEL Process for the  transformation  annealing of  steels Semi-finished steel prod. heat treatment - by rapid annealing, rapid cooling to room temp. and batch overageing Soft annealing copper-coated low carbon steel wire - by rapidly heating to annealing temp. and slow cooling followed by rapid cooling to room temp. and tempering Annealing cold rolled silicon steel sheet - with rapid heating, for improved sec. grain size and core loss that are not affected by subsequent stress relief annealing Manufacture of high tensile strength stainless steel sheet or strip - of dual phase ferrite and martensite by subjecting the cold rolled steel to a rapid anneal. Continuous annealing of steel strip - involves the use of a preheating and a rapid heating zone Unidirectional magnetic steel sheet manufacturing method - involves performing rapid heating at predetermined rate after final cold rolling process, decarburisation annealing and final finish annealing Unidirectional magnetic steel sheet manufacturing method for iron core of transformer - involves heating and applying predetermined rolling, annealing followed by rapid heating of steel slab Manufacture of magnetic steel sheet - involves using two pairs of energising rolls for rapid heating before or during decarburisation annealing, and stopping power and amount of distortions during process satisfies specified relation Manufacture of grain oriented magnetic steel sheet for electrical equipment - involves maintaining wet hydrogen atmosphere satisfying predetermined relationship and oxygen concentration at throat part between decarburisation annealing furnace and rapid heating chamber Cold rolled steel sheet manufacturing method for panel of motor vehicle - involves annealing of steel containing predetermined elements, rapid heating and cooling at predetermined temperature Manufacture of grain-oriented electromagnetic steel sheet for iron core materials, involves subjecting steel slab to hot-rolling, annealing, cold-rolling, and recrystallization annealing, with rapid heating before primary annealing Continuous decarburisation-nitridation annealing furnace - for anisotropic electromagnetic steel plate, with heating zone, cooling zone switchable between slow and rapid cooling, etc. High strength galvanised annealed sheet steel prodn. - by nickel@ plating base sheet, rapidly heating in non-oxidising atmos., galvanising, rapidly heating and alloying Aluminium-killed steel continuous annealing - by rapid increase of temp. to complete recrystn. Unidimensional electromagnetic steel plate - by hot and cold rolling, heating rapidly and annealing Oriented silicon steel plate prodn. - by soaking at high temp. primary recrystallisation annealing, and rapidly heat treating with magnetic field applied in rolling direction Unoriented electromagnetic steel plate mfr. having good magnetic properties - by rapid final recrystallisation annealing in direct electric resistance heating system to prevent oxidn. Mfg. non-oriented magnetic steel sheet with excellent magnetic characteristics - by cold rolling, and recrystallising annealing with rapid heat-up rate Continuous annealing of steel strip - is carried out after coating surface with soot to promote more rapid heating up Disassembling spot-welded joint of APFC steel plates - by drilling nuggets after annealing under rapid heating conditions. High strength, low carbon seamless steel pipe mfr. - by heating steel pipe obtd. by rolling low alloy pipe and rapidly quenching and annealing Stress relief annealing of turbine rotor material - where welded austenitic stainless steel base and low alloy steel are repeatedly slowly cooled and rapidly heated Continuous annealing furnace for steel strip - having ceramic radiant tubes with interposed heat resistant steel tubes for rapid heating Mfg. silicon steel sheet with directional properties - involves application of heat absorbent before intermediate annealing and prior to rapid heating up Mfg. high magnetic flux density electromagnetic steel plate - by annealing silicon steel plate, rapidly cooling and annealing Surface treating original tin plated or tin free steel prodn. - contg. carbon, silicon, manganese, sulphur, etc. which is continuously annealed rapidly cooled and temper-rolled Rapid annealing and pickling of stainless steel sheet - involves plating sheet with chromium, annealing at temp. above recrystallisation temp. and pickling Prodn. of non-ageing container soft original steel plate in rapid heat annealing - comprises hot-rolling coiling, cold-rolling, continuous annealing by heating then forcibly cooling, and temper-rolling Silicon steel plate with non-directional properties - obtd. by hot rolling steel slab, and rapidly heating it to 800-1200 deg. C to perform annealing NoAbstract Dwg 0/4 Annealing of stainless steel sheet - which is carried out in annealing furnace by rapid heating at specified temp. Continuous annealing for band steel - involves rapidly heating then cooling work that has been soaked at 500-750 deg C, then redn. rolling Cold-rolled steel strip mfr., with superior deep reduction characteristics - by hot rolling, cooling under specified conditions, pickling, cold rolling then continuously annealing or recrystallising with a rapid heating interval Oriented magnetic steel sheet mfr. - comprises cold rolling steel sheet contg. silicon@ manganese@ aluminium@ etc., rapid heating and finish annealing. Continuously annealing cold rolled steel plate - includes rapid heating in range from recrystallisation temp. to 860 degrees Celsius (J5 9.8.80) Over-ageing and annealing aluminium plated steel sheet - by rapidly heating to 500-580 degrees C, maintaining at this temp. for up to 20 seconds and cooling (J5 27.6.80) Mfg. high magnetic flux density electromagnetic steel plate - by annealing silicon steel slab, rapidly cooling and annealing Producing spring steel - by rapidly heating quenched steel up to annealing temp. while steel is tensioned, then cooling (J5 5.6.84) Bearing steel having good machinability and cold workability - produced by annealing by rapid heating, isothermally holding at that temperature, rapidly heating, cooling, etc. Manufacture of grain-oriented electrical steel sheet, involves heating, hot-rolling and cold-rolling slab, primary recrystallization annealing by rapidly heating, and secondary recrystallization annealing Extra-thin cold rolled transformer steel sheets mfr. - includes rapid heating to holding pt. in high temp. annealing for improving flatness of final prod. Annealing low carbon steel strip - by rapid two stage heating process Annealing steel to give improved ductility and toughness - by rapid heating to above upper transformation temp. and cooling with some undissolved carbide present  Method for eliminating  low  carbon  steel cover  annealing yield point elongation Improved process of  annealing  low  carbon  steel  HIGH  STRENGTH  STEEL SUPERIOR IN HIGH-FREQUENCY  ANNEALING CHARACTERISTIC, AND MANUFACTURING METHOD METHOD FOR PRODUCING  HIGH  STRENGTH  STEEL SHEET AND HIGH STRENGTH PLATED STEEL SHEET, AND  ANNEALING FURNACE AND PRODUCTION EQUIPMENT USED FOR PRODUCING THEM METHOD FOR  ANNEALING  LOW- CARBON  STEEL CONTAINING CR METHOD FOR MANUFACTURING 780 MPa GRADE HIGH TENSILE STRENGTH HOT ROLLED  STEEL SHEET HAVING EXCELLENT WELDABILITY BY CONTROLLING C, Mn AND Si BASED ON A COMPONENT SYSTEM SATISFYING CARBON EQUIVALENT OF 0.36 OR LESS AND ADDING Nb AND Ti FOR  GRAIN  REFINEMENT METHOD OF DECARBURIZING  ANNEALING OF COLD-ROLLED  LOW- CARBON  STEEL  ANNEALING METHOD OF COLD-ROLLED COILS MADE OF  LOW- CARBON  STEEL METHOD OF CONTINUOUS  ANNEALING OF  LOW- CARBON  STEEL FOR TIN PLATE METHOD FOR RECRYSTALLIZATION  ANNEALING OF COLD-ROLLED  LOW- CARBON  STEEL STABILIZED WITH ALUMINIUM METHOD FOR  ANNEALING CHARGE OF COLD-ROLLED  LOW- CARBON  STEEL SHEET COILS IN BELL-TYPE FURNACE METHOD OF RECRYSTALLIZATION  ANNEALING OF COLD-ROLLED  LOW- CARBON  STEEL METHOD FOR RECRYSTALLIZATION  ANNEALING OF  LOW- CARBON  STEEL FORGINGS METHOD OF RECRYSRALLIZED  ANNEALING OF  LOW- CARBON  STEELS Process of  annealing  low  carbon  steel HIGH STRENGTH AND HIGH DUCTILITY STEEL PLATE HAVING HYPERFINE CRYSTAL GRAIN STRUCTURE PRODUCED BY SUBJECTING ORDINARY  LOW  CARBON  STEEL TO LOW STRAIN WORKING AND  ANNEALING, AND METHOD FOR PRODUCTION THEREOF  Heat treatment method for  grain  refinement of NiCrMoV  steel forging piece  Grain  refinement method of forged  steel cold roller Prevention of particle embrittlement in  grain- refined, high strength  steels. METHOD FOR ROLLING CARBON  STEEL FOR  GRAIN  REFINEMENT METHOD FOR MANUFACTURING HIGH STRENGTH  STEEL BY  GRAIN  REFINEMENT  GRAIN  REFINED  STEEL AND METHOD FOR MANUFACTURING THE SAME  GRAIN  REFINERS FOR  STEEL - MANUFACTURING METHODS AND USE METALLURGICAL METHOD FOR REFINING GRAINS OF  STEEL BY MODIFYING INCLUSIONS THROUGH ADDITION OF MAGNESIUM AND ALUMINUM  ', updated_at: '2014-02-17 17:10:37', created_at: '2014-02-17 17:09:35', )
