Comment.create(id: '1474', tool_id: '267', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>INRAC was a language compiler and natural language processing system created by Tom Etter and William Chamberlain (Olsen 161). It required an IBM PC or compatible with 128K of RAM and was available from INRAC Inc. (Olsen 167).</p> <p>INRAC had a wide applicability, and \"[could] be used to prototype formal natural language interfaces, design conversation systems, and develop experimental forms of computer-generated prose and poetry\" (Olsen 161).</p> <p>Mark Olsen reviewed the INRAC system in 1989 for the journal Computers and the Humanities. His assessment was conflicted - though in his view it \"would prove interesting as a means of testing ideas concerning natural language interfaces in, for example, computer-assisted language education\" (181), he also found it unavoidably idiosyncratic:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">While it has many sophisticated features, such as a built-in conjugation system and supports compilation of lists of related lexical items, INRAC is rather poorly designed and implemented...[i]t might be recommended to individuals who are interested in experimenting with writing interactive systems, but only to those who have considerable amounts of time to kill and a very high frustration threshold. (181)</p> <p>To its credit, INRAC somewhat \"reduces the amount of code required to write natural language interface programs\" (Olsen 162). It also included a sophisticated conjugation system (Olsen 164). It included an editor and debugger, E, that checked for syntax errors and inserted code and variables into the appropriate files (Olsen 162). However, E had a number of bugs that made it preferable for Olsen to make his edits in another program and load the files into E only once he was ready to run them (162).</p> <p>INRAC had a number of notable detrimental characteristics. Its documentation was, in Olsen\'s opinion, \"simply awful\" (Olsen 164). It could only store a limited number of variables (which themselves stored commands and subroutine calls) (Olsen 163). From the user\'s perspective, its \"[c]onditional statements and control of program flow are rather cryptic,\" compounded by the developers\' choice not to include common programming syntax like loops, and instead use small, self-contained modules (163). As a whole, Olsen found that though \"[i]t would be unreasonable to expect INRAC to emulate the logical programming of PROLOG...the current implementation of logical or associative data structures seems to be very weak (Olsen 164).</p> <p>His final assessment of INRAC as a tool for general use within the humanities was firmly negative:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Ignoring my dislike for the INRAC language compiler\'s syntax and design philosophy, which I feel would seriously encumber a reasonably large and complex programming effort, I still cannot recommend INRAC since it is not well finished and documented...[t]his is unfortunate, since INRAC\'s potential...is very great. As currently implemented, however, INRAC is far too idiosyncratic and too poorly finished to be attractive to large numbers of programmers in the humanities. (Olsen 166-167)</p> <p>Nevertheless, Olsen still felt that \"INRAC is an important development in humanities processing\" (Olsen 181).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p><span>Olsen, Mark. \"Software Review: Talking Back: The INRAC Language Compiler.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 23.2 (1989):161-167. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30200156\">Web</a>.</span></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-25 22:50:33', created_at: '2014-02-25 22:49:19', )
Comment.create(id: '1475', tool_id: '270', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>STASEL, an acronym for \"Stylistic Treatment at the Sentence Level,\" was a system for teaching style integrating both artificial intelligence and natural language processing techniques (Payette and Hirst 87). Its developers, Julie Payette and Graeme Hirst of the University of Toronto, described it as</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">an intelligent computer-assisted language instruction system that is designed to teach principals of syntactic style to students of English. Unlike conventional style checkers, the system performs a complete syntactic analysis of its input, and takes the student\'s stylistic intent into account when providing a diagnosis. (87)</p> <p>The system was developed C-PROLOG under UNIX (Payette and Hirst 91). STASEL included a syntactic parser, a prototype lexicon, Prolog utilities to handle its string manipulation and I/O functions, a goal-directed style analyzer, and an information module that formed part of the system\'s output message generation (91). According to Payette and Hirst,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The parser, lexicon, and utility modules serve as a front end for the subsequent stylistic analysis. With the I/O routines of the utility module, the parser reads the input sentence and stores the words in a list structure that is examined from left to right, with backtracking as necessary. (91)</p> <p>STASEL integrated a number of features that differentiated it from similar experimental or commercial stylistic programs:</p> <ul> <li>it bases its analysis upon the writer\'s stylistic intent; that is, the system performs a goal-directed stylistic analysis;</li> <li>it is based upon a comprehensive parser that can recognize stylistic features and analyze an important set of English structures[...];</li> <li>it generates explicit representations of a sentence\'s syntactic structure in the form of parse trees, one of which, the stylistic parse tree, is specifically constructed for stylistic analysis and for teaching the mechanics of English sentence construction;</li> <li>it is designed for educational purposes and provides a communicative environment where the student can \"learn by doing.\" (Payette and Hirst 88-89)</li> </ul> <p>In keeping with its instructional aims, STASEL was an interactive system capable of accepting full sentences and \"analyz[ing] their lexical, structural and positional characteristics\" (Payette and Hirst 89). It was designed to be extensible, so that additional text and semantic processing capabilities could be incorporated at a later date (89). Payette and Hirst identified expandability as a central motivation for STASEL, as it was their intent \"that the STASEL prototype will form the basis for the development of intelligent tutoring systems for teaching writing\" (Payette and Hirst 100).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p><span>Payette, Julie and Graeme Hirst. \"An Intelligent Computer-Assistant for Stylistic Instruction.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 26.2 (1992): 87-102. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204449\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</span></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-25 22:54:53', created_at: '2014-02-25 22:51:33', )
Comment.create(id: '1476', tool_id: '268', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>Parser 1.0 was a text analysis program for IBM PC or compatibles running a minimum of DOS 2.1 (Francis 406). It was developed by Prospero Software, based in London, England (Francis 409).</p> <p>According to Alexander L. Francis, who reviewed Parser 1.0 for the journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> in 1993,</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\"><em>Parser 1.0</em> is designed to take in an arbitrarily large ASCII text file and generate a \"verticalized\" output file containing the words in the text in a variety of different orders, each word paired with one of the 104 \"part-of-speech\" tags that have been taken into account by the program\'s authors. (Francis 406)</p> <p>Francis found the installation straightforward for experienced DOS users, and the step-by-step instructions provided for less experienced users simple to follow (406). He was also pleased with the program\'s design and supporting documentation:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">The excellent instructions make <em>Parser</em> extremely easy to use in its most basic mode. The 63 page documentation booklet is well written and informative, though I would have preferred a little more information about the precise method of analysis used by <em>Parser</em>. (406)</p> <p>The program\'s parsing function was fast, done in seconds for files of 500 words or less, though Francis noted that he did not test Parser with larger files (406). Its output was in the form of an ASCII file that could be processed further with Parser\'s REPORT.EXE package (406). The raw output was \"alphabetically ordered by tag within each sentence, and alphabetically by word within each category of tag\" (Francis 408). Parser also included a batch processing capacity for automating the parsing and output file generation for a sequence of files (Francis 406).</p> <p>Francis had just one complaint about the program, pertaining to its part-of-speech tagging: that it seemed to rely on heavily on the built-in lexicon, and therefore could not provide alternate tags for the user to choose the most appropriate from (Francis 407).</p> <p>Overall, he judged Parser to be useful and effective for word frequency analysis and general parsing, though he recommended testing the program with a subset of one\'s corpus before taking its results at face value (Francis 408).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source</strong></p> <p><span>Francis, Alexander L. \"Technical Review: Parser 1.0: An Elementary Parsing Program for the DOS Environment.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 27.5-6 (1993): 406-409. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204567\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</span></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-25 22:57:08', created_at: '2014-02-25 22:56:01', )
Comment.create(id: '1477', tool_id: '271', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p><strong>Program Overview</strong></p> <p>Morfogen, Morffile/Morfword and Inflword were a package set of interrelated tools for morphological analysis (Kim 133). This package was available from Executive Communication Systems, Inc. in Utah, USA, and ran on IBM PCs and compatibles with 640K of RAM and 1MB of free hard drive space (133).</p> <p>It could perform numerous morphological processes \"from simple prefixation and suffixation to circumfixation, (de)gemination, context sensitive rules and intercalating morphology common in Semitic languages\" (133).</p> <p>Kyunghwan Kim reviewed this package for the journal <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> in 1993. He described Morfogen as \"a finite state compiler for morphological analysis. Rules compiled by <em>Morfogen</em> are used with <em>Morffile</em> and <em>Morfword</em>\" (133). Morffile conducted a search and replace on the user\'s text, replacing words with their stems (133). Users could also have Morffile include the names of morphemes with the stem forms (133). Rather than just segmenting words (\"horse + s\"), the Morrfile/Morfword components represented words plus their morphological features as \"horse + plural\" (133).</p> <p>Morfword generated stem forms and morpheme names for single words typed directly into the user interface (133). The fourth program in the set, Inflword, took user input and produced inflected words by applying a compiled finite state machine generated by a related program called Inflogen (133).</p> <p>Kim had one major complaint about Morfogen et al:</p> <p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">It would be more convenient for users if the software allowed them to change options, edit input files and reload the files within the program. Another possible improvement would be to have a logging mechanism which writes to a disk file the information displayed on the screen during the execution of <em>Morfword</em> and <em>Inflword</em>. (Kim 135)</p> <p>The set included a user manual that covers all four programs, the programs on a 5.25in and a 3.5in disk, and dictionaries and rule files for English, French and Turkish, with additional languages available from the publisher (133).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Source </strong></p> <p><span>Kyunghwan, Kim. \"Technical Review: Morfogen, Morffile/Morfword, Inflword, Version 2.0.\" <em>Computers and the Humanities</em> 27.2 (1993): 133-135. <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/30204485\" target=\"_blank\">Web</a>.</span></p>', updated_at: '2014-02-25 22:59:22', created_at: '2014-02-25 22:58:30', )
Comment.create(id: '1478', tool_id: '391', user_id: '9', is_pinned: '1', is_hidden: '0', index: '0', content: '<p>Many thanks to Dr. Stephen Reimer, who provided a copy of LitStats, its documentation, and a bibliography of publications referencing the tool to TAPoR.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>LitStats was reviewed in the following:</p> <p>LitStats, version 1.62.&nbsp; Reviewed by Estelle Irizarry.&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 25.6 (Dec. 1991): 455-458.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>For more information on LitStats and its applications, please see the following:</p> <p>Schmidhuber, Guillermo.&nbsp; &ldquo;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">La segunda Celestina</span>: Sor Juana y la Estilometr&iacute;a.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Vuelta</span> 174 (May 1991): 54-60.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;Some Approaches to Computer Analysis of Dialogue in Theatre: Buero Vallejo&rsquo;s <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">En la ardiente oscuridad</span>.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 25 (1991): 15-25.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;Stylistic Analysis of a Corpus of Twentieth-Century Spanish Narrative.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 24 (1990): 265-274.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;Literary Analysis and the Microcomputer.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Hispania</span> 71.4 (Dec. 1988): 984-995.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;Some Approaches to Computer Analysis of Dialogue in Theatre: Buero Vallejo&rsquo;s <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">En la ardiente oscuridad</span>.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 25 (1991): 15-25.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;A Computer-Assisted Investigation of Gender-Related Idiolect in Octavio Paz and Rosario Castellanos.&rdquo; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 26 (1992): 103-117.</p> <p>Raschio, Richard A., and Ren&eacute;e Milstein.&nbsp; &ldquo;Bibliografia anotada de logicales, video discos y discos compactos para la ense&ntilde;anza del espa&ntilde;ol o para usa en cursos biling&uuml;es.&rdquo;&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Hispania</span> 76 (1993): 683-720.</p> <p>Irizarry, Estelle.&nbsp; &ldquo;The Two Authors of Columbus&rsquo; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Diary</span>.&rdquo; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Computers and the Humanities</span> 27 (1993): 85-92.</p> <p>Instituto Cervantes.&nbsp; <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Cat&aacute;logo de materiales inform&aacute;ticos para el aprendizaje del espa&ntilde;ol como lengua extranjera</span>.&nbsp; Madrid: DORSL, 1997.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>', updated_at: '2014-02-27 23:32:19', created_at: '2014-02-27 23:26:55', )
